<HEAD>Federal Auditors Searching For $7 Million in Denver HUD Probe</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 More than $ 7 million in proceeds from the sale of foreclosed homes may be missing from the <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Housing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Urban </ORGANIZATION> and Development's regional office here, federal auditors say. However, <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION>'s regional chief said the files that will account for the money are simply in storage and are being recovered. The <LOCATION> Denver </LOCATION> <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION> office is a major focus of a nationwide inquiry of wrongdoing at <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION> during the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration under then-Secretary <PERSON> Samuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Pierce </PERSON>. The agency has been rocked by allegations that money to rehabilitate run-down housing for the poor and elderly was handed out to developers who hired high-priced consultants with ties to the <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> or the administration. In addition, an escrow agent in <LOCATION> Maryland </LOCATION> has said she embezzled $ 5 million in money due the government from the sale of foreclosed property and gave most of the proceeds to the poor. Investigators have dubbed <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> <PERSON> Louise </PERSON> <PERSON> Harrell </PERSON> `` Robin <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION>.'' An auditor's report released Tuesday raised the possibility that the <LOCATION> Denver </LOCATION> office may not have received $ 7,279,136. Federal auditors have given the office eight days to come up with the missing records on 173 foreclosed homes sold in the past five years, or face sanctions. <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION> regional officials knew the files were missing as early as Feb. 9, according to the report by the <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION> inspector general's office The report indicates the investigation into single-family home sales handled by the office began in January. The report said 471 home sales were chosen by auditors for review, but records on 173 could n't be found. According to the report, documentation that proceeds were transferred to <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION> bank accounts was lacking for many other sales. <PERSON> Isaiah </PERSON> `` Ike'' <PERSON> Kelley </PERSON>, acting <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION> administrator in <LOCATION> Denver </LOCATION>, said the files, which have been missing since February, are stored in agency's archives. <PERSON> Kelley </PERSON> said the audit covered home sales from 1984 to 1988. `` I do n't know what happened back then, but I can tell you that as acting administrator I will make sure the regional inspector general obtains those files immediately,'' said <PERSON> Kelley </PERSON>, who took over in April. Earlier this month, a <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION> accountant in <LOCATION> Denver </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Douglas </PERSON> <PERSON> Turner </PERSON>, was suspended on suspicion of diverting $ 1 million to his own account. The auditors' report accused regional officials of lax record-keeping. Auditors complained they found active and inactive files together and that boxes of records were allowed to sit open at the regional office for indefinite periods before being put in storage. The report also criticized the practice of not requiring private agents who sell foreclosed properties for <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION> to confirm that proceeds were deposited in <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION> bank accounts. Normally when a <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION> home is sold, the proceeds are wired immediately to the agency's <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> office `` Of the 256 sales packages examined, 145 did not have wire transfer confirmations,'' the report said.
