<HEAD>Two Blacks Win Judicial Races in Court-Ordered Mississippi Election</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 10 grafs to UPDATE with two blacks winning, other
results; picks up 8th graf, `In 1987...'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JACKSON, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Two black candidates won races for judgeships Tuesday in an election ordered by a federal judge who said <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION>'s judicial districts discriminated against blacks. One other black candidate was narrowly leading, one was trailing and two others lost election bids. Two blacks were unopposed as a result of the court order that forced the redrawing of judicial districts. Prior to the election, <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> had four black judges. Also on the ballot were three proposed constitutional amendments to repeal outdated and unused provisions. One would eliminate the poll tax, adopted to discourage black voting but struck down by the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> in 1966. The four blacks among <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION>'s 78 judges are <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> Justice <PERSON> Reuben </PERSON> <PERSON> Anderson </PERSON>, Circuit Judges <PERSON> Fred </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Banks </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON> and <PERSON> Lillie </PERSON> <PERSON> Blackmon-Sanders </PERSON> and Chancery Judge <PERSON> Isaac </PERSON> <PERSON> Byrd </PERSON>. Each was appointed to fill a vacancy, but <PERSON> Anderson </PERSON> went on to win a full eight-year term in 1986. <PERSON> Byrd </PERSON> did not seek election this year. The two others sought regular terms Tuesday. With 79 of 85 precincts reporting Tuesday night, <ORGANIZATION> Blackmon-Sanders </ORGANIZATION> trailed <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> challenger <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Watson </PERSON> by 8,265 votes to 10,917. Banks and one other black Democrat, <PERSON> Isadore </PERSON> <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Patrick </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Vicksburg </LOCATION>, were unopposed in the general election. The two black winners were <PERSON> Pat </PERSON> <PERSON> Wise </PERSON>, a Democrat, who defeated Republican <PERSON> Billy </PERSON> <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Keyes </PERSON> for an open <LOCATION> Hinds </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> chancery judge's post by 5,942 votes to 1,638; and <PERSON> Denise </PERSON> <PERSON> Sweet </PERSON> <PERSON> Owens </PERSON>, also Democrat, who defeated Republican <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Arthur </PERSON> in another open family court post in the county, 4,628 votes to 1,259 With only five of 37 precincts reporting in the Fourth District, <PERSON> Solomon </PERSON> <PERSON> Curtis </PERSON> <PERSON> Osborne </PERSON>, a black Democrat, was leading independent incumbent Circuit Judge <PERSON> Gray </PERSON> <PERSON> Evans </PERSON> in the Fourth District, 395 votes to 348. But <PERSON> Clell </PERSON> <PERSON> G. </PERSON> <PERSON> Ward </PERSON>, a black Democrat, was defeated by independent incumbent Circuit Judge <PERSON> Howard </PERSON> <PERSON> Q. </PERSON> <PERSON> Davis </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON> in the Fourth District, 4,046 votes to 2,063. Another black candidate, <PERSON> Harold </PERSON> <PERSON> Brittain </PERSON>, also a Democrat, ran fourth in a four-way race for two judgeship posts in the 20 Circuit Court District. The winners were incumbents <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Goza </PERSON>, a Democrat, and <PERSON> Alfred </PERSON> <PERSON> Nichols </PERSON>, a Republican. In 1987, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Barbour </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON> ruled that the state's judicial districts discriminated against blacks. The ruling, the first to apply the 1965 Voting Rights Act to judicial elections, was upheld on appeal. <PERSON> Barbour </PERSON> ordered some districts redrawn to create minority subdistricts so that black voters would have a better opportunity to elect black judges. The ruling and appeals put judicial elections in the state on hold until this year, when all 69 <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Chancery </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> judgeships are being filled. No Supreme Court judgeships are on the ballot.
