<HEAD>Ascot Race Goers Collapse Under Sweltering Sun</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Fashionably dressed race goers at the opening of the four-day <PERSON> Royal </PERSON> <PERSON> Ascot </PERSON> meet sweltered in 88-degree heat and more than 50 collapsed, first-aid workers reported. `` We've been very, very busy,'' said <PERSON> Patricia </PERSON> <PERSON> Gates </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> St. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> John </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ambulance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Brigade </ORGANIZATION>'s volunteer corps. She said most of the victims on Tuesday suffered mild sunstroke or fainted. It was the hottest June day in 13 years and the champagne stalls were busy. The price of a bottle ranged from $ 33 to $ 70. Half a cold lobster cost $ 15.50, a serving of salmon $ 12.40 and strawberries and clotted cream $ 3.10. Queen <PERSON> Elizabeth </PERSON> <PERSON> II </PERSON>, in a pink and turquoise silk-crepe dress and straw hat, strolled through the crowds between the royal enclosure where the elegant parade and the paddock where the horses are paraded. Rules barring anyone under age 16 from the royal enclosure until Friday, the closing day, were broken to admit the queen's 8-year-old granddaughter, <PERSON> Zara </PERSON> <PERSON> Phillips </PERSON>, the daughter of Princess <PERSON> Anne </PERSON>. `` After all, the queen makes the rules,'' said a member of the royal household. A spokesman for the <ORGANIZATION> Ascot </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Authority </ORGANIZATION> noted <PERSON> Ascot </PERSON> is the monarch's racecourse. Prince <PERSON> Charles </PERSON>, the heir to the throne, left <PERSON> Ascot </PERSON> early to play polo in nearby <LOCATION> Windsor </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Great </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Park </LOCATION>. Princess <PERSON> Diana </PERSON> went with him but left after the first match.
