<FIRST>r i PM-Palme-Press     06-21 0690</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Palme-Press,0716</SECOND>
<HEAD>Palme Trial Raises Questions About Unusual Swedish Press Ethics</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Also in Wednesday AMs report.</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHAN RAPP</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>STOCKHOLM, Sweden (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Swedes may not learn the name or see the face of the man accused of killing Prime Minister <PERSON> Olof </PERSON> <PERSON> Palme </PERSON> if they read only their national newspapers. <PERSON> Carl </PERSON> <PERSON> Gustaf </PERSON> <PERSON> Christer </PERSON> <PERSON> Pettersson </PERSON>, who is on trial for the 1986 shooting, is known in <LOCATION> Sweden </LOCATION> only as `` the 42-year-old.'' Under Swedish press law, the identity of a criminal suspect is never published unless he is convicted and sentenced, and even then it must clearly be in the public interest. The regulations are meant to protect the innocent, and a newspaper and its senior editor can be fined for violating them. But the Palme murder trial has put the regulations under a strain, and several provincial papers are disregarding them. `` <PERSON> Christer </PERSON> <PERSON> Pettersson </PERSON> is a historic person, whether guilty or not,'' said <PERSON> Per </PERSON> <PERSON> Ahlstrom </PERSON>, editor of Nya Norrland, a daily with a circulation of 20,000 in the northern town of <LOCATION> Harnosand </LOCATION>. `` I find that there is evident public interest that the name of the person accused of the murder becomes public knowledge,'' he said. International news agencies and foreign newspapers published <PERSON> Pettersson </PERSON>'s identity and his police mug shot when he was charged in December. Swedish papers ran into difficulty when <PERSON> Pettersson </PERSON>, known as `` the 41-year-old'' at the time, had a birthday in April. For a few weeks he was referred to as `` the 42-year-old former 41-year-old.'' About 20 newspapers have flouted the regulations, arguing it was ridiculous to try to hide his identity when foreign newspapers reporting the trial were available at major newsstands in <LOCATION> Sweden </LOCATION>. Other ironies also have become evident. Under Swedish freedom of information laws, <PERSON> Pettersson </PERSON>'s name was available after prosecutors filed the indictment last month. Anyone who calls the <ORGANIZATION> Stockholm </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> can ask the court clerk to read it over the telephone. Papers that have refrained from identifying <PERSON> Pettersson </PERSON> have, at the same time, published every detail of his life, including his police record, the location of his home and interviews with former girlfriends. <PERSON> Kevin </PERSON> <PERSON> Boyle </PERSON>, director of the London-based `` Article 19,'' which monitors press freedom in 50 countries, said the Swedish regulations are `` highly exceptional'' if not unique. `` It is remarkable in that it contradicts the openness of information in so many other areas where <LOCATION> Sweden </LOCATION> leads the world,'' <PERSON> Boyle </PERSON> said in an interview. He said the restrictions do not violate international law, but they could inhibit the search for witnesses. Because of high public interest in the Palme case, the court let <ORGANIZATION> Swedish </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Radio </ORGANIZATION> broadcast the trial with a one-second delay to allow a technician to cover <PERSON> Pettersson </PERSON>'s name with an electronic beep. The technician missed the beat the first time <PERSON> Pettersson </PERSON>'s name was mentioned, however. The broadcasts have been debated heatedly. Professor <PERSON> Carl </PERSON> <PERSON> Magnus </PERSON> <PERSON> Elwing </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lund </ORGANIZATION> said they have turned the trial into `` marketplace theater'' and diminished the stature of the court. `` I would have acted forcefully to stop it,'' <PERSON> Elwing </PERSON> said. Some critics said testimony heard on the radio could influence subsequent witnesses. Presiding Judge <PERSON> Carl-Anton </PERSON> <PERSON> Spak </PERSON> ruled the broadcasts were in line with the law and would be stopped only if they disturbed the trial itself. Since then most of the witnesses, many of whom have criminal records, have demanded that the broadcast be halted for their testimony and the court has complied. Press Ombudsman <PERSON> Torsten </PERSON> <PERSON> Cars </PERSON>, who is employed by the newspaper industry, said the caution regarding <PERSON> Pettersson </PERSON>'s name goes beyond the requirements of press ethics. `` It would not change much if the name were printed, considering all the descriptions of his life that already have been published,'' he said. `` And there are thousands of <PERSON> Christer </PERSON> <PERSON> Petterssons </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Sweden </LOCATION>. ... Publishing the picture is more serious.'' Among those publishing the name is the newspaper <ORGANIZATION> Arbetet </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Malmo </LOCATION>, a city across the <LOCATION> Oregrund </LOCATION> straits from <LOCATION> Denmark </LOCATION>, where such restrictions do not apply. <PERSON> Arbetet </PERSON> was convicted of libel in 1987 and ordered to pay $ 27,000 in compensation to `` the 33-year-old,'' a suspect who earlier was detained and released without charges.
</TEXT>
