<SECOND>AM-Tavern Strike,0182</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tavern on the Green Strike Settled</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Picket lines in the 7-week-old strike at <LOCATION> Central </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Park </LOCATION>'s posh restaurant, Tavern on the Green, came down Tuesday after striking workers tentatively accepted a five-year contract. `` We're delighted,'' said restaurant spokesman <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Scanlon </PERSON>. `` We think it's a fair settlement, we're glad that it's over and we want to see all of our regular customers back here as soon as possible.'' Under the offer, wages will increase 27 percent the first year and about 5 percent each of the four years that follow. `` A 27 percent raise the first year is not a bad wage increase,'' said <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Turchiano </PERSON>, a spokesman for Local 6 of the Hotel Employees and Restaurant Employees International Union. The union represented nearly 300 dishwashers, busboys, waiters and other workers who walked off the job April 30. The members are likely to ratify the contract when they vote on it Wednesday, <PERSON> Turchiano </PERSON> said. Tavern on the Green is a tourist mecca, known for its glittering garden, rococo decor and posh banquets.
