<HEAD>Grand Jury Refuses To Indict City Bus Driver In Slaying Of Passenger</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A <LOCATION> Dallas </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> grand jury on Tuesday declined to indict a city bus driver accused of killing a passenger by shooting him in the back after an argument. <PERSON> Chauncey </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Plummer </PERSON>, 37, a <LOCATION> Dallas </LOCATION> bus driver for 10 years, had been charged with murder in the May 24 shooting of <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Hayden </PERSON>, 25. <PERSON> Plummer </PERSON> picked up <PERSON> Hayden </PERSON> and a woman on a downtown street and told authorities that, through his rearview mirror, he saw the woman hand her bus pass to <PERSON> Hayden </PERSON>, who then tried to use it. The driver told <PERSON> Hayden </PERSON> he could not use the pass, an argument ensued and <PERSON> Plummer </PERSON> ordered <PERSON> Hayden </PERSON> off the bus, police records show. <PERSON> Hayden </PERSON> was shot once in the back with a handgun as he exited. <PERSON> Plummer </PERSON> told police that <PERSON> Hayden </PERSON> punched him in the jaw before he stepped off the bus. <PERSON> Plummer </PERSON> had been assaulted twice on the bus route in the past two years, once breaking his hand and the other time suffering a black eye, <ORGANIZATION> Dallas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Area </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rapid </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transit </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Ron </PERSON> <PERSON> Whittington </PERSON> said. DART authorities, meanwhile, have begun proceedings to dismiss <PERSON> Plummer </PERSON> for violating company policy, which forbids drivers from carrying firearms. A decision was expected by Friday.
