<HEAD>Democrats Failing to Highlight Family Issues, Consultant Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By W. DALE NELSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Democrats are failing to capitalize on family issues such as child care at the polls because they are `` afraid to take on the tax consequences'' of programs that voters say they support, a party consultant says. But a Republican strategist warned women's groups that even though child care has emerged as an important campaign issue in recent years, `` there are a lot of folks who just do n't care about the issue.'' <PERSON> Celinda </PERSON> <PERSON> Lake </PERSON>, a Democratic expert on electing women candidates, and <PERSON> Vince </PERSON> <PERSON> Breglio </PERSON>, a former campaign strategist for <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> Republicans before becoming President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s chief pollster for the 1988 campaign, appeared on a panel at a meeting held by child care advocates Tuesday. Panelist <PERSON> Ethel </PERSON> <PERSON> Klein </PERSON>, an associate professor of political science at <ORGANIZATION> Columbia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>, said a February poll by <ORGANIZATION> Louis </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Harris </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Associates </ORGANIZATION> showed 87 percent approval for a joint government and private effort to meet child care needs. She said 55 percent of those responding to a CBS News poll in February said the federal government had a responsibility to help parents pay for child care if they could n't afford it. <PERSON> Breglio </PERSON>, however, said the most recent White House polls show that <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s child care program, built around a tax credit, has about 5 percent to 6 percent more support than congressional legislation calling for direct government financing. Ms. <PERSON> Lake </PERSON> told the group that family issues `` ought to work very well for Democrats. They are policy issues where people want spending and they want it now, not later. They want government involvement.'' `` We as Democrats have not drawn strong enough political lines on this issue,'' the consultant said. `` Democrats have tended to talk about small cost ... and all this has done is lose the punch of these issues because we have been afraid to take on the tax consequences, the regulatory consequences, of these programs, and in fact voters think these issues are going to take big programs.'' <PERSON> Breglio </PERSON> said such family issues as child care first surfaced in political campaigns in 1986. `` I had candidates who were beaten on those kinds of issues,'' he said. `` They were beaten because, with my stupid advice, they talked about national themes and ideology. Well, national themes and ideology did n't sell in 1986. Concern over nuclear waste and child care did. We were wrong, they were right, and we lost many <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> seats.'' However, he cautioned the group, `` There are a lot of folks out there who feel strongly about it, but I must tell you this: there are a lot of folks who just do n't care.'' Both consultants agreed that family issues will have significant impact in next year's congressional elections. `` I do n't believe serious political candidates in 1990 can avoid discussing the issue of child care,'' <PERSON> Breglio </PERSON> said. `` I do n't believe they can avoid discussing the issue of long-term health care. However, he said he did not believe parental leave would be an issue. Ms. <PERSON> Lake </PERSON> predicted all three would be major issues, particularly if <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> passes child care and parental leave legislation and <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> vetoes it on top of his veto of the recent bill raising the minimum wage. <PERSON> Breglio </PERSON> said <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> is `` doing pretty well'' with women voters, but `` If there is a whole series of vetoes on legislation that is of particular importance to women, that could be a different ballgame.'' The panel was sponsored by the <ORGANIZATION> Child </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Care </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Action </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Campaign </ORGANIZATION>, a coalition seeking a national system of child care combining public and private resources; the Great American Family Tour, a non-profit, non-partisan organization dealing with family policy issues, headed by Rep. <PERSON> Patricia </PERSON> <PERSON> Schroeder </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Colo </LOCATION>.; and <ORGANIZATION> Lifetime </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Television </ORGANIZATION>, a venture of <ORGANIZATION> Hearst </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> @ </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> ABC-Viacom </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Entertainment </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION>, which produce a documentary entitled `` Hush Little Baby: The Challenge of Child Care.
