final appeal. Picks up 4th graf pvs.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JACK ELLIOTT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARCHMAN, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Leo </PERSON> <PERSON> Edwards </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, a black man whose conviction by an all-white jury provoked cries of racism by his attorneys, was put to death in <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION>'s gas chamber early Wednesday. <PERSON> Edwards </PERSON>, 36, convicted of murdering a convenience store clerk during a 1980 crime spree, lost two appeals just hours before the execution. He was pronounced dead at 12:15 a.m. at the <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> State Penitentiary here. The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>, by a 7-2 vote, had denied <PERSON> Edwards </PERSON>' request for a stay Tuesday. Earlier Tuesday, the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> halted the execution of a <LOCATION> Missouri </LOCATION> man convicted of killing an elderly couple. Shortly after that, a federal judge in <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Louis </LOCATION> granted a stay of execution for his accomplice. <PERSON> Leonard </PERSON> <PERSON> Laws </PERSON>, 39, and <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Gilmore </PERSON>, 42, had been scheduled to die early Wednesday morning. The high court's ruling in the <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> case was followed two hours later by a statement from Gov. <PERSON> Ray </PERSON> <PERSON> Mabus </PERSON> saying he refused to grant clemency for <PERSON> Edwards </PERSON>. `` I have reviewed the facts in the case of <PERSON> Leo </PERSON> <PERSON> Edwards </PERSON>, and I will not stand in the way of the court's justice,'' the governor said. `` The facts are that <PERSON> Leo </PERSON> <PERSON> Edwards </PERSON> is a mass murderer who killed in cold blood, he tried and failed to get relief in 16 appeals to the courts, and discrimination had no bearing on his case. `` This is not casual justice. <PERSON> Leo </PERSON> <PERSON> Edwards </PERSON>' sentence is a result of his own crime, and his fate now rests in God's hands,'' the governor said. <PERSON> Edwards </PERSON>, 36, of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Orleans </LOCATION>, was convicted on April 1, 1981 in the death of <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> convenience store clerk <PERSON> Linzy </PERSON> <PERSON> Don </PERSON> <PERSON> Dixon </PERSON> during a robbery. The robbery and killing were committed after <PERSON> Edwards </PERSON> escaped from a <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION> prison. <PERSON> Edwards </PERSON> and co-defendant <PERSON> Mike </PERSON> <PERSON> White </PERSON> went on a five-day robbery spree that left three store clerks dead and two wounded in Hinds and <LOCATION> Madison </LOCATION> counties. White pleaded guilty to murder in <PERSON> Dixon </PERSON>'s death and the slaying of bar owner <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> <PERSON> Ardis </PERSON> <PERSON> Newsome </PERSON>. White got two life terms. <PERSON> Edwards </PERSON> was sentenced to life in <PERSON> Newsome </PERSON>'s killing. <PERSON> Edwards </PERSON> was within less than 14 hours of a trip to the gas chamber on Oct. 25, 1988, when the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> stopped the scheduled execution. <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> has executed three men since the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> reinstituted the death penalty in 1976. <PERSON> Jimmy </PERSON> <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> <PERSON> Gray </PERSON> was executed in 1983, and <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> Earl </PERSON> <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON> and <PERSON> Connie </PERSON> <PERSON> Ray </PERSON> <PERSON> Evans </PERSON> went to the gas chamber in 1987.
