<HEAD>Plan to Revamp Tax Penalties Aims at Willful Non-payers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM LUTHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Tax Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A bill endorsed by the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ways </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Means </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> tries to draw a distinction between careless taxpayers and those who are out to beat the system. Taxpayers also would face less chance of being penalized two or more times for the same mistake, under the measure passed by a voice vote Tuesday. The bill would revamp the system of nearly 150 civil tax penalties that may be imposed by the <ORGANIZATION> Internal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Revenue </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>, and is intended to be part of the committee's share of deficit reduction for the budget year that begins Oct. 1. Rep. <PERSON> J.J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Pickle </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Texas </LOCATION>, chairman of the committee's oversight panel and chief author of the overhaul, said public hearings showed `` the current penalty structure is a confusing morass of complex, overlapping penalties that are often unduly harsh or just plain irrational.'' Just 35 years ago, the <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION> had only 13 penalties to enforce. The growth is partly due to <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>' use of penalties to raise revenue, authorities say. In 1988, the <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION> assessed 26 million penalties totaling nearly $ 6 billion. The <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION> supports overhauling the penalty structure. The rewriting is based on the notion that penalties should be used only to encourage compliance, not to raise money. An example of the changes: Present law imposes a 5 percent penalty for underpayment of tax; the bill would raise that generally to 20 percent. Most of the changes involve penalties on banks and other payers that fail to file reports on interest and dividends paid, and on employers that miss the deadline for turning over withheld taxes to the <ORGANIZATION> Internal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Revenue </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>. In most cases, the revised penalties would be graduated so that the longer the delay in paying or filing and the more blatant the mistake, the higher the penalty. For example, the penalty for failing to file an information return with the <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION> _ such as a Form 1099 statement, on which a bank reports interest paid to a depositor _ now is $ 50 for each failure to file. The maximum is $ 100,000 a year. The bill would vary that from $ 15 for a few days' tardiness -LRB- a maximum of $ 75,000 a year -RRB- to $ 50 per failure, to a maximum of $ 250,000.
