n the dance floor. `` I suddenly burst out,'' she said. `` My body just let go, and he told me it was good. Dancing really helped me to open up, and it became easier to use that freedom to speak.'' At 15, she won favorable notice in <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> for a dance recital by her high school troupe at a <LOCATION> Manhattan </LOCATION> theater. She won scholarships to study at the Joffrey Ballet and the <PERSON> Martha </PERSON> <PERSON> Graham </PERSON> School of Contemporary Dance. This summer, she studied on scholarship with the Dance Theater of <LOCATION> Harlem </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Sandra </PERSON> has pursued her dream without apparent support from her mother, who moved to <LOCATION> Brooklyn </LOCATION> from <LOCATION> Haiti </LOCATION> with <PERSON> Sandra </PERSON>'s brother and sister in 1986. `` My family has never seen me dance,'' she said. `` My mother does n't like it because she says you ca n't earn a good living at dancing.'' But <PERSON> Thompson </PERSON> is convinced that <PERSON> Sandra </PERSON> will prevail because of her natural talent. `` Her growth in the last four years has been phenomenal,'' he said.
