<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> rattles off his address as `` <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Avenue </LOCATION>, 1600,'' but do n't count on finding him there if you visit the nation's capital this summer. From Memorial Day to Labor Day, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> will have spent more days away from the White House than in it. If <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> were required to report to <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> on what he did over the summer, it would fill a substantial volume. Between lengthy trips to <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> has been bounding about the country, giving a string of often disjointed speeches and conducting the nation's business on the road. Some critics have questioned whether <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, in his multitudinous travels, has been logging useful mileage or merely spinning the adminstration's wheels. In the three weeks since he returned from a four-nation, weeklong trip to <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> centered on a <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> meeting in <LOCATION> Brussels </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>: _ Made a 4,000-mile, 30-hour round trip to Yellowstone National Park, <LOCATION> Wyoming </LOCATION>'s Grand Tetons, and <PERSON> Lincoln </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Neb. </LOCATION>, nominally to tout his environmental programs However, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s late-day visit to Yellowstone consisted of a tour of an area damaged by last year's forest fires, and was unrelated to the chief topic of the day _ the <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>'s new clean-air legislation _ Visited a federal law enforcement training center at <LOCATION> Glynco </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ga. </LOCATION>, to talk about his anti-crime package The speech spotlighted a plan whose details had been announced several weeks before. _ Flew by helicopter to the <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION> suburbs, where he gave a high school graduation speech and shook hands with all 331 graduates In addition, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> planned to travel today to <LOCATION> Richmond </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Va. </LOCATION>, where he was to speak at a motor coach exhibit at the <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION> State Fairgrounds and attend a Republican fund-raiser. On Thursday, he travels to <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, both for a fund-raiser and to unveil details of a youth service program. He caps next week with a visit to his family home in <LOCATION> Kennebunkport </LOCATION> for a five-day Fourth of July holiday, then goes to <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> for the seven-nation economic summit and side visits to <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Netherlands </LOCATION>. In August, he plans a 2 -LCB- - week vacation in <LOCATION> Kennebunkport </LOCATION> And he's been spending most weeekends not otherwise accounted for at the presidential retreat in Camp David, Md <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> has been doing some business as he moves around the country. He vetoed the minium wage bill aboard <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> One as he traveled from <LOCATION> Montana </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Nebraska </LOCATION> last week; in <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION>, he signed a routine message formally transmitting his crime package to <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>. `` Usually, this would entail nothing more than a quick flourish of the pen and then sending an aide on a 10-minute car ride up from <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Avenue </LOCATION>, 1600, on up to <LOCATION> Capitol </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hill </LOCATION>,'' he told his law-enforcement audience. `` But when it comes to fighting crime, you deserve more than just business as usual.'' However, even in talking about crime _ a favored subject _ <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> seemed to be sending a mixed message. After a tough speech in which <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> declared, `` let's put the handcuffs on the criminals, not on the criminal justice system,'' he was asked by a <ORGANIZATION> Border </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Patrol </ORGANIZATION> rookie for `` some words of wisdom when we enter the field.'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>: `` You'll find that you and your colleagues will be severely impacted by the battle against narcotics. Word of wisdom would be: an individual should be treated with respect and given his rights, or her rights, even though the evidence looks overwhelming. ... I think we have to be tolerant.'' The press contingent following <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> as he hops from city to city has grown increasingly more sparse. For the trip to <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> canceled travel arrangements for the regular White House press corps, beyond taking a small `` pool.'' It cited lack of interest among news organizations. `` I'm not going to be a policeman or try to guide your coverage habits. It's as simple as that,'' fumed presidential press secretary <PERSON> Marlin </PERSON> <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON>.
