<HEAD>Thornburgh Plan Would Wreck Crime-Fighting Team, Former Leaders Say</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Attorney General <PERSON> Dick </PERSON> <PERSON> Thornburgh </PERSON>'s plan to place the nation's elite corps of organized crime-fighting prosecutors under control of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> attorneys is coming under fire from former leaders of the unit. `` It's impractical, it just wo n't work,'' <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION> attorney <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Vaira </PERSON> said Tuesday at a hearing of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> subcommittee on criminal justice. Under <PERSON> Thornburgh </PERSON>'s plan, prosecutors who are members of the 20-year-old <ORGANIZATION> Organized </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Crime </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Strike </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> would no longer report to the <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>'s criminal division. Instead, they would be controlled by the politically appointed <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> attorneys in the cities were they are based. <PERSON> Thornburgh </PERSON> says the idea would end turf battles between the strike force and the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> attorneys. His critics say the elite force, which has chalked up impressive victories in the war against the mob, would soon vanish. `` I guarantee you three years from now it will take the <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> to find the strike forces,'' said <PERSON> Vaira </PERSON>, a former strike force chief in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Phildelphia </LOCATION> who also was <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> attorney in <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION> and briefly headed the President's Commission on Organized Crime. <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> McDonald </PERSON>, former head of the strike force in <LOCATION> Brooklyn </LOCATION>, was sharply critical of what <PERSON> Thornburgh </PERSON> and his aides `` call euphemistically the merger of the strike force. I like to call it the destruction or the abolition of the strike force.'' The plan already has sent strike force attorneys in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> hunting for new jobs, he said, adding that the departure of highly experienced prosecutors is likely to grow worse. Lawmakers are considering a move to bar <PERSON> Thornburgh </PERSON> from implementing the plan until Oct. 1 as part of a stopgap spending bill likely to go to President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> and gain his signature. But the move could go forward after that. Former <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> strike force chief <PERSON> Jeremiah </PERSON> <PERSON> T. </PERSON> <PERSON> O'Sullivan </PERSON> testified that strike force attorneys often are paid $ 7,000 to $ 10,000 less than <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> attorneys, even though they usually have more experience. Because of salary adjustments, <PERSON> Thornburgh </PERSON>'s plan would cost $ 100,000 in each city where the strike force is located, <PERSON> O'Sullivan </PERSON> testified. `` You'd be looking at an increase of $ 1 million right off the bat'' nationwide, he said. `` After all these victories, I think it is fair to ask: What is broke that needs fixing?'' said subcommittee Chairman <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Schumer </PERSON>, D-N. He said, however, that he would keep an open mind on the issue. <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> S.G. </PERSON> <PERSON> Dennis </PERSON>, head of the criminal division of the <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>, told the panel that <PERSON> Thornburgh </PERSON>'s `` concern for the fight against organized crime is second to none.'' <PERSON> Thornburgh </PERSON> `` feels strongly enough about this proposal that he is willing to take the heat and the controversy that this proposal stimulates,'' <PERSON> Dennis </PERSON> said. He said the idea of merging the strike forces in each city with the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> attorney's office was one that would promote `` even more harmony'' between the two groups of prosecutors and end `` turf fights.'' <PERSON> Dennis </PERSON> took issue with claims that the plan would mean the end of the strike force, saying its members would not be reassigned to work on cases not involving organized crime. He said turf fighting between strike force attorneys and the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> attorneys offices has at times cut into time that should be spent on fighting mobsters. `` The question is, are we going to spend 30 percent of our time arguing whose case this is, or are we going to make the case?'' <PERSON> Dennis </PERSON> said.
