<SECOND>PM-Tampon Labeling,370</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tampon-Labeling Proposal too Confusing, Says Consumer Group</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH MESCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A government proposal aimed at helping women minimize the risk of toxic shock syndrome is too confusing, a consumer group says, because it would allow tampon boxes to show two types of absorbency ratings. <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Food </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Drug </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION>'s revised plan would require manufacturers to display one of six new standardized absorbency rating terms ranging from low to high. However, they also could continue using traditional designations like regular and super. `` This whole range system is n't as informative and clear as it could be,'' said <PERSON> Patti </PERSON> <PERSON> Goldman </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Citizen </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION>. The proposal is an improvement over <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION>'s earlier plan to use an absorbency scale of letters from A to F, `` but there's still potential for confusion to have the old terms appear nearby,'' she said. The <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION> said Tuesday it revised its earlier proposal in response to about 275 comments from consumers, consumer groups and manufacturers, many of whom complained that it was too confusing. The labeling is designed to help women select the lowest absorbency tampon they need to reduce the risk of toxic shock syndrome, which has been associated with tampon use. Toxic shock syndrome is rare, but sometimes fatal. Under the new plan, tampon absorbency would be rated as low, medium, medium-high, high, very high and highest _ according to the number of grams the tampon was designed to absorb. Tampon boxes also would have to carry labels advising women to select the lowest absorbency needed to minimize risk of toxic shock syndrome. Regulations have required this warning since 1982 but allow it to appear on a package insert. Package inserts also must list toxic shock syndrome's symptoms: sudden fever, vomiting, diarrhea, fainting or nearly fainting when standing up, dizziness and a sunburn-like rash. The <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION> has been trying since 1981 to convince manufacturers to voluntarily label their products with a standardized absorbency rating so women could compare brand-to-brand. The agency gave up that route in 1984 and began regulatory efforts. The <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION> invited public comments on the new proposal until Aug. 11.
</TEXT>
