<HEAD>Utility Boosted Security to Stem Potential Nuclear Sabotage</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BURNS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Authorities took extra precautions against potential sabotage by workers at the <LOCATION> Rancho </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Seco </LOCATION> nuclear power station near <LOCATION> Sacramento </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>, after city residents voted to close the troubled plant, officials disclosed. The only incident since the June 6 vote was resolved safely, but federal regulators said Tuesday they're keeping a close eye on plant conditions as the <ORGANIZATION> Sacramento </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Municipal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Utility </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> gradually switches off the reactor with a shrinking work force. `` It's not what you'd call an unsafe situation,'' but the unusual circumstances of the plant shutdown have prompted extra caution, said <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Murley </PERSON>, director of the <ORGANIZATION> Nuclear </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Regulatory </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>'s office of reactor regulation The vote marked the first time citizens have decided to close an operating reactor, but analysts say it seems unlikely the move will trigger other closures soon. Still, the shutdown is a blow to an industry already hampered by widespread public concerns about the safety and reliability of nuclear power. Rancho Seco has a spotty record, producing less than 40 percent of the electricity that would have resulted from unfailing year-round operation _ far below the industry average. The utility district had to double its rates over the past four years to pay for plant improvements that cost more than the reactor itself. <PERSON> Murley </PERSON> said plant executives gave him explicit assurances that the shutdown would go smoothly, and he said that so far there was no evidence to the contrary. `` It's a very tough period because all the good people will be looking for other jobs,'' <PERSON> Murley </PERSON> said, adding that there also was a danger of `` bad reactions'' by plant workers to being forced out of the 15-year-old nuclear station. The utility district's senior nuclear executive, <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Firlit </PERSON>, has resigned, and about 1,000 regular plant workers were expected to leave by month's end. The <ORGANIZATION> NRC </ORGANIZATION>, which is responsible for ensuring safety at the nation's 110 nuclear reactors, boosted its usual complement of three resident inspectors at <LOCATION> Rancho </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Seco </LOCATION> by three or four for several days before and after the election, <PERSON> Greg </PERSON> <PERSON> Cook </PERSON>, a spokesman at the commision's regional office in <LOCATION> Walnut </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Creek </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>, said <PERSON> Cook </PERSON> said extra security inspectors also were sent to the site to provide around-the-clock surveillance. The <ORGANIZATION> NRC </ORGANIZATION> has returned to normal levels of supervision at the plant, he said. The utility increased its security at the site but has since trimmed it back, said spokesman <PERSON> Bert </PERSON> <PERSON> Heffner </PERSON>. He said he was not sure of all the reasons for the added protection but that a rush of news reporters to the plant was one. <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> Smeloff </PERSON>, a member of the utility district's board, said in an interview that utility security personnel were added as a general precaution against possible worker backlash and because of a a specific incident with one disgruntled employee. An offduty reactor operator, angered at the prospect of losing his job, telephoned the plant the day after the election to say `` he would not shut it down if so ordered,'' said <PERSON> Smeloff </PERSON>. <PERSON> Heffner </PERSON> said the incident did not constitute a threat to security, but the worker's access to the plant was suspended. He said no decision has been made on possible disciplinary action against the man, whose name was not disclosed. Dean Kunihiro, an official at the <ORGANIZATION> NRC </ORGANIZATION>'s <LOCATION> Walnut </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Creek </LOCATION> office, said that while `` it's kind of business as usual'' again at <LOCATION> Rancho </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Seco </LOCATION>, the commission is still watchful because a serious accident involving radioactive release is still possible even though the reactor is no longer sustaining a chain reaction. The plant owner is planning to remove the fuel rods from the reactor vessel in August but has not yet decided whether it will continue with the lengthy process of dismantling the plant or try to sell it to another potential operator.
