<HEAD>Amid Strained Relations, Chinese Art Exhibition On Schedule</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-US-China Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GENE KRAMER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A Chinese government-sponsored art show was launched for year-long showings in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> on schedule and without incident _ but also without official <LOCATION> Chinese </LOCATION> representation. <PERSON> Wang </PERSON> <PERSON> Yani </PERSON>, a 14-year-old prodigy who has made 10,000 brush-and-ink paintings since she was 3 years old, was the undisputed star at the preview of her exhibition of 69 colorful pictures. In a demonstration lasting barely an hour, she created a 70th painting, dashing barefoot, brush in hand, from end to end of a 3-by 6-foot parchment laid on a floor. Her works show monkeys, birds and other beasts displaying human emotions and expressions while cavorting through exquisitely drawn foliage and mountains of <PERSON> Yani </PERSON>'s rugged native <LOCATION> Guangxi </LOCATION> province, in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>, far from the turmoil of <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Shanghai </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Culture </ORGANIZATION> is listed as sponsor of the exhibition but no one from the <ORGANIZATION> Chinese </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Embassy </ORGANIZATION> appeared at Tuesday's event, `` maybe because they were too busy,'' said <PERSON> Milo </PERSON> <PERSON> Beach </PERSON>, director of the <ORGANIZATION> Smithsonian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Insitution </ORGANIZATION>'s Sackler Gallery for Asian art At the very hour of the preview, <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> members critical of <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s violent crackdown against the pro-democracy movement rallied at the nearby <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Capitol grounds, then went to the <ORGANIZATION> Chinese </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Embassy </ORGANIZATION> to protest killings, violence and arrests in what they described as a confrontational meetin