<HEAD>Exports Rise Slightly in May Despite Protests</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-China, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The government today said exports rose slightly in May while imports soared, a situation reflecting <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s recent economic and political turmoil. According to customs authorities, <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> exported $ 4.43 billion of goods in May, up 0.8 percent over the same month in 1988. Imports were up 21.1 percent to $ 5.31 billion in the same period, the official <ORGANIZATION> Xinhua </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> reported today. The customs figures showed exports for the first five months of the year were up 4.7 percent to $ 18 billion, while imports jumped 24.4 percent to $ 22.67 billion _ a trade imbalance of $ 4.6 billion that was $ 3.8 billion more than the first five months of 1988. The report did not cite reasons for the worsening trade situation. However, the nation is suffering from increasingly serious shortages of raw materials and energy and has had to divert some important export items, such as coal and oil, to the domestic market while importing more raw materials for its processing industries. Politically, <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> was hit in May by the pro-democracy student demonstrations that disrupted some factory production and distracted the national leadership. The trade situation is expected to worsen in June, when the military killed hundreds of unarmed civilians in <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION>, triggering unrest throughout the nation.
