<HEAD>LaserPhoto CX3</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A 3-month-old boy with severe burns was the first beneficiary of <PERSON> Dennis </PERSON> <PERSON> Genz </PERSON>'s decision to donate 4 square feet of his excess skin to a hospital burn unit. Genz' diet recently allowed him to shed 170 pounds, but left him with a large flap of skin on his abdomen, which was removed surgically Monday. `` There have been rare cases where parents have donated skin for their children,'' <PERSON> Betty </PERSON> <PERSON> Perls </PERSON>, education director for the <ORGANIZATION> Regional </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organ </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Illinois </ORGANIZATION>, said Tuesday. `` But none of us have ever heard of a case like this.'' The 5-foot-11 Genz weighed 430 pounds last August when he began a high-protein weight-loss regimen. Last week, he weighed in at 260. He said the operation removed 19 -LCB- pounds of skin and adjoining tissue. Some of the skin went to <PERSON> Dexter </PERSON> <PERSON> Moore </PERSON>, a 3-month-old victim of a fire in <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION>. When the infant was admitted, he was suffering from smoke inhalation and burns to his face, head and arms. It was a life-threatening situation, said <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Easton </PERSON>, spokesman at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION>. Now, said <PERSON> Easton </PERSON>, `` he's doing well.'' More lives are saved by skin transplants than any other donated organ, said Dr. <PERSON> Lawrence </PERSON> <PERSON> Gottlieb </PERSON>, professor of surgery and director of the hospital's burn unit. Most donated skin comes from cadavers, Ms. <PERSON> Perls </PERSON> said. Donated skin `` is used as a kind of living bandage'' while the patient regenerates his own skin, Ms. <PERSON> Perls </PERSON> said. Then the bor