<TEXT>
 Brewery employees drove a jittery <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> veteran over the edge by making sudden loud noises so they could watch him throw himself to the floor, a panel ruled in awarding him $ 86,000 in worker's compensation. `` This is a case where the human insensitivity often witnessed in the children's schoolyard has reappeared in the adult workplace,'' two administrative law judges wrote in a decision in favor of <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Beverly </PERSON>, 42, of <LOCATION> Waterloo </LOCATION>. `` Such callous behavior is not merely reprehensible, but a disgrace.'' Co-workers at <ORGANIZATION> Miller </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Brewing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> learned he had been diagnosed as suffering from post-traumatic stress disorder, including an exaggerated startle reaction, and `` preyed upon this startle reaction apparently for amusement or perhaps outright cruelty,'' said Judges <PERSON> Randall </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kaiser </PERSON> and <PERSON> Nancy </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Schneiders </PERSON>. From 1981 to 1983, co-workers dropped tables, broke beer bottles, dropped heavy equipment from forklifts, popped empty milk cartons and paper cups and set off fireworks. <PERSON> Beverly </PERSON> responded with a flash of fear and an increased heart rate and jumped or threw himself to the floor. A rocket set off in the lunchroom in <PERSON> Beverly </PERSON>'s direction so unnerved him that he was hospitalized for seven months for psychiatric treatment, the judges said last week. <PERSON> Beverly </PERSON>, who left his job as a production worker in 1983 and never returned, suffers chronic anxiety, distrust of other people, depression, anxiety attacks and nightmares, the judges found. <PERSON> Miller </PERSON> and its insurance companies said the harassment or horseplay was not directed at <LOCATION> Beverly </LOCATION>, or if it was, it was not unusual st