s fears concerning the handicapped can not be used to block the development of group homes,'' <PERSON> Turner </PERSON> said in the statement from <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. The lawsuit asks the federal court in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> to bar <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Heights </LOCATION> from interfering with construction of the home and to assess unspecified damages and a penalty. <PERSON> Turner </PERSON> defended the concept of group homes, which have encountered opposition from prospective neighbors and delaying tactics around the country. `` Studies have shown that these facilities are better for residents than the out-of-sight, out-of-mind institutions of the past, and that they have no adverse effects on the neighborhood,'' he said.
