ORGANIZATION> NTSB </ORGANIZATION> investigators have said the door would help determine what caused the plane to pop open at 22,000 feet, ripping a 10-by-20-foot hole in the fuselage. In April, a three-day hearing on the accident failed to produce conclusive evidence of the cause. <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> executives said then they wanted to see the door recovered. Negotiations were reported to be under way at that time on whether to retrieve the door and how the costs would be divided. Military radar had tracked an object believed to be the cargo door falling into the ocean at a point where the water is 16,800 feet deep. Soon after the mishap, undersea experts said the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> is probably the only agency with equipment capable of handling the recovery of the door. A search would probably involve use of a sonar sled and a remote-controlled vehicle with a camera, <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Wolcott </PERSON>, a research submarine pilot at the <LOCATION> Hawaii </LOCATION> Undersea Research Lab at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hawaii </ORGANIZATION>, said earlier this year. The vehicle could probably hook a line to the door to lift it to the surface, he said. The least likely possibility because of the tremendous cost _ up to $ 40,000 a day _ would be the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION>'s Sea Cliff, one of the world's few manned research submarines capable of reaching that depth, <PERSON> Wolcott </PERSON> said
