<HEAD>Times Says Home Mortgage Insurer's Reserves May Disappear</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 An audit of the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Housing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> is expected to show that its main mortgage insurance fund has been suffering losses at a rate that could run it dry in five months, <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> said today. The newspaper, citing government investigators and private auditors, said the findings will be contained in the first full audit of the 55-year-old agency, which insures $ 275 billion worth of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> home mortgages. It cited agency officials as saying the <ORGANIZATION> FHA </ORGANIZATION> was down to a five-month reserve, $ 2.8 billion, to cover holders of defaulted mortgages. When the reserve runs out, the <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> must pick up the payments. The main fund is the Mutual Mortgage Insurance Fund, which covers 5.5 million mortgages of up to $ 101,000 each on single-family homes. The insurance is financed largely by premiums paid by home buyers. Claims on the fund amounted to $ 2.9 billion in 1986, $ 4.4 billion in 1988 and will hit an estimated $ 6.6 billion this year, according to budget documents cited by the Times. It said that a <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Accounting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> report last month put <ORGANIZATION> FHA </ORGANIZATION>'s losses for the year ending September 1988 at $ 452 million and that preliminary figures for the following six months indicated an additional $ 150 million in losses. Economic downturns, particularly in the oil industry in the <LOCATION> Southwest </LOCATION>, plus fraud, mismanagement and a sluggish housing market contributed to the agency's problems, the Times said. Senior officials of the <ORGANIZATION> FHA </ORGANIZATION>'s parent organization, the <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Housing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Urban </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Development </ORGANIZATION>, speaking anonymously, said the two consecutive years of losses did not pose a serious threat, the Times said. But a private auditor said he was less optimistic, particularly if there were a recession.
