<DATELINE>OSLO, Norway (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Charter planes flew hundreds of weary tourists home today after they were plucked from a Soviet ocean liner that had crashed into an iceberg, cutting short a pleasure cruise to the land of the midnight sun. Workers plugged the holes on the 630-foot cruise ship <PERSON> Maxim </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorky </PERSON> and the vessel steamed toward the island of <LOCATION> Spitsbergen </LOCATION> today, escorted by two other Soviet vessels, the Soviet news agency <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> said. Maritime experts said the ocean liner, on a cruise to see the 24-hour summer light in the arctic, was moving too fast when it struck the ice in the <LOCATION> Norwegian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sea </LOCATION>, 300 miles east of northern <LOCATION> Greenland </LOCATION> and 180 miles west of <LOCATION> Spitsbergen </LOCATION>. No one was seriously injured. Norwegian helicopters flew the aged and most infirm to safety, but some passengers spent up to seven hours huddled under blankets in lifeboats until they were picked up. Others waited on ice floes. For West German passenger <PERSON> Giesela </PERSON> <PERSON> Rillinger </PERSON>, `` It was six hours of nothing but ice floes and the sky. If a storm had come up it would have been all over for us. Six hours of facing death.'' The Norwegian <ORGANIZATION> coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> guard </ORGANIZATION> ship Senja evacuated 660 passengers _ all but about a dozen West Germans _ and 193 <PERSON> Maxim </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorky </PERSON> crew members to <LOCATION> Longyearbyen </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Norway </LOCATION>'s administrative center on <LOCATION> Spitzbergen </LOCATION> island, from where the tourists were flown to <LOCATION> Dusseldorf </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>. Capt. <PERSON> Marat </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Galimov </PERSON> and 192 other Soviet crew members remained on the <PERSON> Maxim </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorky </PERSON>, said <PERSON> Sigurd </PERSON> <PERSON> Kleiven </PERSON>, captain of the Senja. <PERSON> Kleiven </PERSON> said it was <PERSON> Galimov </PERSON>'s first voyage in the area. Tour leader <PERSON> Winfried </PERSON> <PERSON> Prinz </PERSON> said he was standing on the bridge next to <PERSON> Galimov </PERSON> when the ship struck the iceberg. `` It happened very fast,'' <PERSON> Prinz </PERSON> told a reporter in <LOCATION> Dusseldorf </LOCATION>. `` We went into the ice field without warning and unexpectedly, something nobody had counted on. The ship was cruising at normal speed, about 18 knots, so it was n't exactly slow, as the collision shook the ship,'' <PERSON> Prinz </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Kleiven </PERSON> said the liner was moving at 18.4 knots when it hit the ice, tearing a gash 20 feet long and four to six inches wide in the bow. `` I would hardly have sailed faster than two to three knots in such ice-clogged water,'' <PERSON> Kleiven </PERSON> told reporters on board his coast guard vessel. `` There was fog in the area, and it seems to me as if the <PERSON> Maxim </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorky </PERSON> may have sped too fast straight into the ice,'' <PERSON> Kleiven </PERSON> said. But experienced <LOCATION> Norwegian </LOCATION> sailors agreed the <PERSON> Maxim </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorky </PERSON> had sailed too fast in an area often clogged with ice. `` Not even the coast guard vessels sail faster than three to five knots in such waters,'' <PERSON> Guttorm </PERSON> <PERSON> Jacobsen </PERSON>, a skipper who has sailed the arctic for 40 years, told the <ORGANIZATION> Verdens </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Gang </ORGANIZATION> newspaper. `` The <PERSON> Maxim </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorky </PERSON> must have been too eager to keep its schedule.'' The newspaper quoted other experts as saying that even if the captain had seen the ice from a distance of 10 miles it would have taken his ship up to 45 minutes to stop from a speed of 18 knots. The Soviet Embassy in <LOCATION> Oslo </LOCATION> said the ship today was moving at 4.5 knots toward <LOCATION> Spitzbergen </LOCATION>, where it would receive emergency repairs. It was accompanied by a Soviet tugboat and a freighter. The ship set out June 11 from <LOCATION> Bremerhaven </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, sailed to <LOCATION> Iceland </LOCATION> and encountered its difficulties while sailing around the <LOCATION> Spitsbergen </LOCATION> archipelago on its way to <LOCATION> Norway </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Maxim </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorky </PERSON> had about 952 people aboard when it struck the ice early Tuesday while most passengers were partying in a shipboard nightclub. The luxury liner was built in 1969 in <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> and sold to the Soviets in 1974.
