<HEAD>Florida Passes Gun-Safety Bill</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 6 grafs to CLARIFY that bill applies to children
shooting anyone, not just other children, tightens. PICKS UP 7th graf,
`Exemptions are ...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JACKIE HALLIFAX</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TALLAHASSEE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> lawmakers passed a bill making gun owners subject to prison terms if their firearms are used by children to shoot someone. The Legislature acted after accidental shootings killed three children since June 5. `` We have experienced too many tragedies, and it's time to put an end to them,'' said Rep. <PERSON> Harry </PERSON> <PERSON> Jennings </PERSON>, a retired <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> colonel who has pushed the proposal for two years. The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> passed the gun-safety bill 26-6 and the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> approved it 71-39 on Tuesday. Gov. <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Martinez </PERSON>, who was persuaded last week to include the bill in this week's special session, was expected to sign the measure. Under the bill, gun owners who fail to secure loaded weapons in their homes could be charged with a felony carrying up to five years in prison and a $ 5,000 fine if children 15 years and younger hurt someone with the firearms. If the child displays the gun in public, the gun owner could be charged with a misdemeanor punishable by up to 60 days in jail and a $ 500 fine. Exemptions are provided for hunting and target shooting accidents, shootings involving stolen guns and the guns of law enforcement officers or military personnel. The law also provides a seven-day delay before parents of a wounded child can be arrested on the felony charge. <PERSON> Jennings </PERSON>, the bill's sponsor, described it as `` one of the most important pieces of legislation that we have addressed in years in this Legislature.'' His legislation gained national attention after three <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> children were killed and four wounded in seven accidents earlier this month. The bill requires gun-shop owners to post a sign explaining the law and to hand out a written warning to customers. The measure also directs the state <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Education </ORGANIZATION> to prepare a gun-safety education program that lawmakers can consider next year. A lobbyist for the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rifle </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> said the bill was acceptable. `` My job was to try to help produce a bill that had the potential to do some good and not just run willy-nilly, damaging additional lives,'' said <ORGANIZATION> NRA </ORGANIZATION> lobbyist <PERSON> Marion </PERSON> <PERSON> Hammer </PERSON>. Rep. <PERSON> Dick </PERSON> <PERSON> Locke </PERSON> led the opponents in the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>, which had approved a similar version during the regular session that ended June 3. `` This bill does not make common sense,'' <PERSON> Locke </PERSON> said. `` You ca n't put Mama and <PERSON> Daddy </PERSON> in jail, the kids in a foster home, the court system is full, the fails are full. Other opponents contended that more children are hurt and killed in accidents involving cars, pools, fires and household poisons than guns. Accidental gunshots are the fifth-leading cause of death of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> children under age 14, and <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> has one of the three highest rates of accidental shootings in the country, according to Sen. <PERSON> Jeanne </PERSON> <PERSON> Malchon </PERSON>, who proposed similar legislation two years ago. Last year, 441 <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> children were injured or killed by guns and another 3,110 were victims of crimes involving firearms.
</TEXT>
