<FIRST>r w PM-Spill-Taxes     06-21 0515</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Spill-Taxes,500</SECOND>
<HEAD>Administration Opposes Bill to Deny Exxon a Cleanup Tax Deduction</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM LUTHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Tax Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration today opposed a bill aimed at denying <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> a tax deduction for costs of cleaning up the <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION> oil spill. `` The bill would violate the fundamental principle of business taxation that a taxpayer's ordinary and necessary business expenses may be deducted in computing net income,'' <PERSON> Kenneth </PERSON> <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gideon </PERSON>, assistant treasury secretary for tax policy, told the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Finance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>. Sen. <PERSON> Harry </PERSON> <PERSON> Reid </PERSON>, D-Nev., sponsor of the bill, said: `` I do not want to tell my constituents that the <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> people owe <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION>, the biggest polluter in history, millions of dollars in a tax rebate in return for destroying the environment and raising prices at the gas pumps. Waving a handful of <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION> credit cards that irate customers had mailed him in protest, <PERSON> Reid </PERSON> added: `` Given the company's dismal cleanup performance and the resultant permanent scar that now defaces <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION>'s beauty, it is incomprehensible that <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION> should be able to claim its cleanup costs _ estimated at $ 500 million _ as an ` ordinary and necessary' cost of doing business. Some 10 million gallons of crude oil were spilled into <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION>'s Prince <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Sound </PERSON> on March 24 when the tanker <PERSON> Exxon </PERSON> <PERSON> Valdez </PERSON> ran aground A large share of <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION>'s cleanup costs apparently are covered by insurance. Under present law, any uninsured share could be deducted from taxable income as a cost of doing business. Because the top corporate tax rate is 34 percent, the effect would be for the federal treasury to pay 34 percent of the uninsured expenses. <PERSON> Reid </PERSON>'s bill, which also would apply to any future chemical spill, would prohibit such a deduction unless the federal government certified that the cleanup had been conducted in accordance with the law. Sen. <PERSON> Ted </PERSON> <PERSON> Stevens </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Alaska </LOCATION>, who said he supports the concept of <PERSON> Reid </PERSON>'s bill, pointed out that existing environmental laws contain no objective standards for determining whether a cleanup was proper. <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Huard </PERSON>, vice president of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Manufacturers </ORGANIZATION>, which opposes the bill, said the legislation likely would discourage corporate efforts to clean up spills. `` Because the sanctions ... are so draconian, a likely response is that taxpayers involved in oil spills or hazardous substance dischages will undertake very little cleanup activity on their own initiative, and instead will choose to protect the deductibility of their expenditures by awaiting specific directions from the applicable government agency,'' <PERSON> Huard </PERSON> said. The bill was supported by <PERSON> Clifton </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Curtis </PERSON>, executive director of the <ORGANIZATION> Oceanic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Society </ORGANIZATION>, an environmental group. He said the legislation should be made tougher by denying `` tax deductions to spillers for oil or hazardous spill-related expenses without regard to adequacy of cleanup.'' `` Such an approach would send a message that would foster stronger preventive measures by industry,'' <PERSON> Curtis </PERSON> said. Rep. <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> O. </PERSON> <PERSON> Lipinski </PERSON>, D-Ill., who has introduced a companion bill to <PERSON> Reid </PERSON>'s in the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>, said <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION>'s cleanup expenses should not be tax-deductible because `` oil and toxic spill cleanup is not ` ordinary' and is not a ` necessary' business expense.
