 June 17 The <ORGANIZATION> Milwaukee </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Journal </ORGANIZATION> on a healthy start program for infants: Children deserve the best possible start in life. That means their mothers must have adequate prenatal care, a relative luxury for the thousands of <LOCATION> Wisconsin </LOCATION> women not fortunate enough to be covered by insurance yet not needy enough to qualify for Medicaid. It is for these women, and their infants less than a year old, that <LOCATION> Wisconsin </LOCATION>'s Healthy Start program was designed. Now legislators seem inclined to expand <ORGANIZATION> Healthy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Start </ORGANIZATION>, to include women whose family incomes are higher than current ceilings set by the state. That's not just a compassionate gesture; in the long run, it would prove cost-effective, too. Healthy Start pays all prenatal doctor bills, whatever prescription costs the woman incurs during pregnancy and all expenses associated with labor and delivery. In addition, the program covers the costs of the mother's medical care for 60 days after delivery and the infant's for a full year. Obviously, a baby who is immunized and whose growth and development are tracked by a doctor will have an edge over one lacking such attention. The benefits of prenatal care may seem murkier but are no less compelling. The longer a woman delays prenatal visits to a doctor, the more likely she is to bear a child needing medical attention because of prematurity, low birth weight or some other complication. Experts calculate that every $ 1 spent on prenatal care saves $ 3.38 that would otherwise have to be spent later on a youngster born with problems.
</TEXT>
