<HEAD>Massachusetts Porn Law Challenge Sent Back to State Courts</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD CARELLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 An anticipated <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> showdown over state child pornography laws fizzled today when the justices, in splintered voting, sent a <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> case back to that state's courts The court told the <ORGANIZATION> Massachusetts </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Judicial </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> to decide whether a since-amended state law can be used to prosecute <PERSON> Douglas </PERSON> <PERSON> Oakes </PERSON>, 40, of <LOCATION> Holden </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mass. </LOCATION>, for `` soliciting a child to pose ... in a state of nudity ... for pornographic purposes.'' Today's ruling is a setback for <PERSON> Oakes </PERSON>, who had been freed from any criminal liability by the state's highest court. <PERSON> Oakes </PERSON> was criminally convicted in <LOCATION> Worcester </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>. Prosecutors said that in 1984 he induced his 14-year-old stepdaughter to pose for photographs while clothed only in bikini underpants and a scarf. Police were contacted after the girl's mother discovered the photos. <PERSON> Oakes </PERSON> was sentenced to 10 years in prison, and was paroled after two years. The state's highest court threw out <PERSON> Oakes </PERSON>' conviction and dismissed the criminal indictment against him. The state court said the 1982 law under which <PERSON> Oakes </PERSON> was prosecuted was too broad, and criminalized `` conduct that virtually every person would regard as lawful.'' `` For example,'' the state court said in its ruling, `` -LRB- the law -RRB- makes a criminal of a parent who takes a frontal view picture of his or her naked 1-year-old running on a beach or romping in a wading pool.'' The law later was amended to add a `` lascivious intent'' requirement. Today's decision was accompanied by three written opinions but no majority opinion attracting at least five justices. Four of the court's members, led by Justice <PERSON> Sandra </PERSON> <PERSON> Day </PERSON> <PERSON> O'Connor </PERSON>, said the issue of whether the original <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> law was overbroad became moot when it was amended. Two justices _ <PERSON> Antonin </PERSON> <PERSON> Scalia </PERSON> and <PERSON> Harry </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Blackmun </PERSON> _ voted to reverse the <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> court and rule that <PERSON> Oakes </PERSON>' prosecution was constitutional. `` Perhaps I am wrong in my estimation of how frequently the posings prohibited by -LRB- the old law -RRB- are done for artistic purposes, or for family photographs, or in some other legitimate and constitutionally protected context I have not envisioned,'' <PERSON> Scalia </PERSON> wrote in an opinion joined by <PERSON> Blackmun </PERSON>. `` We can deal with such a situation in the unlikely event some prosecutor brings an indictment,'' he said. Three justices _ <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Brennan </PERSON>, <PERSON> Thurgood </PERSON> <PERSON> Marshall </PERSON> and <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Stevens </PERSON> _ said the court should uphold the state court decision and rule that the original child-porn law violated free-speech rights. Writing for the three, <PERSON> Brennan </PERSON> noted that the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sunbathing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, a nudist group, told the court that photographs taken of its 30,000 members in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> could lead to prosecutions under the old <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> law. The case is <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> vs. <PERSON> Oakes </PERSON>, 87-1651.
