<HEAD>Court Rules Federal Law Does Not Apply to ABA Role in Picking Judges</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> ruled today that a federal law allowing public scrutiny of governmental advisory groups does not apply to the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bar </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>'s role in picking federal judges. Voting 8-0, the justices allowed the <ORGANIZATION> ABA </ORGANIZATION>'s deliberations to remain largely secret. Justice <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Brennan </PERSON>, in his opinion for the court, said <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> did not intend the <ORGANIZATION> ABA </ORGANIZATION>'s confidential relationship with the <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> in selecting judges to be made public when it passed a law covering adivisory committees. Tipping the balance in favor of confidentiality, <PERSON> Brennan </PERSON> said, is the risk that public disclosure of <ORGANIZATION> ABA </ORGANIZATION> deliberations would infringe improperly on the president's power to nominate federal judges. But <PERSON> Brennan </PERSON> stopped short of declaring that the constitutional doctrine of separation of powers between <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> and the president guarantees the confidentiality of the deliberations. Today's ruling upheld a federal judge's decision last year barring application of the Federal Advisory Committee Act to the <ORGANIZATION> ABA </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Standing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> on the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Judiciary </ORGANIZATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> ABA </ORGANIZATION>, the nation's largest lawyers' organization, has for some 40 years played a key role in advising presidents on nominees to the federal bench. The <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> asks the <ORGANIZATION> ABA </ORGANIZATION>'s judiciary committee for confidential evaluations of possible judicial nominees. The panel is the only non-government group that routinely is told of potential nominees before the names are made public. <ORGANIZATION> ABA </ORGANIZATION> evaluations are made public after a nomination is submitted to the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> _ although the substance of the deliberations generally remains secret. The <ORGANIZATION> ABA </ORGANIZATION>, after interviewing lawyers, judges, professors and the nominee, rates potential nominees as exceptionally well qualified, well qualified, qualified or not qualified. The <ORGANIZATION> ABA </ORGANIZATION> is not required to reveal who was interviewed or any specifics of the process. A controversy over the <ORGANIZATION> ABA </ORGANIZATION>'s role was ignited when the <ORGANIZATION> ABA </ORGANIZATION> panel was divided over former President <PERSON> Ronald </PERSON> <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s nomination of <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Bork </PERSON> to the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> in 1987. Republicans on the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Judiciary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> accused <ORGANIZATION> ABA </ORGANIZATION> committee members of being politicallly motivated in questioning <PERSON> Bork </PERSON>'s fitness to be a justice. The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> defeated <PERSON> Bork </PERSON>'s nomination after a long, bittr fight in which opponents said he was too rigidly conservative. The conservative <ORGANIZATION> Washington </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Legal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foundation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Citizen </ORGANIZATION>, a liberal public-interest organization, joined forces in seeking to compel the <ORGANIZATION> ABA </ORGANIZATION> committee to reveal its deliberations. The former <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration opposed the move. The <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> last year said the Federal Advisory Committee Act is aimed at special groups and the <ORGANIZATION> ABA </ORGANIZATION> panel does not fit into that category. Justice <PERSON> Antonin </PERSON> <PERSON> Scalia </PERSON> did not take part in today's ruling. The cases are Public Citizen vs. <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>, 88-429, and <ORGANIZATION> Washington </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Legal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foundation </ORGANIZATION> vs. <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>, 88-494.
