<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> will veto major child-care legislation being advanced by <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> Democrats and a Republican if it reaches the White House in its present form, the administration said today. A letter from the <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Management </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Budget </ORGANIZATION> distributed on <LOCATION> Capitol </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hill </LOCATION> said the multibillion-dollar package before the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> `` violates all of the president's principles.'' The letter said the revised measure before the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> was an improvement over the original bill but remained `` fundamentally flawed.'' It said the measure would restrict parental choice in child care, provide assistance only to families who pay for child care and discriminate against low-income parents who have other family members care for their children. The White House is backing an alternative Republican package. The <ORGANIZATION> OMB </ORGANIZATION> letter said that if the plan favored by the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> leadership `` were presented to the president, his senior advisers would recommend that he veto it.'' The statement was distributed as <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> GOP leaders sought support for the alternative. Debate on the issue continued in the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> today, but no votes were scheduled until Thursday. The criticisms in the <ORGANIZATION> OMB </ORGANIZATION> letter were similar to those raised by many Republicans during the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>'s five days of debate on the issue. The points prompted Sen. <PERSON> Orrin </PERSON> <PERSON> Hatch </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> Utah </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> who co-sponsored the Democratic bill, to lash out at his <ORGANIZATION> GOP </ORGANIZATION> colleagues. `` I'm ashamed when I hear some of the arguments that I've heard on this floor,'' <PERSON> Hatch </PERSON> said Tuesday, accusing critics of spreading `` misinformation and disinformation and distortions.'' `` I have no respect for people who distort the facts,'' <PERSON> Hatch </PERSON> said. `` We have an obligation to tell the truth and let the chips fall as they may.'' <PERSON> Hatch </PERSON>, who has been critical of the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration's competing child care proposal, said he believed provisions of the president's tax-credit package could be merged with the revised Act for Better Child Care sponsored by <PERSON> Hatch </PERSON> and Sen. <PERSON> Christopher </PERSON> <PERSON> Dodd </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Conn </LOCATION>. `` This should not be a partisan political issue,'' <PERSON> Hatch </PERSON> `` We're willing to do what it takes to get a child care bill and we do n't care who gets the credit for it.'' Republican leader <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Dole </PERSON> had planned to offer a White House-backed alternative to the <ORGANIZATION> ABC </ORGANIZATION> plan on Tuesday but held off as the <ORGANIZATION> GOP </ORGANIZATION> leadership sought support from Southern Democrats. It relies almost exclusively on tax credits, including an expansion of the existing earned income tax credit for low-income families with children under the age of 5. Like the Dodd-Hatch proposal, the <PERSON> Dole </PERSON> alternative would provide up-front money to families that otherwise could not take advantage of the existing dependent care tax credit because of low income. <PERSON> Dole </PERSON> also called for a $ 400 million block grant program states could use to fund programs designed to improve the quality and quantity of child care. And, borrowing a proposal from Sen. <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Armstrong </PERSON>, R-Colo., <PERSON> Dole </PERSON> proposed exempting child care earnings from the outside income limitations faced by Social Security recipients <PERSON> Dole </PERSON> and other Republicans have touched on their plan during the four days of <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> debate. Democrats, joined by the <ORGANIZATION> GOP </ORGANIZATION>'s <PERSON> Hatch </PERSON>, have called it inadequate while offering to merge its tax credit provisions with the direct subsidies provided to parents and child care providers under the <ORGANIZATION> ABC </ORGANIZATION> plan. Benefits under <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s plan would be available mainly to those making under $ 10,000 a year. The Democratic subsidies would be available according to formulas determined at the state level. An aide to <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> Majority Leader <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Mitchell </PERSON> predicted <PERSON> Dole </PERSON>'s effort to substitute his proposal for the Dodd-Hatch measure would fail. `` Senator <PERSON> Mitchell </PERSON> has proven in the past that he knows how to count,'' the aide said. <PERSON> Mitchell </PERSON>, unable to reach agreement with Republicans on a timetable to bring the issue to a final vote, warned he would delay a two-week <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> recess due to begin next week if debate and amendments prevented a final vote by Friday. `` This is a very important matter,'' <PERSON> Mitchell </PERSON> said. `` We're going to stay as long as it takes.'' With <PERSON> Dole </PERSON> holding his plan, the highlight of Tuesday's debate was <PERSON> Hatch </PERSON>'s angry criticism of fellow Republicans and conservatives. Waving a copy of a circular distributed at a <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> caucus that attacked the Dodd-Hatch bill, <PERSON> Hatch </PERSON> said he did not mind arguments over honest disagreements but added: `` I mind people who try to win their case with falsehoods.'' He said the letter was on paper without a letterhead. `` I do not know who prepared this piece of junk.'' As revised, the <ORGANIZATION> ABC </ORGANIZATION> bill would authorize $ 1.75 billion for child care programs in fiscal 1990, with 70 percent of the money going to low-income parents to help them pay for child care. The remaining funds would go to states for programs to improve the quality and quantity of available child care.
