<HEAD>Judge Temporarily Restores Dropout's License</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID WILKISON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHARLESTON, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A judge temporarily restored driving privileges today to a teen-age father-to-be whose license was revoked because he dropped out of school. Circuit Judge <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Zakaib </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON> set aside <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Means </PERSON>' license revocation for 30 days while lawyers file briefs and the judge makes a decision. Means, 17, who dropped out in ninth grade last year, is appealing the loss of his license May 30 under a first-of-its-kind law aimed at curbing truancy in a state where the dropout rate is around 17 percent. Under the law passed last summer, students under 18 who miss more than 10 consecutive days of school or have 15 unexcused absences lose their driving privileges. Means, whose 16-year-old wife, <PERSON> Tonya </PERSON>, is expecting their first child this fall, sued on June 8, the first time the law has been challenged in court. His father said the teen-ager can not support his growing family without a license. The law allows school boards to grant hardship exceptions, but state officials maintain that the teen-ager could hold a job and still complete his education. Educators have praised the legislation, saying its brings teen-agers back to school, but Means' lawyer, <PERSON> Chris </PERSON> <PERSON> Butch </PERSON>, has argued that it conflicts with another law allowing students to drop out at 16. He called the law ridiculous. `` It says you're poor, you dropped out of high school, and now we're going to punish you some more,'' <PERSON> Butch </PERSON> said. Several states, including <LOCATION> Wisconsin </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>, where Gov. <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Clements </PERSON> signed a dropout bill into law Friday, have similar laws. The judge today <PERSON> Zakaib </PERSON> said Means keep his driving privileges if he enrolls in a high school equivalency course and makes satisfactory progress. `` I think they're trying to force me to go into a GED program and I do n't like being forced to do anything,'' Means said after the hearing.
