<HEAD>Mayors Deplore Supreme Court Rulings on Race</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 15 grafs to UPDATE Flynn winning election and RESTORE
first reference to Atwater. PICKS UP 13th graf pv, ``Even some ...'</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto WX9</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM M. WELCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHARLESTON, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The nation's mayors today adopted a statement deploring recent <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> decisions that they say weaken affirmative action. The <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Conference </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mayors </ORGANIZATION> also called for higher federal taxes and a ban on possession of semi-automatic weapons. Before wrapping up their annual conference, the mayors also settled an unprecedented contested race for the conference's future leadership, choosing Democrat <PERSON> Ray </PERSON> <PERSON> Flynn </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION> over Republican <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Althaus </PERSON> of <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Pa </LOCATION>. The mayors overwhelmingly voted down an effort by some <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> mayors to soften the language of their resolution on anti-discrimination in employment. Mayor <PERSON> Cecil </PERSON> <PERSON> Bradbury </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Pinellas </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Park </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Fla. </LOCATION>, argued that whites have been victims of discrimination through efforts aimed at encouraging minority employment. But the mayors sided with Republican <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Hudnut </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Indianapolis </LOCATION>, who argued that without affirmative action, `` the good ol' boy network'' will favor whites. The mayors said recent <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> decisions are `` making it more difficult to ensure equal opportunities in employment for all Americans.'' Among the other statements, the mayors called for higher federal taxes to cut the deficit and allow more urban aid, and urged a ban on possession of military-type semi-automatic assault weapons. The five-day meeting of mayors from around the nation neared an end one day after the session erupted into partisan name-calling, with <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>'s <PERSON> Ed </PERSON> <PERSON> Koch </PERSON> launching a bitter tirade against the Republican national chairman. <PERSON> Flynn </PERSON> was elected chairman of the organization's advisory committee, an unglamorous title but a job that puts him in line to be president of the conference in 1991. The vote was cast largely along party lines, 67-35, although <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION>'s <PERSON> Kathy </PERSON> <PERSON> Whitmire </PERSON>, a Democrat and incoming president of the group, sided with the Republican. <PERSON> Flynn </PERSON> said the issue was whether the mayors wanted an outspoken critic of President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> who would challenge Republican policies. <PERSON> Whitmire </PERSON>, from <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>, has said she is optimistic about the new administration. `` I do n't think this is time for mayors to sit back and just go along, to say everything's all right in our cities. Everything is not all right in our cities,'' <PERSON> Flynn </PERSON> said. The contest for advisory committee chairman was thrown to the full conference when two Democrats sided with the Republicans and deadlocked a nominating committee that for 57 years has settled such matters in private. The meeting, where partisanship is often submerged in discussions of common urban needs, saw party bickering flare when <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> <PERSON> Atwater </PERSON>, the <ORGANIZATION> GOP </ORGANIZATION> national chairman, spoke Monday. Even some Republicans complained about his blunt partisan speech, including <PERSON> Atwater </PERSON>'s statement that he was targeting <PERSON> Koch </PERSON>'s re-election race Arriving Tuesday, <PERSON> Koch </PERSON> denounced <PERSON> Atwater </PERSON> as `` amoral'' and a `` pathological'' liar. He said <PERSON> Atwater </PERSON> bore responsibility for the <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> memo that attacked <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> Speaker <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Foley </PERSON> with homosexual innuendo and had lied in denying it. `` He may be the best hired gun in the world, but he carries with him all of the things that <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> hates, which is low-level, disgusting tactics ... vile things,'' <PERSON> Koch </PERSON> said of <PERSON> Atwater </PERSON>. Democratic National Chairman <PERSON> Ron </PERSON> <PERSON> Brown </PERSON>, who previously called for <PERSON> Atwater </PERSON>'s resignation, also addressed the group Tuesday and laced his speech with blasts at <LOCATION> Atwater </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Brown </PERSON> accused his Republican counterpart of having `` taken politics to the lowest level of my lifetime.'' `` Thanks to the Lee Atwaters of the world, national politics is looking more and more like the coastline of <LOCATION> Valdez </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION>,'' <PERSON> Brown </PERSON> said. `` Make no mistake, they want the political oil spill of negative campaigning to spread across <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>.'' In <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> RNC </ORGANIZATION> spokeswoman <PERSON> Leslie </PERSON> <PERSON> Goodman </PERSON> said, `` We assume <PERSON> Ed </PERSON> <PERSON> Koch </PERSON> has said all these things because he's in a heated race for mayor.'' She had no comment on <PERSON> Brown </PERSON>'s remarks. The partisanship, combined with the unusual leadership race, dominated discussions among the mayors. <LOCATION> Indianapolis </LOCATION> Republican Mayor <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Hudnut </PERSON>, who on Tuesday had said he was `` embarrassed and disappointed'' by <PERSON> Atwater </PERSON>'s remarks, criticized <PERSON> Brown </PERSON> on Wednesday. `` I just think politicizing the meeting is wrong, and <PERSON> Ron </PERSON> was as guilty as <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> was,'' <PERSON> Hudnut </PERSON> said. He noted that many mayors are elected in races where no party affiliation is listed, and said the conference should n't invite national party chairmen again. `` We work very hard not to be partisan in this organization,'' added <PERSON> Althaus </PERSON>, who was working to avoid a party-line vote in his own race since Democratic mayors outnumber Republicans. The race was for the job of chairman of the conference's advisory committee. It carries an unglamorous title, but the job is third on the group's leadership ladder and means the winner will be scheduled to assume the post of president of the conference _ and leading spokesman for the nation's mayors _ in 1991. The race had partisan dimensions because a victory by <PERSON> Althaus </PERSON> would mean the conference would have two consecutive Republican leaders for the first time ever. Republican Mayor <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Isaac </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Colorado </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Springs </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Colo. </LOCATION>, has the job and is scheduled to be president in 1990, following Democrat <PERSON> Kathryn </PERSON> <PERSON> Whitmire </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION>, who was to assume the presidency today after a year as vice president. The mayors were ending their meeting having barely mentioned the scandals involving the <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Housing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Urban </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Development </ORGANIZATION>, which is beset by allegations of influence peddling and disclosures of embezzlement. `` We ca n't let the Republicans turn housing programs for the poor into subsidy programs for wealthy Republican consultants,'' <PERSON> Brown </PERSON> said in one of the few public airings of the issue this week.
