<DATELINE>KHAO NONG KHLO, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Thai jet fighters dropped bombs and helicopter-borne <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> infantrymen swooped down on imaginary enemies Wednesday in the climax to this year's joint war games. About 400 <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> troops and a like number of <LOCATION> Thai </LOCATION> soldiers took part in a day of live fire exercises in hilly, forested countryside about 200 miles northwest of <LOCATION> Bangkok </LOCATION>. The scenario in the `` Cobra Gold'89'' war games called for the two sides to resist an enemy push and launch a counterattack with the support of tanks, artillery and air strikes. A company from the 3rd Brigade of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> 25th Infantry Division was flown into attack position while jets and helicopter gunships provided support. Both sides flew supersonic F-16 fighters, which <LOCATION> Thailand </LOCATION> has acquired from the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. Two Thai <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> F-5 warplanes dropped 500-pound bombs on a hillside. The exercise was watched by military attaches from the region and Brig. Gen. <PERSON> Mya </PERSON> <PERSON> Thien </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Burma </LOCATION>. Burmese troops have recently intruded and fired weapons into <LOCATION> Thailand </LOCATION> while fighting <PERSON> Karen </PERSON> rebels. The fighting continues along the frontier just west of where the games were staged. `` Cobra Gold'89,'' the eighth in this annual series, began June 3 and has involved 6,000 Thai troops and 3,200 <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> personnel, including 2,000 from the Hawaii-based <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> 25th Infantry Division. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, which based thousands of troops in <LOCATION> Thailand </LOCATION> during the Vietnam War, is the country's key Western ally.
