<HEAD>4 Arrested in Baby-Selling Scheme</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER ALAN HARPER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Four people, including a father-daughter team of lawyers, ran a baby-selling scheme that bilked 100 couples of $ 500,000, authorities charged. Only 50 couples got babies, state Attorney General <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Abrams </PERSON> said Tuesday. Some others who had paid up to $ 16,000 got neither a child nor a refund after being told the mother miscarried or changed her mind, he said. Authorities said the brokers actually were selling the babies to the highest bidder, doing business in such places as the parking lot of an International House of Pancakes. The mothers, mostly unwed teen-agers from rural areas, were lured through ads in The Star, a supermarket tabloid, and offered help with adoption, counseling, free medical care and financial support. The adoptive couples were middle-class people from urban areas in 21 states and <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Seymour </PERSON> <PERSON> Fenichel </PERSON> and his daughter, <PERSON> Deborah </PERSON> <PERSON> Fenichel </PERSON> <PERSON> Greenspan </PERSON>, both lawyers, and <PERSON> Harriet </PERSON> and <PERSON> Lawrence </PERSON> <PERSON> Lauer </PERSON>, all of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, were indicted on 144 counts. The four pleaded innocent Tuesday to charges of grand larceny, conspiracy, fraud, perjury, filing false documents and making false statements by illegally operating <ORGANIZATION> Child </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Haven </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Northeastern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pennsylvania </ORGANIZATION>, a private adoption agency. <PERSON> Abrams </PERSON> said neither the mothers who gave up their children nor the adoptive parents face charges. Officials also said it was unlikely the mothers would try to get the children back. Partly because the four defendants used a legitimate social worker to process the adoption cases through the courts, the attorney general said he felt the children were in good hands and the adoptions were not reversible. The Lauers' attorney, <PERSON> Harvey </PERSON> <PERSON> Baum </PERSON>, said, `` Our clients' involvement with adoption agencies have sprung from their own experiences in overcoming great obstacles in obtaining their own children in adoption `` Their actions were always generated from good intentions and to help others who had the same problems they had,'' he said. Mrs. <PERSON> Lauer </PERSON> wrote an article for Good Housekeeping magazine in 1979 about getting her younger daughter through a classified ad. <PERSON> Fenichel </PERSON> was released on $ 100,000 bail, his daughter on $ 2,500. The Lauers were released and given two weeks to raise $ 10,000 bail. The most serious charge carries a maximum of seven years in prison and a $ 5,000 fine or double the amount illegally gained. <PERSON> Abrams </PERSON> said he would seek restitution for the couples.
