<HEAD>Justice Department Charges Suburb Over Group Home for Retarded</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Suburban <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Heights </LOCATION> violated an anti-discrimination law when its <ORGANIZATION> City </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> blocked construction of a home for mentally retarded adults, the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> alleges in a lawsuit. It is the first lawsuit brought by the department alleging housing discrimination against the handicapped under the Fair Housing Amendments Act that took effect March 12, the agency said in a news release. At issue is a May 1 vote by the <ORGANIZATION> City </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> in the southern suburb of 32,000 people, denying a special-use permit for construction of a home for 15 mentally retarded adults in a neighborhood of single-family and two-family homes, the department said. The complaint, filed Tuesday in federal court in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>, contends the council denied the request because of neighbors' opposition `` based on fears and prejudices,'' the statement said `` Under the new Fair Housing act, stereotypes and baseless fears concerning the handicapped can not be used to block the development of group homes,'' said <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Turner </PERSON>, acting assistant attorney general in charge of of the Civil Rights Division, in the statement issued in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. `` Studies have shown that these facilities are better for residents than the out-of-sight, out-of-mind institutions of the past, and that they have no adverse effects on the neighborhood,'' <PERSON> Turner </PERSON> said. <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Creswell </PERSON>, corporation counsel for <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Heights </LOCATION>, did not immediately return a telephone call seeking comment on the lawsuit. <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Heights </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Police </ORGANIZATION> Commissioner <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Gliottoni </PERSON>, one of the five council members, would not comment on the merits of the case because of the lawsuit. But he said the council followed the lead of the city's zoning board and its plan commission in the decision. `` They are the sounding boards,'' <PERSON> Gliottoni </PERSON> said of the two panels. `` They listen to all the people who are for it and all the people who are against it. We as council members have no input whatsoever.'' He said both groups denied zoning approval, and the Council followed those recommendations, as it does more than 99 percent of the time. The <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> statement said the building permit was sought by <ORGANIZATION> RFMS </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, a <LOCATION> Galesburg </LOCATION> company that specializes in developing homes for the retarded. There was no answer at a telephone number listed for RFMS.
