<HEAD>Court Eases Way for Railroad to Sell Off Lines Without Labor Talks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD CARELLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>, by a 5-4 vote, today gave railroads greater leeway to sell off rail lines without first entering into collective bargaining about a sale's effects. The court, resolving one of the most critical issues facing the nation's railroad industry, said the <ORGANIZATION> Pittsburgh </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Lake </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Erie </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Railroad </ORGANIZATION>, or P & amp; LE, may sell its 182 miles of rail line in eastern <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> and western <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION> without first negotiating with its employees' unions. Interpreting the Railway Labor Act, a federal law governing the railroad and airline industries, the court said the P & amp; LE was not obligated to bargain over the effects of the sale, including lost jobs. The P & amp; LE, having lost $ 60 million in the five previous years, announced in 1987 that it had agreed to sell its trackage and other assets for about $ 70 million to a newly formed subsidiary of the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> West </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pullman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp </ORGANIZATION>. The subsidary intended to operate the railroad as the P & amp; LE had, except that it would not assume the <ORGANIZATION> P </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> LE </ORGANIZATION>'s union contracts and would lay off about 500 of the railroad's 750 employees. When the unions were notified of the sale, they challenged it as a violation of the Railway Labor Act. The <ORGANIZATION> Interstate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>, however, approved the sale. A federal trial judge and the 3rd <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> ruled that the <ORGANIZATION> P </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; LE was legally obligated to negotiate with its unions about the sale's effects on the workforce. Today, the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> said the lower courts were wrong. After the sale was postponed, the <ORGANIZATION> P </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <PERSON> LE </PERSON> sought a new purchaser. Today's decision also makes that pursuit easier. Writing for the high court, Justice <PERSON> Byron </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> White </PERSON> said the P & amp; LE was not obligated to postpone its sale of the trackage `` beyond the time the sale was approved by the commission and was scheduled to be consummated.'' He added: `` To the extent that the unions' demands could be satisfied only by the assent of the buyers, they sought to change or dictate the terms of the sale, and in effect challenged the decision to sell itself. `` At that time, P & amp; LE was under no obligation to bargain about the terms it had already negotiated,'' <PERSON> White </PERSON> wrote. White was joined by Chief Justice <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Rehnquist </PERSON> and Justices <PERSON> Sandra </PERSON> <PERSON> Day </PERSON> <PERSON> O'Connor </PERSON>, <PERSON> Antonin </PERSON> <PERSON> Scalia </PERSON> and <PERSON> Anthony </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON>. Justices <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Stevens </PERSON>, <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Brennan </PERSON>, <PERSON> Thurgood </PERSON> <PERSON> Marshall </PERSON> and <PERSON> Harry </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Blackmun </PERSON> dissented. But by a unanimous vote the court left unresolved _ and sent back to the 3rd Circuit court for further study _ the related issue of what authority federal courts have to block strikes in such cases. The cases are <ORGANIZATION> Pittsburgh </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Lake </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Erie </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Railroad </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> vs. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Railway </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Executives </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, 87-1859, and <ORGANIZATION> P </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; LE vs. RLEA, 87-1888.
