<HEAD>Two Blacks Win Judicial Races in Court-Ordered Mississippi Election</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 7 grafs to ADD poll tax repealed; PICKS UP 6th graf
pvs, `The state's ...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT NAYLOR Jr.</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JACKSON, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Two of six black candidates won judgeships in elections ordered by a judge who said <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION>'s judicial districts discriminated against blacks. <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> now has five blacks among its 78 judges, a gain of one after Tuesday's elections. One incumbent lost. `` In spite of some black leaders' allegations that there is no more discrimination in <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION>, these election results are clear indication that discrimination is alive and well in <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> and will probably be around for some time to come,'' said attorney <PERSON> Carrol </PERSON> <PERSON> Rhodes </PERSON>. <PERSON> Rhodes </PERSON> was one of the lawyers who represented blacks in a 1986 federal lawsuit that resulted in the redrawing of judicial districts in <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION>. `` Voting patterns along racial lines, if it has been changing, it's becoming more pronounced,'' he said. `` It just shows that we have a lot more work to do.'' Mississippians on Tuesday also finally removed from the state constitution an unenforcable poll tax that was enacted years ago to keep blacks from voting but was struck down by the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> in 1966. With 98 percent of the vote in, unofficial returns had 99,648 voting for repeal of the tax and 72,844 against repeal. The state's four black judges are <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> Justice <PERSON> Reuben </PERSON> <PERSON> Anderson </PERSON>, Circuit Judges <PERSON> Fred </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Banks </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON> and <PERSON> Lillie </PERSON> <PERSON> Blackmon-Sanders </PERSON> and Chancery Judge <PERSON> Isaac </PERSON> <PERSON> Byrd </PERSON>. Each was appointed to fill a vacancy, but <PERSON> Anderson </PERSON> went on to win a full eight-year term in 1986; he was not up for election Tuesday. <PERSON> Byrd </PERSON> did not seek election, Banks was unopposed and <PERSON> Blackmon-Sanders </PERSON> was challenged. <PERSON> Blackmon-Sanders </PERSON> lost to Republican challenger <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Watson </PERSON>, 12,878 votes to 9,600. One other black Democrat, <PERSON> Isadore </PERSON> <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Patrick </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Vicksburg </LOCATION>, was unopposed in the general election. The two black winners in contested races were <PERSON> Pat </PERSON> <PERSON> Wise </PERSON>, a Democrat, who defeated Republican <PERSON> Billy </PERSON> <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Keyes </PERSON> for an open <LOCATION> Hinds </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> chancery judge's post, 5,942 votes to 1,638; and <PERSON> Denise </PERSON> <PERSON> Sweet </PERSON> <PERSON> Owens </PERSON>, also a Democrat, who defeated Republican <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Arthur </PERSON> in another open family court post, 4,628 votes to 1,259. Black candidates <PERSON> Solomon </PERSON> <PERSON> Curtis </PERSON> <PERSON> Osborne </PERSON>, <PERSON> Clell </PERSON> <PERSON> G. </PERSON> <PERSON> Ward </PERSON> and <PERSON> Harold </PERSON> <PERSON> Brittain </PERSON> all lost to incumbents. `` I am disappointed with the situation as it now exists outside of <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>,'' said former state Sen. <PERSON> Henry </PERSON> <PERSON> Kirksey </PERSON> of <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>, one of the plaintiffs in the lawsuit that resulted in the redistricting. <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> is the county seat of <LOCATION> Hinds </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> and the state capital. <PERSON> Kirksey </PERSON> said the voting vindicated his complaints about the redrawing of some of the districts. He also said there was n't enough time to persuade black voters to cast ballots only for black candidates. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Barbour </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON> ruled in 1987 that <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION>'s judicial districts discriminated against blacks. The ruling, the first to apply the 1965 Voting Rights Act to judicial elections, was upheld on appeal. <PERSON> Barbour </PERSON> ordered some districts redrawn to create minority subdistricts so that black voters would have a better opportunity to elect black judges. Sixteen elections were contested Tuesday. Those elected will take office on July 3.
