<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TACOMA, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A federal judge today refused to accept a guilty plea from a company indicted for water pollution, demanding <ORGANIZATION> Pennwalt </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> send its `` top man'' rather than the three executives it flew in from <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION>. The case involved a 1985 spill into <LOCATION> Tacoma </LOCATION>'s Hylebos Waterway in which at least 75,000 gallons of a cancer-causing chemical escaped from a ruptured 180,000-gallon storage tank that had been poorly maintained. An undetermined amount of the chemical reached the waterway in an overflow last year. In a plea bargain, <ORGANIZATION> Pennwalt </ORGANIZATION> agreed to pay $ 1.1 million for the spills. `` Before I accept this plan the top officer of your company will be here. Not a division; the top man,'' <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Tanner </PERSON> told <ORGANIZATION> Pennwalt </ORGANIZATION> senior vice president <PERSON> Marty </PERSON> <PERSON> Schwartzberg </PERSON>. In addition to <PERSON> Schwartzberg </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Pennwalt </ORGANIZATION> sent a senior vice president for legal matters and president of the company's inorganic chemical division. <PERSON> Tanner </PERSON> had told attorneys in May that he would not accept the plea unless a <ORGANIZATION> Pennwalt </ORGANIZATION> executive was present, but he did n't specify which executive. Assistant <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Attorney <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Marshall </PERSON> told the judge that he was satisfied that <PERSON> Schwartzberg </PERSON> and another of the executives `` are very high in this company and should be able to answer any questions the court has.'' <ORGANIZATION> Pennwalt </ORGANIZATION> lawyer <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Kelly </PERSON> argued it was very unusual to compel executives to appear in such cases. Usually, a company pleads through its attorneys. `` People in this company have had deterrence imprinted on their memory through this investigation,'' <PERSON> Kelly </PERSON> said. `` There will be deterrence here, your honor.'' <PERSON> Tanner </PERSON>, however, cited statistics indicating <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> ranks second in the country in the number of such reported pollution violations. `` Apparently deterrence is not being very effective,'' he said. The judge rescheduled the plea hearing for July 19.
