<DATELINE>FORT WAYNE, Ind. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 An <ORGANIZATION> Indiana </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> pilot killed during an emergency landing after he blacked out would have been grounded if officials had known he had high blood pressure, a <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bureau </ORGANIZATION> report says. First Lt. <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kruse </PERSON> had lied to flight surgeons, concealing his medical problems for years, so he could fly F-4E Phantom fighters assigned to the 122nd Tactical Fighter Wing at <LOCATION> Baer </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Field </LOCATION>, said the report released Tuesday in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. `` Had the military medical staff been aware of the extent of <PERSON> Kruse </PERSON>'s civilian medical problems, he could never have been medically qualified for flying duty,'' investigators said. Medical report forms indicate <PERSON> Kruse </PERSON> hid his blood pressure problems from military doctors even though he had been a patient at the <ORGANIZATION> Hypertension </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> at <ORGANIZATION> Indiana </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Kruse </PERSON> fainted after shoveling snow Dec. 27, 1988, and his doctor advised him to tell a flight surgeon about the blackouts, the report said. Adj. Gen. <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> K. </PERSON> <PERSON> Elrod </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Indiana </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> has ordered flight surgeons to review the medical records of all flying personnel. <PERSON> Kruse </PERSON>, 26, of <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Wayne </LOCATION>, blacked out about 10 minutes after dec