<TEXT>
 Police on Wednesday foiled an apparent attempt to kill <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION>'s most celebrated Mafia fighter when they discovered a bomb near his villa, news reports said. Security forces assigned to protect Judge <PERSON> Giovanni </PERSON> <PERSON> Falcone </PERSON> reportedly found 44 pounds of plastic explosives stuffed inside a waterproof bag. The guards, part of a 24-hour security detail, noticed the bag on a sunbathing platform at the edge of the sea, about 20 yards from the villa. The bag was the type used by divers to store their gear. Experts blew up the bomb. The Italian news agencies <ORGANIZATION> ANSA </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> AGI </ORGANIZATION> quoted explosives experts who examined the bomb as saying it was clearly meant to kill the judge or his family, who frequently went for swims in the morning. News agencies said investigators theorized that the potential assassins had set up a surveillance base either in one of the nearby villas or in a boat offshore. They theorized the bomb would have been set off when <PERSON> Falcone </PERSON> went down the walk leading to the sea. When the bomb was discovered, <PERSON> Falcone </PERSON> was about to leave the villa for a morning workout at a health club. His guards rushed him instead to his heavily guarded office in <LOCATION> Palermo </LOCATION>'s Palace of Justice. It was not reported whether other members of his family were home at the time. <PERSON> Falcone </PERSON>'s investigations of the Mafia have led to hundreds of convictions. He reportedly receives frequent threats, and his security precautions are among the tightest in <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION>. For his summer stay at the villa, guards have been stationed along the road that runs above the villa, and police motor launches periodically patrol offshore. Mafia members who turned informants have reportedly said that <PERSON> Falcone </PERSON> is the top target of the organization.
