ck at least $ 1.4 billion in development loans while he said <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> is gripped by an `` atmosphere of suspicion and reprisal.'' Hours after the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> actions were announced, Chinese authorities in <LOCATION> Shanghai </LOCATION> ignored the international pleas for clemency and shot to death the three men, who had been convicted of setting a train on fire. They were the first reported executions since the crackdown began. White House spokesman <PERSON> Marlin </PERSON> <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> acknowledged today that <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> has not been influenced by the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> or other nations. `` The weight of world opinion has been heavy on the shoulders of <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> and it does not appear to have made much difference,'' he said, adding that `` history has shown that they generally are not that responsive to outside kinds of pleas.'' <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> said the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> could not afford to turn its back on <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> even though it deplores what is happening there. `` Everyone has to recognize, first of all, that this is a country of a billion people ... a sizeable portion of the world's population that can not be closeted off and ignored,'' he said. Moreover, he said <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> plays an important role in regional conflicts, such as <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION> and the Iran-Iraq war, and also is a nuclear power that possesses ballistic missiles. `` It's important that we have some perspective in viewing the overall, longterm relationship with <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> and that we believe we have tried to strike the right balance,'' <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Genscher </PERSON>, at a picture-taking session with the president, was asked his reaction to the executions. `` We are condemning the brutal ...,'' <PERSON> Genscher </PERSON> began. His comment was interrupted by a <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> aide who shouted an order that ended the photo session. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> made no comment. On <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s orders, the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> will try to postpone consideration of new loans to <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> by international financial institutions. One administration source said the action could freeze $ 1.4 billion over the next six months from the <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Development </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION>. Other estimates indicated the figure could be even higher. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> also curtailed contacts by <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials with their Chinese counterparts, ordering a suspension of all high-level exchanges of government officials with <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION>. While not affecting embassy-to-embassy contacts, it will force <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Mosbacher </PERSON> to scrap a trip to <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> next month, <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> said. `` This action is being taken in response to the wave of violence and reprisals by the <LOCATION> Chinese </LOCATION> authorities against those who have called for democracy,'' White House press secretary <PERSON> Marlin </PERSON> <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> said. `` The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> hopes that the current tragedy in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> can be brought to a peaceful end and that dialogue will replace the atmosphere of suspicion and reprisal,'' <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> said. `` <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> is an important state with which we hope to continue productive relations.'' The latest action follows earlier orders for a freeze on military sales to <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> and a suspension of contacts by military leaders. With the repression in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> has been prodded by conservative and liberal members of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> alike to take tougher action, such as withdrawing most-favored-nation trading privileges from <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION>. The administration has argued that <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> is impervious to pressure from the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, and <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> has said he wants to refrain from commercial sanctions that would hurt the <LOCATION> Chinese </LOCATION> people. Congressional Del. <PERSON> Walter </PERSON> <PERSON> Fauntroy </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-D.C. </LOCATION>, said at a <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> Banking subcommittee hearing prior to <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s action that <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> has $ 4.7 billion in loans `` pending or in the pipeline'' at the <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> and $ 1.1 billion being processed by the <ORGANIZATION> Asian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Development </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION>. The White House statement said <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s action was aimed at new loans to <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>, so it was unclear how much money was involved.
