<HEAD>18 Chinese Want Asylum in Taiwan</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-China, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EILEEN GUERRERO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Eighteen Chinese refugees who arrived in the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION> by boat have asked for asylum in <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION> because they are afraid to return to their homeland, officials said Wednesday. Immigration Chief <PERSON> Miriam </PERSON> <PERSON> Defensor </PERSON> <PERSON> Santiago </PERSON> said the 16 men and two women would be turned over to the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> High Commissioner for Refugees to determine whether they can be classified as political refugees. Ms. <PERSON> Santiago </PERSON> said the group, mostly fishermen, left the southern <LOCATION> Chinese </LOCATION> province of <LOCATION> Guangdong </LOCATION> on April 29 and reached the northern <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION> on May 3, a month before Chinese troops dispersed pro-democracy demonstrators in <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION>. They were brought to <LOCATION> Manila </LOCATION> June 13, Ms. <PERSON> Santiago </PERSON> said. They apparently left <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> `` because they anticipated that trouble was brewing ... that there was going to be political commotion in the next few months,'' Ms. <PERSON> Santiago </PERSON> said. `` And at the same time, they left because of a desire to enhance their economic status,'' she added. `` According to the affidavits taken, they do not wish to return to mainland <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>. They are afraid that they will be punished or killed by authorities in the mainland. They wish to go to <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION> because they think that there are better job prospects there.'' Seven of the 18 refugees went before reporters at Ms. <PERSON> Santiago </PERSON>'s office The others were being held at the headquarters of the Philippine army. When reporters asked why the refugees were afraid to return home, one of them, <PERSON> Lim </PERSON> <PERSON> Niet </PERSON> <PERSON> Nee </PERSON>, replied: `` Because we will be killed.'' `` We want to go to <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION> or any other place other than <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>,'' <PERSON> Lim </PERSON> said through an interpreter. <PERSON> Karola </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON>, deputy representative of the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> High Commissioner for Refugees, said <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> officials would interview the group and consult with <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> officials before deciding whether to certify them as political refugees. In <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Liao </PERSON> <PERSON> Cheng-hao </PERSON>, deputy director of the <ORGANIZATION> Government </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Information </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION>, said the Nationalist government would not accept the 18 Chinese until they are confirmed to be political refugees and not just people looking for a better life. Ms. <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> said the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> High Commissioner for Refugees advised its regional offices on June 12 to expect a possible exodus of Chinese refugees from the mainland following the June 3-4 crackdown on pro-democracy demonstrators in <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION>.
