<FIRST>r a AM-Epilepsy     06-21 0564</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Epilepsy,0559</SECOND>
<HEAD>Epilepsy Drug Linked to Birth Defects</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release at 6 p.m. EDT</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANIEL Q. HANEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A medicine commonly used to control epilepsy in pregnant women appears to cause minor birth defects and retardation, raising a dilemma about how to prevent seizures that can also harm the unborn, a study concludes. Other epilepsy drugs have already been linked with birth defects. Now researchers say that one called Tegretol or carbamazepine should be added to the list. The drug's manufacturer questioned the way the study was conducted and its conclusion. `` Physicians who treat women with seizures are in a very difficult position,'' said <PERSON> Ronald </PERSON> <PERSON> V. </PERSON> <PERSON> Lacro </PERSON>, a co-author of the study. `` This is the drug of choice because it seemed to be safe. We ca n't say that anymore.'' The study found evidence that women who took Tegretol during pregnancy were more likely to produce babies with delayed development and mental retardation. They were also more likely to have unusual facial formations _ including upward slanting eyes, long upper lips and short noses _ and incomplete development of the fingernails. <ORGANIZATION> Ciba-Geigy </ORGANIZATION>, the company that makes Tegretol, said the latest study is a reminder that the risks and benefits of anticonvulsant drugs need to be weighed carefully, but that the medicine should still be considered for epileptic women who want to have children. `` We feel that our past data show that Tegretol is a good option for epileptic women. We still feel that way,'' said spokeswoman <PERSON> Cathy </PERSON> <PERSON> Kernen </PERSON>. The study was directed by Dr. <PERSON> Kenneth </PERSON> <PERSON> Lyons </PERSON> <PERSON> Jones </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> California-San </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Diego </ORGANIZATION>. It was published in Thursday's New England Journal of Medicine Studies have found that severe epileptic seizures during pregnancy can temporarily interrupt the flow of blood to the fetus, causing brain damage. However, epileptic women have an increased risk of producing babies with minor birth defects, even if they do n't have seizures during their pregnancies. `` Counseling has to start before pregnancy for these women,'' said <PERSON> Lacro </PERSON>, a pediatrician at <ORGANIZATION> Children </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hospital </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION>. `` If the woman has severe enough seizures and needs the medicine, then by all means you have to give it. But there is no completely safe therapy other than being off medications.'' The researchers first identified the pattern of birth defects in eight children who had been exposed to the drug before birth. They confirmed it by evaluating an additional 48 children whose mothers had taken the medicine. They found that 11 percent of those exposed had facial abnormalities, 26 percent had incomplete finger nails and 20 percent were slow to develop. Only one of the youngsters with delayed development was old enough to take an intelligence test. That child, aged 6, had an IQ of 65. In a statement, <ORGANIZATION> Ciba-Geigy </ORGANIZATION> criticized the study for `` serious methodological problems.'' It noted that the doctors used women who did not have epilepsy in a comparison group. The higher risk of birth defects among the children of the epileptic women might have resulted from the epilepsy, not the medications, it said. <PERSON> Lacro </PERSON> said, `` I think that what we are seeing is due to the drug. If the changes that we saw were due to seizures alone, then we would see the same pattern of malformations for all kinds of seizure drugs. I think the defects are drug specific, but I ca n't prove that.''
</TEXT>
