 Nervous about falling under Chinese control, residents of <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION> are applying for temporary visas to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> at an accelerating rate. But most of those wanting to move permanently from the world's third-largest financial trading center are looking to other countries Last year, applications for non-immigrant _ or temporary _ visas to visit the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> averaged 650 a day. Since Chinese troops fired on pro-democracy demonstrators in Tiananmen Square June 3-4, the daily total has risen above 1,000, the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said Wednesday. There were no figures available on permanent immigration, but a department official said other countries were preferred because <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> law restricts entry to aliens with close family ties to Americans, occupations in demand here, or other specific qualifications. Other countries are more lenient. Telephone calls for information to the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> consulate in <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION> have increased, but most <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION> residents are well aware of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> rules, the official said. <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s 99-year lease on <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION> expires in 1997 under terms worked out with the Chinese in 1984. The agreement specifies that <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION> would retain its status as an intenrational financial center. The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> consulate reported to the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> that residents were `` nervous about coming under <ORGANIZATION> PRC </ORGANIZATION> -LRB- People's Republic of <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> -RRB- sovereignty and they have responded with an unprecedented demand for foreign visas,'' said an official, declining to be quoted by name. `` We're not getting the bulk of them.'' Last year, <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> reserved 4,800 visas for wealthy immigrants from <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION>.
