<HEAD>Embarrassed Arkansas Lawmakers Scramble to Avert Fiscal Crisis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SCOTT CHARTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LITTLE ROCK, Ark. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Red-faced legislators met in an emergency special session Wednesday to re-pass hundreds of spending bills that were ruled invalid because the <ORGANIZATION> Legislature </ORGANIZATION> violated a requirement in the state's constitution. Virtually all state spending will halt July 1, when <LOCATION> Arkansas </LOCATION>' fiscal biennium begins, unless the legislators approve nearly 300 appropriations bills all over again `` I am embarrassed,'' veteran state Rep. <PERSON> Jodie </PERSON> <PERSON> Mahony </PERSON> said of the procedural snafu during the regular session, which ended in April. `` But it is an honest mistake.'' The special session convened late Tuesday, one day after a specially appointed <ORGANIZATION> Arkansas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> ruled that the General Appropriation Act did not pass with a three-fourths majority as required by the state's 115-year-old constitution. Since the General Appropriation Act must be passed before any other spending bills may be enacted, the ruling meant the state had not authorized a spending blueprint. `` The fact that our state constitution is an amalgamation of anachronisms is no justification to ignore it,'' <ORGANIZATION> Arkansas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Gazette </ORGANIZATION> columnist <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Brummett </PERSON> wrote Wednesday. During the regular legislative session, the general appropriation bill got a 65-22 vote in the 100-member <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>, and a 25-9 vote in the 35-member <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>, where 27 votes equals three-fourths. The <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>, and later a <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rules </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, decided that the general appropriation bill fell under the category of `` just debts,'' which the constitution says is exempt from the three-quarters rule. A Little Rock attorney, <PERSON> Sam </PERSON> <PERSON> Perroni </PERSON>, then filed a friendly lawsuit challenging the General Appropriation Act's validity. When a <LOCATION> Pulaski </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> chancellor rejected the `` just debts'' argument in ruling the appropriation act invalid, the issue went to the state <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>. However, the seven justices recused themselves, citing a possible conflict of interest because the legislature appropriates funds for the high court. A special seven-member <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> was appointed that also rejected the `` just debts'' argument, so on Monday night, Gov. <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Clinton </PERSON>'s staff began rounding up lawmakers to return to <LOCATION> Little </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rock </LOCATION>. The only legislators missing from the special session were a <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> member who was sick and another who was out of the country. The constitution requires that all special sessions meet for at least three days, and <PERSON> Clinton </PERSON> said he hoped lawmakers could wrap up things Thursday or Friday. To show his desire for no-nonsense action, <PERSON> Clinton </PERSON> decided against an opening speech for the session, which is costing taxpayers an estimated $ 20,000 a day. `` I want to do it as quickly as possible, keep it to this agenda and finish,'' the governor said. Once in session, lawmakers hastily assigned bill numbers and gave the familiar items two readings, dispatching them to the <ORGANIZATION> Joint </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Budget </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, where the panel's co-chairman, Rep. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Miller </PERSON>, pressured colleagues to grind out all spending bills in a two-hour sitting. `` Understand, this is a re-hash, the same thing, and all of us know what we have done,'' <PERSON> Miller </PERSON> said. `` We're showing we're not derelict in our duties.'' `` It's just unfortunate we are not as good constitutional lawyers as the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>,'' said Rep. <PERSON> Mike </PERSON> <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON>, a lawyer. `` But I know there was a general good faith belief that it was properly passed.'' The court ruling also invalidated an unpopular $ 119 million, 10-year settlement of state liability in desegregation lawsuits surrounding schools in <LOCATION> Little </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rock </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Pulaski </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>. The settlement passed by a narrow margin the first time around, and opponents say they wo n't let it pass again. Sen. <PERSON> Stanley </PERSON> <PERSON> Russ </PERSON>, a member of the <ORGANIZATION> Joint </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Budget </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, which recommended the settlement bill for passage Wednesday, predicted the bill would pass the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> but die in the House.
