<HEAD>Bush Meets with Lawmakers on Steel Import Issue</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF BARKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Opponents of steel import restraints told President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> on Wednesday that he should not feel bound by a campaign pledge to renew the trade barriers. `` -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> Winston </ORGANIZATION> -RRB- <PERSON> Churchill </PERSON> used to say, ` I'd rather be right than be consistent,' and I reminded the president of that,'' Sen. <PERSON> Phil </PERSON> <PERSON> Gramm </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Texas </LOCATION>, told reporters after the meeting at the White House regarding the import curbs that expire Sept. 30. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> met privately with lawmakers who favor extending the trade program and with <PERSON> Gramm </PERSON> and others who are urging it be dropped. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> `` tipped his hand in no direction whatsoever,'' said Sen. <PERSON> Jay </PERSON> <PERSON> Rockefeller </PERSON>, D-W. <LOCATION> Va. </LOCATION>, chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Steel </ORGANIZATION> The <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration negotiated five-year, product-by-product `` voluntary restraint agreements'' in 1984 with <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Community </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION> and other nations to limit the flow of foreign steel into the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. Three days before last November's election, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> wrote a letter to Sen. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Heinz </PERSON>, R-Pa., pledging to renew the program in some form But with the steel industry newly profitable, opponents of the curbs say they can make a case for <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> to end the barriers or at least narrow their scope. `` We'd like to think his normal inclination would be on the side of fewer barriers,'' Sen. <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Packwood </PERSON>, R-Ore., told reporters after the meeting `` What he's going to do with that statement that he made in <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION> toward the end of the campaign, I do n't know. But I suppose I could live with a compromise.'' `` Everything is different than it was in 1984,'' <PERSON> Gramm </PERSON> said. `` The industry is operating at 96 percent of capacity, steel prices are rising very rapidly now, especially for the smaller fabricators who do not have long-term agreements with the domestic steel industry. The steel industry is profitable.'' Advocates of continuing the program argue that steel price hikes have been caused not by import barriers but by strong worldwide demand and shifting exchange rates. The trade conditions that spawned the restraint program still exist, <ORGANIZATION> Rockefeller </ORGANIZATION> said. `` America is playing by the right rules and everybody else is playing by protectionism, and we get hurt,'' <PERSON> Rockefeller </PERSON> said. He said the program must be extended `` so the steel industry can complete about another $ 10 billion of modernization that they have to complete in order to be competitive with the rest of world, which is already subsidizing and dumping in <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>.'' The administration has not said when a decision will be made, but <PERSON> Heinz </PERSON> said he expected something in the next several weeks. <PERSON> Heinz </PERSON> and <PERSON> Rockefeller </PERSON> said they attended the meeting on behalf of steel companies and steelworkers pressing for a five-year renewal of the program.
