<FIRST>r a AM-SubAccident     06-21 0233</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sub Accident,0239</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sub's Sonar Sub Didn't Spot Tugboat, Investigator Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONG BEACH, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A nuclear submarine that snagged a towing cable and dragged a tugboat under, killing a deckhand, had failed to detect the 97-ton vessel by sonar, a federal investigator says. The analysis by <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Safety </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> investigator <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> Tyrell </PERSON> is based on interviews with the crew of the USS <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION> after the accident June 14. <PERSON> Tyrell </PERSON>, in an interview in Wednesday's <LOCATION> Long </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Beach </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Press-Telegram </LOCATION>, said the tug's engine noises may have been masked by the sounds of larger ships in the area, or the sub may have been in a spot where it could n't pick up the tug's sounds. Requests for <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> comment were referred to Lt. <PERSON> Sonja </PERSON> <PERSON> Hedley </PERSON> at the sub's home port in <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Diego </LOCATION>, and she was n't immediately available. According to <PERSON> Tyrell </PERSON>, the 360-foot sub was relying on `` passive'' sonar, which allows tracking of vessels by engine and other noises. This is normal for military subs, <PERSON> Tyrell </PERSON> said, noting that active sonar, which emits `` pings'' that bounce back and locate vessels more accurately, give away a sub's position. The <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION> snagged the submerged cable linking the 73-foot tug to two barges. Two crewmen swam to safety in the early-morning fog, but a deckhand was lost. Shortly before the accident, the sub had helped in filming of the movie `` The Hunt for Red October.''
