<HEAD>Prepare New Drive for Wayne Williams in Atlanta Murders</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOSEPH B. FRAZIER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Nearly a decade after the first of the `` child murder'' victims was found, lawyers for <PERSON> Wayne </PERSON> <PERSON> Williams </PERSON> are headed back to court to try to show that the <PERSON> Ku </PERSON> <PERSON> Klux </PERSON> <PERSON> Klan </PERSON>, not <PERSON> Williams </PERSON>, was responsible for the deaths. From July 1979 to May 1981, 29 poor, generally street-wise young blacks were found killed in and around <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION>. One other is missing. <PERSON> Williams </PERSON>, now 30, was convicted in 1982 of two of the deaths and is serving two life sentences. Authorities attributed 22 other killings to him. The other cases remain classified as unsolved. <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> civil rights lawyer <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Kuntsler </PERSON> said he and others working on <PERSON> Williams </PERSON>' case will meet Tuesday in <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> to organize what he called `` the final thrust'' of their appeal and to request a new evidentiary hearing. `` We've been collecting more and more information, all of which points to <PERSON> Wayne </PERSON>'s innocence,'' he said Wednesday from his <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> office. The prosecution has contended since <PERSON> Williams </PERSON> was convicted that the evidence points to him and to nobody else. But doubt has remained in the minds of many, including the parents of some victims, over whether <PERSON> Williams </PERSON> was behind all of the killings or acted alone. The <ORGANIZATION> Georgia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> unanimously rejected an initial appeal of <PERSON> Williams </PERSON>' conviction in 1983 and later voted 6-1 not to reconsider. In November 1985, <PERSON> Kuntsler </PERSON> and others on the defense team appealed in <ORGANIZATION> Butts </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> County </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Superior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Jackson </LOCATION>, where <PERSON> Williams </PERSON> is imprisoned, claiming authorities withheld vital information from the defense that might have exonerated the former freelance photographer and music promoter. Since then, the case has remained dormant while defense attorneys sought information to support their contention. `` What we have put together is the fact that there was a meeting in the governor's office in which it was decided that they could not charge a white Klan member without causing a race riot,'' <PERSON> Kuntsler </PERSON> contended. `` <PERSON> Wayne </PERSON> became the fall guy. Everything we have sustains that.'' <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Busbee </PERSON> was governor at the time. His secretary said he could not immediately comment Wednesday because he was in meetings. <PERSON> Kuntsler </PERSON> said investigators have amassed more than 300 pages of new evidence that points away from <ORGANIZATION> Williams </ORGANIZATION>. `` We have as much as we're going to get,'' he said. `` We're going to reopen this case and get <PERSON> Wayne </PERSON> out of there and go after the Klan.'' Among evidence withheld, he contends, are wiretap recordings in which Klan members admit `` that they did it and they boasted about it.'' <PERSON> Lewis </PERSON> <PERSON> Slaton </PERSON>, district attorney for <LOCATION> Fulton </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> where most of the killings took place, said he was aware of `` nothing new'' in the case and added that the move appears to be a continuation of the appeal previously filed. <PERSON> Williams </PERSON> was convicted largely on the basis of fibers found on the victims that could be traced to the <PERSON> Williams </PERSON> household carpet, <PERSON> Williams </PERSON>' bedspread, his dog and other sources. Prosecution witnesses testified that the odds of random duplication of that combination of fibers were 150 million to one. <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Drolet </PERSON> of the <LOCATION> Fulton </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> district attorney's office, who prosecuted the case, said fiber evidence linked <PERSON> Williams </PERSON> to about 20 of the cases and the same fiber combination has not been found on a murder victim since <PERSON> Williams </PERSON> was arrested. Some victims were found in rivers or on river banks and were washed clean of evidence, he said.
