<HEAD>Young Americans Urged to Help Rescue Those ``Free Falling Through
Society''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CONNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, in a clarion call to community service, urged young Americans on Wednesday to help rescue millions of homeless, poor and other needy people who are `` free falling through society.'' `` I need your help. ... <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> needs your help,'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> told more than 3,000 teen-agers and children on the White House lawn. `` It is a time of need for millions of Americans,'' said <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>. `` Too many people are free falling through society with no prospect of landing on their feet. `` No one _ young, old, white, brown or black _ should be permitted to go through life unclaimed,'' said <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>. `` You must show us how to reclaim these lives.'' He made his appeal as part of his Youth Engaged in Service -LRB- YES -RRB- to <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> drive to muster support for community service. In <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> on Thursday, he will unveil details of a wider national service initiative `` to encourage volunteers of all ages, all backgrounds, all abilities,'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said. Aides said <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> would urge virtually every institution in society to give a new push to volunteerism. But on this steamy morning, he aimed his message at the young, from 5 to 25, saying all had something to give. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> invoked the image of the bell in the church steeple that in `` a simpler time'' summoned neighbors to help. `` When people heard that bell, they did n't stop to ask why it was ringing, they just came, -LRB- on -RRB- horseback or foot, by buggy or bicycle, honking the horn of a Model T, they just came,'' said the president. `` Whatever the problem, whoever was in need of help, they were ready.'' `` The bells have been silent too long,'' he said. `` Let them ring in your hearts and across the land.'' `` Commit yourselves. Listen to the bells. Make it your mission to make a difference in somebody else's life,'' he said. `` All of you have something to offer _ kids from tough neighborhoods, kids from broken homes, kids who have grown up on food stamps and hand-me-downs. ... You each have a gift that <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> needs,'' he said. His remarks hit a receptive chord in the audience, invited from Boy Scout troops, church groups, schools and other organizations already engaged in service. `` He's preaching to the converted in my case,'' said <PERSON> Alexandra </PERSON> <PERSON> Warren </PERSON>, 19, of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hope </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Pa. </LOCATION>, who is spending this summer as a volunteer for Common Cause before her junior year at <ORGANIZATION> Haverford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION>. Service `` is part of the Quaker ethos at <LOCATION> Haverford </LOCATION>,'' she said. <PERSON> Shaka </PERSON> <PERSON> Brown </PERSON>, 12, a Boy Scout from <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> D.C. </LOCATION>, said, `` I just helped somebody a little while ago. A young lady lost her nametag.'' He helped her find it on the soggy and packed White House lawn. As presidents in time of war called for young people to defend <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said he was urging them to fight poverty, homelessness and other ills. He told <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> in February he will seek $ 100 million over four years to endow a YES foundation to provide matching grants for community service projects. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said young people could find meaning and adventure in community service. He listed sad statistics about <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s youth _ 1,700 drop out of school, 4,000 run away from home and 2,700 become pregnant daily _ but he insisted: `` You're not the problem. You are the solution.'' `` You do n't need to be bribed with incentives and threatened with penalties to get engaged in community service,'' he said. `` Service is its own reward, satisfaction guaranteed.'' `` He wants to save money,'' said <PERSON> June </PERSON> <PERSON> Shih </PERSON>, 17, of <ORGANIZATION> St. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agnes </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Alexandria </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Va. </LOCATION>, where the girls are required to perform 40 hours of community service before senior year. `` It's good, the 1,000 points of light and everything,'' said <PERSON> Shih </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cross </ORGANIZATION> volunteer. `` <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s in the red. He has to find some way to help the less-fortunate without straining the budget.''
