<HEAD>Authorities Refuse to Fire Policeman Accused of Intimidation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HEIDI VON EGIDY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WINDHOEK, Namibia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Namibia </LOCATION>'s administrator Wednesday refused to dismiss paramilitary policemen who have been accused of intimidating civilians and jeopardizing independence elections in the territory. South African Administrator <PERSON> Louis </PERSON> <PERSON> Pienaar </PERSON> told a news conference he will allow members of the recently disbanded <ORGANIZATION> Koevoet </ORGANIZATION> counterinsurgency unit to remain in the regular police force. Members of <ORGANIZATION> Koevoet </ORGANIZATION>, which means `` crowbar'' in <LOCATION> Afrikaans </LOCATION>, wore military uniforms and traveled the <PERSON> bush </PERSON> in armored personnel carriers. They are known for often brutal tactics against supporters and guerrillas of the <ORGANIZATION> South-West </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Africa </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION>, which has fought 23 years to end South African rule of <LOCATION> Namibia </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Koevoet </PERSON> was made up mostly of black Namibians led by white South Africans. <LOCATION> Pretoria </LOCATION>, which has ruled <LOCATION> Namibia </LOCATION> for 74 years, has agreed to a yearlong transition to independence supervised by more than 4,000 <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> monitors. Both the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> South-West </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Africa </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> accuse ex-Koevoet members of continuing to harass civilians since their January integration into the regular police force `` Their activities appear to have createad an atmosphere of fear and intimidation among much of the population in the northern region,'' <PERSON> Martti </PERSON> <PERSON> Ahtisaari </PERSON>, the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> special representative to <LOCATION> Namibia </LOCATION>, said in a June 9 letter to <PERSON> Pienaar </PERSON>. `` In my opinion, -LRB- they are -RRB- unfit for continued service in the police during the transition period in view of the need to ensure the necessary conditions for free and fair elecations,'' the letter said. <PERSON> Pienaar </PERSON> said he has reports guerrillas are storing arms caches in northern <LOCATION> Namibia </LOCATION> and he can not afford to reduce the police strength. `` We feel obliged to maintain a state of alertness, commensurate with a potential threat to the security of the region,'' he said. `` I reject the possibility that men should be removed from the police just because they have been members of the counterinsurgency unit.'' He emphasized he would dismiss individuals found guilty of misconduct. <PERSON> Ahtisaari </PERSON> and <PERSON> Pienaar </PERSON> met Wednesday to discuss the intimidation charges and plan more talks, officials said. In other developments, <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> officials said 5,621 Namibian exiles have been flown home since they began a repatriation campaign 10 days ago. The <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> has registered more than 41,000 Namibian refugees at camps in neighboring <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Zambia </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Botswana </LOCATION> and wants to bring back 1,000 a day for six weeks. <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> agreed to grant <LOCATION> Namibia </LOCATION> independence in exchange for the withdrawal of 50,000 Cuban troops helping <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION>'s government fight U.S.-backed rebels.
