<HEAD>Rebel Leader: Summit Will Fail Without Rebel-Gov't Talks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAURINDA KEYS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOA ESPERANCA, Angola (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Rebel leader <PERSON> Jonas </PERSON> <PERSON> Savimbi </PERSON> said Wednesday an African summit aimed at resolving the Angolan civil war will fail unless direct talks begin between the rebels and the government. But he told a news conference at his bush camp that `` never in 14 years of war have we come so close'' to peace. <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION>'s official news agency announced Wednesday the government released 700 rebel prisoners. The dispatch said the prisoners were released June 2 and reported the prisoners had renounced the rebel movement and accepted the government's offer of clemency. The announcement came on the eve of a meeting of African leaders in <LOCATION> Gbadolite </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Zaire </LOCATION>. The meeting could clear the way for direct peace talks between <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION>'s Marxist government and the rebel <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> for the Total Independence of <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Savimbi </PERSON> said his delegation in <LOCATION> Zaire </LOCATION> was willing to be flexible about procedures leading to elections and formation of a national unity government. But, he said, the rebels would reject any amnesty or clemency for the guerrillas. `` Our army, 75,000 men in the field, will not accept amnesty, clemency or integration'' into the ruling <ORGANIZATION> Popular </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Movement </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> the </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Angola </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Savimbi </PERSON> said. `` That wording has a political context that means -LRB- the rebel army -RRB- is considered criminal. Our army was not defeated and is not going to be defeated.'' <PERSON> Savimbi </PERSON> said he has agreed to stay out of the negotiations and will not demand a role in any transitional government. But he said he would remain the head of his party. He also wants to participate in free elections he anticipates within two years of a formal cease-fire. He dismissed reports he might go into exile, saying he would remain in <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION> after a cease-fire, but not necessarily in his southeastern stronghold of <LOCATION> Jamba </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION>'s government has rejected elections, insisting on maintaining one-party rule and offering some rebels positions in the administration. The Angolan news service <ORGANIZATION> ANGOP </ORGANIZATION> said Wednesday that President <PERSON> Jose </PERSON> <PERSON> Eduardo </PERSON> <PERSON> dos </PERSON> <PERSON> Santos </PERSON>' has a peace plan calling for <PERSON> Savimbi </PERSON> to go abroad, recognize the legitimacy of the government and for the rebel movement to be integrated into the one-party state. <PERSON> Savimbi </PERSON> vehemently vetoed all these proposals at his news conference. <PERSON> Savimbi </PERSON> said the Angolan government was under pressure, because within six months, half of the 50,000 Cuban soldiers who have supported it will have left <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION> under a U.S.-mediated southern African peace agreement reached in December. The Cubans have agreed to a gradual withdrawal, to be completed by July 1991. But <PERSON> Savimbi </PERSON> said the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> have promised to `` help the Cubans leave quickly'' if the peace talks lead to formation of a transitional unity government before then. The U.S.-backed rebels have been fighting a guerrilla war to force the <LOCATION> Cuban </LOCATION> - and Soviet-assisted government to share power since shortly after <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION> gained independence from <LOCATION> Portugal </LOCATION> in 1975 <PERSON> Savimbi </PERSON> praised Zairean President <PERSON> Mobutu </PERSON> <PERSON> Sese </PERSON> <PERSON> Seko </PERSON> for organizing the summit, expected to be attended by leaders from <LOCATION> Zaire </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mozambique </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Cape </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Verde </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Guinea-Bissau </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Sao </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Tome </LOCATION> e Principe, <LOCATION> Botswana </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Zambia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Zimbabwe </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Gabon </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ivory </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Coast </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Tanzania </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Congo </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Mali </LOCATION>. According to news reports in <LOCATION> Portugal </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Savimbi </PERSON> might also travel to <LOCATION> Zaire </LOCATION> to participate in the indirect talks. <PERSON> Savimbi </PERSON> was preparing to fly out of <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION> after the news conference Wednesday but did not say where he was going. At the request of <LOCATION> Ivory </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Coast </LOCATION> President <PERSON> Felix </PERSON> <PERSON> Houphouet-Boigny </PERSON>, the rebels have declared a `` de facto'' cease-fire and are conducting only defensive operations. He said the government army is still attacking, `` trying to capture prisoners for their amnesty,'' but with much less intensity than in the past.
