<HEAD>Bush Administration Raises Possibility of Child Care Veto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Labor Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration on Wednesday raised the prospect that a child-care package being pushed by the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> leadership would be vetoed and Republicans sought support for an alternative the White House supports The specter of a veto was raised in an administration policy statement distributed on <LOCATION> Capitol </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hill </LOCATION> as the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> debated the issue for a fifth day. At the <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>, however, a spokesman said President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> still hoped to reach agreement with <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> on a plan. In the three-page policy statement, the administration said the child-care package being advocated by <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> leaders with the help of one leading <ORGANIZATION> GOP </ORGANIZATION> senator, <PERSON> Orrin </PERSON> <PERSON> Hatch </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Utah </LOCATION>, `` is fundamentally flawed'' and that if it reached the White House <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s `` senior advisers would recommend that he veto it. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> spokesman <PERSON> Marlin </PERSON> <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> was less direct when asked whether <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> would veto the legislation if it clears <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> as it stands now. <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> said the administration believed its tax credit proposal was the best approach to helping low-income parents pay for child care but was `` willing to talk about alternatives and how this could be approved.'' The legislation before the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> is a revised version of the Act for Better Child Care sponsored by <PERSON> Hatch </PERSON> and Sen. <PERSON> Christopher </PERSON> <PERSON> Dodd </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Conn </LOCATION>. It authorizes $ 1.75 billion to be spent on child care in fiscal 1990 through subsidies to parents and states to help pay for child care and expand its availability. States would be required to give 70 percent of the money directly to low-income families for child care expenses, with the rest used to fund and administer state programs designed to improve the quality and quantity of child care. Tacked on to the measure is a package of tax credits designed to help parents offset the costs of child care and health insurance. Those credits, endorsed by the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Finance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, are similar to the credits at the heart of the alternative package being offered by <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> Republican leader <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Dole </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION> with the support of the White House. But <PERSON> Dole </PERSON> and other <ORGANIZATION> GOP </ORGANIZATION> lawmakers have virtually ignored the tax-credit provisions of the revised Dodd-Hatch plan and focused their attacks on the subsidy provisions of the measure, which they contend give too much control of the money to state governments and not enough to parents. The alternative Republican plan includes an expansion of the existing earned-income tax credit for parents with children under age 5 and a proposal to provide money up front to low-income families who can not take advantage of the dependent-care credit because their incomes are so low they do not pay taxes. The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> is scheduled to vote Thursday on whether to kill the Democratic leadership plan in favor of the <ORGANIZATION> GOP </ORGANIZATION> approach. Republicans have been lobbying Southern Democrats in hope of winning enough support for their package, but the Democratic leadership says it has the votes to quash the <ORGANIZATION> GOP </ORGANIZATION> effort.
