<HEAD>Key Burmese Opposition Leader Arrested, Released</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RANGOON, Burma (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Burma </LOCATION>'s main opposition leader and 15 supporters were detained Wednesday during a ceremony to honor people slain last year during a military crackdown on pro-democracy demonstrators, official sources said. The sources said <PERSON> Aung </PERSON> <PERSON> San </PERSON> <PERSON> Suu </PERSON> <PERSON> Kyi </PERSON> and her followers were interrogated for about an hour and then released. They spoke on condition of anonymity. No official statement was made about the incident at <LOCATION> Myeinigon </LOCATION>, four miles north of downtown <LOCATION> Rangoon </LOCATION>. In <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> deputy spokesman <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Boucher </PERSON> said the incident would be a `` grave blow to hopes that next year's election will be free and fair. <PERSON> Boucher </PERSON> said the administration has noted with concern the <LOCATION> Burmese </LOCATION> government's restrictions on political activity, including a ban on gatherings of five or more people, prohibition of opposition publications and harassment and arrest of opposition party leaders. <PERSON> Aung </PERSON> <PERSON> San </PERSON> <PERSON> Suu </PERSON> <PERSON> Kyi </PERSON> is the daughter of deceased national hero Gen. <PERSON> Aung </PERSON> <PERSON> San </PERSON>. A 44-year-old political neophyte, she is widely regarded as the most powerful opposition figure in <LOCATION> Burma </LOCATION>. Her party appears to have the biggest backing among the more than 200 that have mushroomed since last year's pro-democracy movement. She held a religious ceremony with her followers at a branch office of her National League for Democracy and then walked to the spot where several demonstrators were shot by police last June 21. Several hundred people were present at the wreath-laying when authorities moved in. Witnesses said <PERSON> Aung </PERSON> <PERSON> San </PERSON> <PERSON> Suu </PERSON> <PERSON> Kyi </PERSON> and the others were taken away in open military trucks to a government office near where the ceremony took place. In recent months, <LOCATION> Aung </LOCATION> <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Suu </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kyi </LOCATION> has been harassed on occasion but generally been given considerable leeway by the military government to campaign throughout the country. She returned to <LOCATION> Rangoon </LOCATION> from <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, her home for many years, to look after her ailing mother in April 1988, and became embroiled in political turmoil sweeping <LOCATION> Burma </LOCATION> at the time. She became one of the main leaders of a pro-democracy uprising that seemed on the verge of toppling 26 years of authoritarian rule through massive street demonstrations. But in September, Gen. Saw <PERSON> Maung </PERSON> and a group of military officers brutally crushed the student-led protests and clamped martial law on the country. The new leaders allowed the formation of opposition political parties and have promised free general elections next year. <PERSON> Aung </PERSON> <PERSON> San </PERSON> <PERSON> Suu </PERSON> <PERSON> Kyi </PERSON> joined with two popular leaders, retired Brig. Gen. <PERSON> Aung </PERSON> <PERSON> Gyi </PERSON> and former Defense Minister Tin Oo, to form the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> League </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democracy </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Aung </PERSON> <PERSON> Gyi </PERSON> later left the group, claiming the league was being infiltrated by communists.
