<HEAD>Former Chief Justice, Speaker Brought Down By Mob Ties</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN FLIPPEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PROVIDENCE, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Bevilacqua </PERSON>, whose lifelong friendships with reputed mobsters tarnished and eventually ended his career as <LOCATION> Rhode </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION>'s top legislator and top judge, died Wednesday. He was 70. <PERSON> Bevilacqua </PERSON> died at <LOCATION> Brigham </LOCATION> and Women's Hospital in <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION>. No further information was immediately available, said hospital spokeswoman <PERSON> Brenda </PERSON> <PERSON> Buratti </PERSON>. He had been hospitalized several times during the last few months in <LOCATION> Providence </LOCATION>, most recently in early May for a heart attack. He was taken to <LOCATION> Brigham </LOCATION> and Women's on May 30 when he complained of problems with his medication, relatives said. <PERSON> Bevilacqua </PERSON> was elected to the <LOCATION> Rhode </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION> <LOCATION> House </LOCATION> in 1954 and maintained a successful criminal law practice while he rose through the ranks to become majority leader in 1966 and speaker in 1969. Questions about his ties to criminals came into the open when the <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION> elected him chief justice of the state <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> in 1976. Among them were allegations that <PERSON> Bevilacqua </PERSON> had harbored a fugitive from a 1963 department store robbery and accepted $ 2,000 of the loot from him. The fugitive, <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Northrop </PERSON>, later recanted his story. Then-Attorney General <PERSON> Julius </PERSON> <PERSON> Michaelson </PERSON> investigated the matter in 1977 but concluded there was `` no prosecutable case.'' At about the same time, a letter surfaced in which <PERSON> Bevilacqua </PERSON> told the state <ORGANIZATION> Parole </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> in 1973 that <PERSON>