 the matter, <PERSON> Bevilacqua </PERSON> resigned. In February 1987, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Attorney <PERSON> Lincoln </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Almond </PERSON> confirmed that <PERSON> Bevilacqua </PERSON>'s personal finances were under investigation. At the time <PERSON> Bevilacqua </PERSON> stepped down, the impeachment hearings had begun to focus on his personal finances, which he handled in cash and through third parties. He is survived by his wife, two sons and daughter. Funeral plans were incomplete.
