<HEAD>Killer Dies in Gas Chamber</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JACK ELLIOTT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARCHMAN, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A robber who shot a convenience store clerk to death was executed Wednesday in <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION>'s gas chamber, insisting to the last that he was convicted unfairly because of racial discrimination. A doctor at the <ORGANIZATION> Mississippi </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Penitentiary </ORGANIZATION> at <LOCATION> Parchman </LOCATION> said <PERSON> Leo </PERSON> <PERSON> Edwards </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, 36, of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Orleans </LOCATION> was heavily sedated at his own request. But the lethal fumes awakened him and he cried out and gasped before he died at 12:15 a.m. <PERSON> Edwards </PERSON> was the fourth person executed at the <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> penitentiary and the 113th in the nation since the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> reinstated the death penalty in 1976. He was executed for the shooting death of <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> convenience store clerk <PERSON> Linzy </PERSON> <PERSON> Don </PERSON> <PERSON> Dixon </PERSON> in a June 14, 1980, robbery that netted $ 111. <PERSON> Dixon </PERSON> was shot while he talked on the telephone. <PERSON> Edwards </PERSON>, who was black, was convicted by an all-white <ORGANIZATION> Hinds </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> County </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> jury and was sentenced to death April 1, 1981. Defense attorneys protested that prosecutors deliberately excluded blacks from the jury, but four appeals courts disagreed. <PERSON> Edwards </PERSON> maintained again in a <LOCATION> Memphis </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Tenn. </LOCATION>, newspaper interview published Tuesday that he did not receive a fair trial, recalling that when he saw the all-white jury he said, `` I'm dead.'' Late Tuesday, Gov. <PERSON> Ray </PERSON> <PERSON> Mabus </PERSON> rejected a plea for clemency. `` I will not stand in the way of the courts' justice. ... <PERSON> Leo </PERSON> <PERSON> Edwards </PERSON> is a mass murderer who killed in cold blood,'' <PERSON> Mabus </PERSON> said. `` He tried and failed to get relief in 16 appeals to the courts, and discrimination had no bearing in his case.'' The <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> refused, in a 7-2 vote, to delay the execution on procedural grounds. <PERSON> Dixon </PERSON>, who also was black, was killed during a five-day robbery spree by <PERSON> Edwards </PERSON> and co-defendant <PERSON> Mike </PERSON> <PERSON> White </PERSON> that left three people dead and one wounded. White, who got three life terms, testified that <PERSON> Edwards </PERSON> told him he had shot the store clerk to avoid being identified later. Before his execution, family members including his mother and daughter spent most of the day with <PERSON> Edwards </PERSON>. He also talked with a priest.
