<HEAD>Criminal Charges Dropped Against Interns Who Went on Strike</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HARARE, Zimbabwe (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Authorities said Wednesday they have dropped criminal charges against medical interns arrested during a four-day strike last week. The decision was made `` in the public interest'' and to smooth the way for a settlement of grievances, according to a government statement. Several hundred striking interns at state hospitals and clinics stayed off the job to demand a review of salaries and working conditions. More than 70 were detained by police June 14 on charges they violated laws barring those working in essential services from going on strike. The strikers spent a night in jail but were then released and ordered to appear in court June 29 and July 19. The crimes with which they were charged carry a maximum sentence of 10 years in jail. There were no reports of deaths of patients during the strike. The stoppage ended after the government promised to settle grievances in the state health service. Health minister <PERSON> Felix </PERSON> <PERSON> Muchemwa </PERSON> said salaries will be raised and their compulsory attachment to state health facilities will be reduced from five years to three years. Interns earn a monthly income of about $ 300. <PERSON> Muchemwa </PERSON> did not release details of the pay offer. <PERSON> Andrew </PERSON> <PERSON> Cakana </PERSON>, leader of the <ORGANIZATION> Hospital </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Doctors </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ' </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, said Wednesday his organization was reserving its comments until interns have studied the offer.
