<HEAD>Job Service Employees Suspended Following Discrimination Check</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. PAUL, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Ten employees of a state job service agency have been suspended for a month without pay for agreeing to requests to provide only white male applicants for certain job openings, officials said. Such actions are `` totally in violation of anything this department is about,'' said state Jobs and Training Commissioner <PERSON> Joe </PERSON> <PERSON> Samargia </PERSON>, whose department oversees the job service offices. The suspensions announced Tuesday came after an investigation by the state <ORGANIZATION> Human </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rights </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>, which made tape-recorded phone calls to state employment offices in April and May. In the calls, job applicants were requested for a fictitious employer. `` They were told, ` We do n't want any females and we do n't want any minorities _ we just want white males,''' said state Human Rights Commissioner <PERSON> Stephen </PERSON> <PERSON> Cooper </PERSON>. `` We made 12 different calls and 10 came up bad and two came up good.'' After the findings, the state <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Jobs </ORGANIZATION> and Training and the <ORGANIZATION> Human </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rights </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> reached agreement on training and rules to ensure that discriminatory job orders are n't accepted in the future. `` We were going to file some charges, but they were willing to work with us so we did n't need to,'' <PERSON> Cooper </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Samargia </PERSON> said the 10 job service interviewers were suspended last week. Reconstructing one conversation, <PERSON> Samargia </PERSON> said a job service worker told the undercover caller that the discriminatory order could not be accepted as offered but that the order would be handled as the caller desired. `` If <PERSON> St. </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> found out, I'd be in trouble,'' the employee said, according to <LOCATION> Samargia </LOCATION>. An official of the <ORGANIZATION> Minnesota </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Professional </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Employees </ORGANIZATION>, a union representing nine of the suspended employees, said it is contesting the suspensions. `` They were totally inappropriate,'' said union president <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> LeWon </PERSON>, contending that the department provided little, if any training for employees on how to handle such matters. <PERSON> Samargia </PERSON> insisted, `` We've had training on this.''
