<HEAD>Baryshnikov to Leave American Ballet Theatre Post</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> Baryshnikov </PERSON>, artistic director of the American Ballet Theatre for nine years, will step down at the end of the 1990 season, the company's board of trustees announced Wednesday. The board learned Tuesday night of his decision to leave, said <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Pontarelli </PERSON>, the company's director of public relations. `` I would say this is a surprise. It was unexpected,'' he said. <PERSON> Baryshnikov </PERSON>, 41, became ABT's artistic director in September 1980. He joined the company in 1974 after defecting from the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, where he danced with the Kirov ballet company. `` I will have given 10 years to the company, and it has been a true challenge,'' he said. `` The dancers in the company are superb. Of all the responsibilities associated with being artistic director, I've enjoyed working with the dancers more than anything else.'' <PERSON> Baryshnikov </PERSON> said he would `` pursue other professional options'' but did not elaborate. He is starring on Broadway in `` Metamorphosis,'' a play based on <PERSON> Franz </PERSON> <PERSON> Kafka </PERSON>'s story, and has appeared in such films as `` White Nights'' and `` The Turning Point.'' He also recently launched a perfume for women called `` Misha,'' his nickname. A search committee will be formed to find a successor, <PERSON> Pontarelli </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Melville </PERSON> <PERSON> Straus </PERSON>, chairman of the board of the <ORGANIZATION> Ballet </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Theatre </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foundation </ORGANIZATION>, said in a statement: `` <PERSON> Misha </PERSON> has brought <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ballet </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Theatre </ORGANIZATION> into a new era and has set a standard of excellence by which the company will be measured in years to come.''
