<HEAD>Energy Official Says Power Shortages are Looming</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BURNS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The nation soon may face a shortage of electricity, a senior <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> official said Wednesday in comments reflecting a <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration campaign to convince the public of a need for more nuclear power plants. `` The demand for electricity in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> is growing beyond our ability to provide additional generating capacity,'' said <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Tuck </PERSON>, the undersecretary of energy. He noted that electricity accounts for 37 percent of total <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> energy use. Tuck said it was `` inescapable'' that many more power plants will be needed if the economy is to continue to grow at a reasonable rate, adding that utilities have balked at such construction because of the high cost and lack of public support. No new nuclear plants have been ordered in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> since 1978. `` Considering all these factors, it is apparent that the nation may have an electricity shortage on its hands in the not-too-distant future,'' <PERSON> Tuck </PERSON> said in remarks to an industry-sponsored symposium on nuclear reactors and <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> energy security. Tuck cited the case of <LOCATION> Long </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Shoreham </LOCATION> nuclear power station, which <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> state is planning to dismantle even though it recently gained a license to operate. The <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> is trying to block the move, arguing that <LOCATION> Shoreham </LOCATION> is needed as a regional energy source and a national symbol of nuclear power's future Tuck said the <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> is eager to complete research and development on several new types of nuclear reactors designed to be safer and more reliable than the light-water reactors that have been used in this country since the 1950s. `` We at the <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> believe that nuclear energy, led by a new generation of advanced reactors, will have a role in averting a possible electricity shortage,'' he said. Tuck said a greater reliance on nuclear power also would help limit the nation's dependence on foreign oil, although this is disputed by many private analysts. They note that while nuclear power's only non-military role is to generate electricity, oil-fired plant produce only about 5 percent of the nation's electricity. About two-thirds of the oil is used in cars and other vehicles. Nuclear power plants generate about 20 percent of the electricity supply.
