<HEAD>AMA Endorses Federal Mandated, Employer-Provided Health Insurance</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDSEY TANNER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, for the first time in its history, endorsed Wednesday the concept of federally mandated, employer-provided health insurance. Under a proposal passed by delegates at the <ORGANIZATION> AMA </ORGANIZATION>'s annual policymaking convention, the nation's largest organization of doctors agreed to press for legislation calling for `` a phased-in requirement that employers -LRB- limited initially to larger employers -RRB- provide health-insurance coverage within the private sector for all full-time employees, with coverage expanding over several years.'' In addition, the delegates recommended `` a program of diminishing tax credits or other incentives to avoid adverse effects on employers.'' The policy adopted by the 433 members of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Delegates </ORGANIZATION> calls for the <ORGANIZATION> AMA </ORGANIZATION> to work with business groups to develop the approaches that are best suited to the needs of small employers. Such legislation would help the nation's 37 million uninsured and also would allow doctors to recover fees lost under the Medicaid program, an <ORGANIZATION> AMA </ORGANIZATION> spokesman said. Small businesses have lobbied heavily against proposals calling for any type of federally mandated employer-provided insurance, and an industry spokeswoman said they would do the same with measures like that endorsed by the <ORGANIZATION> AMA </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Marcia </PERSON> <PERSON> Bradford </PERSON>, spokeswoman for <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Small </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Business </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION>, a <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> D.C. </LOCATION> lobbying organization representing about 50,000 small businesses, said that while the <ORGANIZATION> AMA </ORGANIZATION>'s desire to include small businesses in developing national legislation is a step in the right direction, `` there's still a fundamental question of government mandates that we're opposed to.'' The <ORGANIZATION> AMA </ORGANIZATION>'s action is part of the organization's effort to combat moves to nationalize the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> health care system. A group of physicians started such an effort this year, seeking adoption of a system similar to <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>'s in which individuals and employers are taxed to pay for health coverage for all. The <ORGANIZATION> AMA </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trustees </ORGANIZATION> strongly opposes the Canadian system, in which `` all responsibility for health care payment is placed on the government.'' The <ORGANIZATION> AMA </ORGANIZATION> also opposes a move led by Sen. <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON>, D-Mass., to force employers to provide a specific package of health-insurance benefits for employees, said Dr. <PERSON> Wayne </PERSON> <PERSON> Bradley </PERSON>, the <ORGANIZATION> AMA </ORGANIZATION>'s assistant executive vice president That plan, with no gradual phase-in, `` might cause an employer not to hire an extra person, or it might cause a business to go broke,'' <PERSON> Bradley </PERSON> said. The <ORGANIZATION> AMA </ORGANIZATION> favors less drastic reforms and advocates `` the principle that employees be covered by health insurance in the workplace,'' he said. `` It's a major national problem.'' <PERSON> Bradley </PERSON> said it was the first time the <ORGANIZATION> AMA </ORGANIZATION> had endorsed the concept of federally mandated, employer-provided health insurance. In other action Wednesday, the delegates elected the first female phsyician to the <ORGANIZATION> AMA </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trustees </ORGANIZATION>, its governing body. <PERSON> Nancy </PERSON> <PERSON> Dickey </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Richmond </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>, thanked the delegates for the `` history you have just made.'' Women have been appointed in the past by other board members to student and resident trustee positions, but <PERSON> Dickey </PERSON> is the first to be elected a regular trustee by the full delegation. Dr. <PERSON> Alan </PERSON> <PERSON> Nelson </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> Salt </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lake </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> internist and president-elect for the past year, was named president of the <ORGANIZATION> AMA </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Nelson </PERSON> takes over the one-year post from Dr. <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Davis </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> Durham </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.C. </LOCATION>, surgeon. Dr. <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Tupper </PERSON>, an internist from <LOCATION> Davis </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>, was elected president-elect. Dr. <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> <PERSON> Ann </PERSON> <PERSON> Contogiannis </PERSON>, a resident physician from <LOCATION> Winston-Salem </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.C. </LOCATION>, was elected to the resident position on the <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trustees </ORGANIZATION>. Dr. <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Jacott </PERSON>, a family physician from <LOCATION> Minneapolis </LOCATION>, was elected to the Board of Trustees. Re-elected to the board were Dr. <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> B. </PERSON> <PERSON> Walker </PERSON>, a pathologist from <LOCATION> Detroit </LOCATION>, and Dr. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Ring </PERSON>, a family physician from <LOCATION> Mundelein </LOCATION>.
