<HEAD>China Ignores World Opinion in Executions</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 5th graf, ``In addition, ...'' to fix wording and to conform
to AM-China.</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-China, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERRIL JONES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s execution of three people Wednesday for burning a train during a pro-democracy protest flouted worldwide calls for mercy in the government's crackdown on political dissent. The death sentences, announced on radio and television, were carried out in <LOCATION> Shanghai </LOCATION>, where the arson incident occurred June 6. The executions came a day after President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> appealed for clemency, and <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Marlin </PERSON> <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> acknowledged that <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> had turned its back on the pleas. `` The weight of world opinion has been heavy on the shoulders of <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> and it does not appear to have made much difference,'' he said. `` History has shown that they generally are not that responsive to outside kinds of pleas.'' So far, 28 people have been condemned to death: the three who were executed, the 17 who were sentenced on Wednesday after a public trial in <LOCATION> Shandong </LOCATION> province, and eight others in <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> who were previously sentenced to death. Their crimes ranged from `` rumor-mongering'' to beating soldiers and burning vehicles. The three executed were convicted of setting fire to a train after it smashed through a barricade set up by demonstrators, killing six people. The three then beat firefighters who tried to douse the blaze, according to the <ORGANIZATION> Shanghai </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Intermediate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> on Tuesday suspended high-level U.S.-Chinese contacts and moved to block $ 1.4 billion in development loans to protest the crackdown. <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Netherlands </LOCATION> already had frozen relations and <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> has suspended new development loans. The government depends heavily on foreign investment for capital and technology, and has stressed during the past two weeks that things are back to normal in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> did not immediately respond to the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> moves, but the state-run <ORGANIZATION> Xinhua </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> said Wednesday the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> was interfering in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s affairs and that there would be no mercy. `` The 11 thugs have been sentenced to death according to <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s criminal law, because they committed heinous crimes of beating, smashing, looting and burning,'' <ORGANIZATION> Xinhua </ORGANIZATION> before the additional sentences were announced Other nations had joined the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> in urging clemency, and some denounced <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> following the executions. `` What is happening in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> is atrocious,'' Foreign Minister <PERSON> Roland </PERSON> <PERSON> Dumas </PERSON> of <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> told the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION>. `` The totalitarian machine, in all its horror, is rolling.'' Prime Minister <PERSON> Margaret </PERSON> <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> said in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> that she and Prime Minister <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Hawke </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION> were discussing steps against the Chinese government. `` The punishment is totally out of proportion to the crime,'' she said. In the <LOCATION> Hague </LOCATION>, the Dutch government said it was seized by `` disgust.'' `` This new sad fact can only lead to a further cooling of relations,'' said a statement issued by the <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION>. <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> began its crackdown on the pro-democracy movement on June 3 and has said the matter is a domestic affair. Premier <PERSON> Li </PERSON> <PERSON> Peng </PERSON> said Monday the government would spare no effort in tracking down protest organizers. The approach is not new. In a 1987 speech, senior leader <PERSON> Deng </PERSON> <PERSON> Xiaoping </PERSON> said that after widespread arrests of pro-democracy protesters 10 years ago, <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> suffered `` no discredit,'' and that `` on the contrary, the prestige of the country is steadily growing.'' <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> said the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> could not afford to turn its back on <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> even though it deplored the crackdown. `` Everyone has to recognize, first of all, that this is a country of a billion people ... a sizeable portion of the world's population that can not be closeted off and ignored,'' he said. <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> imposes the death penalty for certain violent and economic crimes but also for some political offenses, and often for crimes involving foreigners. In April a court in <LOCATION> Shanghai </LOCATION> sentenced a man to death after he was convicted of robbing the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Consulate in that city over a period of 14 months of about $ 8,900. The human rights group <ORGANIZATION> Amnesty </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> said in 1985 that 10,000 people had been executed in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> since a nationwide crackdown on crime two years earlier. Chinese officials do not release figures on executions.
