<HEAD>Rafsanjani Invites Gorbachev to Iran, Agrees on Economic Cooperation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANN IMSE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> ended nearly a decade of icy relations Wednesday when <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> speaker invited <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> to visit <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> and the two leaders agreed on wide economic cooperation. Speaker <PERSON> Hashemi </PERSON> <PERSON> Rafsanjani </PERSON> told the Soviet president that Iranians hold him in high esteem and look forward to meeting him, the official <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> news agency reported. It said <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> thanked <PERSON> Rafsanjani </PERSON> for the invitation and said frequent high-level contacts are appropraite as relations warm. No date was set. Only a handful of Third World leaders have visited <LOCATION> Tehran </LOCATION> since the 1979 Islamic Revolution transformed the Iranian capital into a city known for mobs of religious fanatics shouting, `` Death to <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>! Death to <LOCATION> Russia </LOCATION>!'' <PERSON> Rafsanjani </PERSON> and <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> have been meeting in the <LOCATION> Kremlin </LOCATION> over two days with a number of their colleagues. <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> said they will sign several agreements before <PERSON> Rafsanjani </PERSON> leaves <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>. Among them are a promise to be good neighbors on their 1,550-mile border and an agreement on joint projects in 15 areas of the economy, including nuclear energy, gas processing, and space. The level of relations, which may extend to putting an Iranian on board a Soviet spaceship, marks a dramatic turnaround. Earlier this decade, the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> was supplying weapons for <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> to fight <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>, and <PERSON> Ayatollah </PERSON> <PERSON> Ruhollah </PERSON> <PERSON> Khomeini </PERSON>'s fundamentalist regime was banning <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>. In contrast, <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> quoted <PERSON> Rafsanjani </PERSON> as saying Wednesday, `` I have been in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> less than 24 hours, yet already I feel almost at home.'' <LOCATION> Tehran </LOCATION> television said <PERSON> Rafsanjani </PERSON> is extending his visit beyond the planned Thursday departure. It was <PERSON> Rafsanjani </PERSON> who suggested a joint Soviet-Iranian space voyage, and <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> ordered his deputies to begin planning details. <PERSON> Rafsanjani </PERSON> emphasized that it was <PERSON> Khomeini </PERSON> himself who in February, several months before his death on June 3, called for better relations with the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> noted that <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> and <PERSON> Khomeini </PERSON> exchanged messages in February, and since then their foreign ministers have met four times. `` We should admit that in the past we had periods where our border turned into a blank wall,'' <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> said at a <LOCATION> Kremlin </LOCATION> banquet for <PERSON> Rafsanjani </PERSON>. `` It is good that those times apparently have passed.'' <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> had hoped the revolution that ousted the late <PERSON> Shah </PERSON> <PERSON> Mohammad </PERSON> <PERSON> Reza </PERSON> <PERSON> Pahlavi </PERSON>, a longtime <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> ally, would give it a toehold in the nation on its southern border. Instead, Iranian fundamentalists chose an independent path and held <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> in disdain. Now, <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> said, rail links will be restored and another rail line constructed. With ties to the West strained, <LOCATION> Tehran </LOCATION> is looking to the Soviet bloc for help in rebuilding <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> after its eight-year war with <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>, which halted with a cease-fire in August. Iranian officials said last month they hoped to sign an arms deal with <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>, but <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> said nothing on the subject.
