<HEAD>Government Allows Boeing 737-400 Jets To Fly With Power Curb</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Civil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aviation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Authority </ORGANIZATION> Wednesday lifted its grounding order on 12 <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> 737-400 planes operated by British airlines provided modifications are made to the engines. The planes were grounded nine days ago after two incidents in which 737-400s were forced to make emergency landings because fan blades broke in their CFM 56-3C engines. The engines are manufactured by <ORGANIZATION> CFM </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION>, a joint venture between <ORGANIZATION> SNECMA </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> and <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Electric </ORGANIZATION> of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s aviation authority imposed power cuts of 1,500 pounds of thrust on the CFM 56-3C engines, effectively converting them to a previous generation of that make. The planes will be allowed a maximum thrust of 22,000 pounds, the same as the previous <ORGANIZATION> CFM </ORGANIZATION> 56-3B, which had 6 million hours of reliable service. Airlines were also ordered to replace the engines' fan blades and discs. Regular visual inspections of fan blades and the front face of the engine discs will also be required, a spokesman for the British authority said. Airlines were already making the modifications and some 737-400s might be back in operation on Thursday, he said. Demonstrations Wednesday by the engine manufacturer showed that fan fatigue occurred near the peak in the engine's thrust, the spokesman said. `` It has now been found that running it at that higher speed, particularly at the rate of climb, has induced something that will need further investigation,'' he said. The grounding order was made after fan blades broke on a DanAir plane at <LOCATION> Gatwick </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Airport </LOCATION> on June 9 and on a British <ORGANIZATION> Midland </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airways </ORGANIZATION> aircraft at <LOCATION> Heathrow </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Airport </LOCATION> on June 11. Fan blade problems were also thought to have contributed to the engine failure that led to the January crash of a <LOCATION> British </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Midland </LOCATION> 737-400 near <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Midlands </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Airport </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Leicestershire </LOCATION>, killing 47. The <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aviation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Adminstration </ORGANIZATION> rejected the British authority's grounding request and cleared 737-400s to fly with the lower engine thrust and new blades and discs. In addition to British <LOCATION> Midland </LOCATION> and DanAir, 737-400s are operated by <PERSON> Novair </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Europe </ORGANIZATION> and Air UK-Leisure.
