<HEAD>Judge Temporarily Restores Dropout's License</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MEG THOMAS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHARLESTON, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A judge temporarily restored driving privileges Wednesday to a married teen-ager whose license was suspended under a law aimed at curbing a high rate of school dropouts. <LOCATION> Kanawha </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> Circuit Judge <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Zakaib </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON> set aside <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Mean </PERSON>'s license suspension for 30 days to allow attorneys to file briefs in the case. Means, 17, of <LOCATION> Charleston </LOCATION>, who dropped out of the ninth grade last year, appealed a <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Vehicles </ORGANIZATION> decision to suspend his license under a first-of-its-kind law aimed at reducing the state's dropout rate, now about 17 percent. Under education reform law passed by the <ORGANIZATION> Legislature </ORGANIZATION> last summer, students under 18 who miss more than 10 consecutive days of school or have 15 unexcused absences must give up their driving privileges. Means' attorney, <PERSON> Christopher </PERSON> <PERSON> Butch </PERSON>, argued that the law was in conflict with another state law permitting students to drop out of school at age 16. The law, he said, was condemning Means and his family to poverty because he was unable to earn the money he needed to support his family without a driver's license. `` The law is not only draconian, it's unreasonable in this case,'' <PERSON> Butch </PERSON> told the court Wednesday. Means' 16-year-old wife, <PERSON> Tonya </PERSON>, who is expecting a child in August, said the state was preventing her husband from caring for her and their unborn child. Her license also was suspended because she is a dropout. `` We have the same responsibilities as anyone over 18,'' she said. `` He has a house to pay for and has to earn money to care for me and the baby.'' Means said despite the judge's decision, he still felt the state was trying to force him to return to school. `` I think they're trying to pressure me, to force me to enroll in a -LRB- high school equivalency -RRB- program. I do n't like being forced to do anything,'' he said. <PERSON> Zakaib </PERSON> said Means could retain his driving privileges permanently if he enrolls in an equivalency course and makes satisfactory progress. Deputy Attorney General <PERSON> Bruce </PERSON> <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON>, who represents the <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Vehicles </ORGANIZATION>, said he was satisfied with the progress of the case. `` I was just worried that this would drag on through the courts until he turned 18,'' <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON> said. `` I think this allows for a quick resolution.'' <PERSON> Butch </PERSON> left the court room immediately after the judge stayed the suspension and was unavailable for comment. <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON> argued that revoking the decision to suspend Mean's license would send the wrong message to teen-agers in similar situations `` It will encourage those people who want to avoid their responsibility to the state and to themselves,'' <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON> said. He argued that statistics show dropouts are less likely to be able to obtain jobs paying above the minimum wage. `` Maybe an education, some training, would help these people break this cycle, a cycle of poverty and lowered ambitions.'' <PERSON> Therese </PERSON> <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON>, director of the <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Support </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> for the state <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Education </ORGANIZATION>, testified that after the law went into effect, 1,800 dropouts returned to school in the fall and 50 percent were still attending school in March. The state's recent dropout rate of around 17 percent is equivalent to 5,000 students, <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON> said. The state expected to reduce the rate this year by 1,000 students as a direct result of the new law, she said. Several states, including <LOCATION> Wisconsin </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> where Gov. <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Clements </PERSON> signed a dropout bill into law Friday, have passed similar legislation and others are considering such laws.
