<HEAD>Cable Industry Has Become Monopoly, Senator, Others Claim</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAY ARNOLD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A few major cable television operators are now the `` godfathers'' of the industry, exacting tribute from start-up companies and withholding programming from rural viewers, a <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> panel was told Wednesday. An increasingly prosperous cable industry has raised prices and stiff-armed microwave and home satellite dish companies that need programming, while growing into a `` cable Cosa Nostra'' that can do as it pleases without fear of regulation or competition, Sen. <PERSON> Albert </PERSON> <PERSON> Gore </PERSON>, D-Tenn., said Since 1986, when a 1984 law deregulating cable was fully in place, only about six new cable program networks have been successful, and they all are at least partially owned by major cable system operators, <PERSON> Gore </PERSON> said at a <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> communications subcommittee hearing on ownership of the cable TV industry. In the wake of deregulation, `` We have witnessed an extraordinary concentration of control and integration by cable operators and program services, manifesting itself in blatantly anticompetitive behavior towards those who would compete with existing cable operators for the right to distribute services,'' <PERSON> Gore </PERSON> said. `` In the case of satellite dish owners, for example, program services have consistently refused to deal with distributors unless they are cable operators, shutting out almost all competition for a market that, ironically, cable itself has largely refused to serve,'' added <PERSON> Gore </PERSON>, who has introduced legislation that would re-regulate cable, allow telephone companies to compete in cable and require cable operators to provide access for all program services and delivery technologies. Wednesday's was the second in a series of three hearings on media ownership that have featured a virtual who's who of television industry executives. The hearings were spurred by increasing complaints to <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> of price hikes and poor service and of `` quick-buck'' buying and selling of cable systems. The `` horizontal concentration'' of a few companies has turned cable into a major TV force that enters more than half the nation's living rooms. At least a dozen bills are pending in <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> to re-regulate cable prices, try to induce competition or to slow the shift of TV sports to pay television. <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Mooney </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cable </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Television </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, testified that there was `` great sensitivity'' in his industry to complaints but that cable has changed television for the better as it loosened the stranglehold of <ORGANIZATION> ABC </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> CBS </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION> and offered far more and better programming. Cable industry investment in new programming _ so-called vertical integration _ has spurred the cable boom and has not impeded the development of competing technologies or program services, <PERSON> Mooney </PERSON> said. But <PERSON> Preston </PERSON> <PERSON> Padden </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Independent </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Television </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stations </ORGANIZATION>, said that when <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION> launched its new Consumer News and Business Channel earlier this year, <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION> reportedly paid the nation's largest cable system operator, <ORGANIZATION> Tele-Communications </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, `` an estimated $ 20 million to buy or lease <ORGANIZATION> Tempo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Television </ORGANIZATION> _ a cable service whose apparent assets would appear to have been negligible.'' `` That transaction has all the appearances of the payment of tribute for access through <ORGANIZATION> TCI </ORGANIZATION>'s concentrated monopoly subscriber base,'' <PERSON> Padden </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Gore </PERSON> called it a `` shakedown'' by a `` godfather'' - like `` cable Cosa Nostra'' in which any new programming source first must get approval from a half-dozen major cable operators before it can even think of proceeding <PERSON> Gore </PERSON>, subcommittee Chairman Sen. <PERSON> Daniel </PERSON> <PERSON> Inouye </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Hawaii </LOCATION>, and Sens. <PERSON> Larry </PERSON> <PERSON> Pressler </PERSON>, R.-S.D., and <PERSON> Conrad </PERSON> <PERSON> Burns </PERSON>, R-Mont., expressed concern that their largely rural constituencies were being shortchanged by the cable industry's apparent reluctance to sell programs to microwave cable and home satellite dish users
