<HEAD>Chemical Removed from Hazard List</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By H. JOSEF HEBERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Environmental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Protection </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> on Wednesday declared that sodium sulfate, which accounts for about half of the hazardous chemical releases by industry nationwide, is n't a toxic substance at all. Sodium sulfate is a widely used agent and byproduct in a variety of processes including the production of paper, glass and detergents. The chemical industry had petitioned the <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> to reclassify sodium sulfate arguing that there is no evidence the chemical poses a significant health threat. The action by the <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> had been expected. The agency staff had earlier recommended that sodium sulfate be reclassified as being nontoxic `` due to an apparent absence of significant toxicity concerns'' about the chemical. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Israel </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> petitions coordinator, said the reclassification was taken after the agency concluded that sodium sulfate `` did not meet the health and environmental toxicity criteria'' required by the law. The chemical is widely used in industry and accounted for nearly 54 percent of all the toxic chemicals releases into the air, water and soil during 1987, according to an <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> report eaerlier this week on releases by industry of 328 toxic chemicals. The agency said that more than 12 billion pounds of sodium sulfate were releases by industrial plants, most of it into surface water, during 1987. The absence of sodium sulfate from the <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> toxic chemical list will result in significant changes in the national profile on toxic releases, agency officials said. For example, the largest volume of sodium sulfate releases occurred in <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>, including 5.3 billion pounds from one plant, causing that state to lead every other state in toxic industrial chemical releases for 1987. Without sodium sulfate, <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> would have ranked ninth, the <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> said. Overall, 22.5 billion pounds of toxic releases were reported for 1987, according to the <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> report. But that volume is more than cut in half without sodium sulfate. Water discharges were the most common form of toxic chemical releases in 1987 largedly because three-fourths of all relases of sodium sulfate were into surface water. Without sodium sulfate, water releases would have ranked last.
