<TEXT>
 <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Hurt </PERSON> referred to his lover as his wife when she was pregnant with their child, according to a doctor's wife who testified Wednesday that she recognized the actor's voice from the movie `` Body Heat.'' <PERSON> Shirley </PERSON> <PERSON> Credle </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Beaufort </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> S.C. </LOCATION>, wife of Dr. <PERSON> Bernard </PERSON> <PERSON> Credle </PERSON>, an obstetrician, said Hurt called their house sometime after he arrived in the state in late October 1982 to film `` The Big Chill.'' Hurt was referring to dancer <PERSON> Sandra </PERSON> <PERSON> Jennings </PERSON>, 32, who was then about eight months pregnant with <PERSON> Hurt </PERSON>'s son, <PERSON> Alexander </PERSON> <PERSON> Devon </PERSON> <PERSON> Hurt </PERSON>, now 6. <PERSON> Jennings </PERSON> claims a common-law marriage exists between her and Hurt under <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION> statutes. She says she now wants a `` divorce'' and up to half of everything he has earned in the past 6 -LCB- years. <PERSON> Jennings </PERSON>' lawyer, <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Golub </PERSON>, estimates Hurt's worth at $ 10 million. Mrs. <PERSON> Credle </PERSON> said she did not recognize <PERSON> Hurt </PERSON>'s voice until he identified himself but then she remembered his voice from the movie `` Body Heat.'' `` Is this Mrs. Doctor?'' Mrs. <PERSON> Credle </PERSON> quoted Hurt as asking. She said she told him she was and <PERSON> Hurt </PERSON> said, `` Can I speak to the doctor about my wife?'' She said she never met Hurt or <PERSON> Jennings </PERSON>. <PERSON> Jennings </PERSON>' claim is based on four weeks she spent with Hurt in <LOCATION> Beaufort </LOCATION>, from Dec. 9, 1982, to Jan. 10, 1983, while he was filming `` The Big Chill.'' Hurt reportedly learned he was divorced from actress <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> <PERSON> Beth </PERSON> <PERSON> Hurt </PERSON> on Dec. 9, 1982, after seven years of marriage. <PERSON> Jennings </PERSON> argues that from that day on, a common-law marriage has existed between her and Hurt although there was never a formal ceremony. <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, where the two lived most of the time, does not recognize common-law marriages. <PERSON> Golub </PERSON> said Mrs. <PERSON> Credle </PERSON>'s testimony proved Hurt and <PERSON> Jennings </PERSON> were living as husband and wife in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION>, but since Mrs. <PERSON> Credle </PERSON> could not say for certain that the call came after Dec. 9, 1982, the value of her testimony is questionable. <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> Justice <PERSON> Jacqueline </PERSON> <PERSON> Silbermann </PERSON>, who is hearing the trial without a jury, must decide whether a common-law marriage exists. The judge has indicated that <PERSON> Jennings </PERSON> will have a hard time proving her case. <PERSON> Jennings </PERSON> was on the stand part of Wednesday's court session for cross-examination, and Hurt's lawyer, <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> <PERSON> Shelton </PERSON>, showed that her testimony was sometimes inconsistent with earlier sworn statements. For example, she once said Hurt had her sign a prenuptial agreement on Dec. 3, 1982, in which she forfeited any claims to his money. She later testified she had learned they signed the agreement around Christmas that year. Hurt testified no agreement was ever signed. In a sworn affidavit, <PERSON> Jennings </PERSON> said <PERSON> Hurt </PERSON> told her it would be unseemly for them to have a civil marriage ceremony with her being nine months pregnant and everybody thinking they were already married. In court Wednesday, she testified that Hurt had never said anything about a civil ceremony being unseemly. The trial is scheduled to resume Thursday.
