<HEAD>Perez Hits Role of Developed World in Debt Crisis</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS throughout, CORRECTING foreign debt figure to $401 billion
sted $410 billion; identifying Brady and expanding on proposal, UPDATING
with Mongolia admitted. No pickup</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANTHONY CAPLAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CARACAS, Venezuela (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Carlos </PERSON> <PERSON> Andres </PERSON> <PERSON> Perez </PERSON> on Wednesday told delegations from 127 nations that the `` economic totalitarianism'' of the developed world is crushing an increasingly restive Third World. <PERSON> Perez </PERSON>, in a welcoming speech to the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION> of 77, praised the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> <PERSON> Brady </PERSON> plan as an important initiative for relieving the burden of a $ 1.3 trillion debt on the Third World. `` But we impatiently wait for the concrete gains ... in light of our urgent situation,'' said <PERSON> Perez </PERSON>. <PERSON> Perez </PERSON>'s efforts to impose austerity measures in his country, backed by international creditors, prompted riots in February that killed about 300 people. Similar riots were reported in May in <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION>, another large contributor to <LOCATION> Latin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s $ 401 billion foreign debt. <PERSON> Perez </PERSON> said 40 countries in the underdeveloped world _ with a combined population of more than 800 million _ faced severe financial problems because of the debt. He said that since 1982, those countries signed up to 90 restructuring agreements with banks, but the banks never agreed to interest rates at or below market rates. `` When we speak of that economic totalitarianism that is forced on us ... we refer to insensitive attempts to relegate our economic and social development to immediate needs of fiscal balance in order to assure the payment of the debt,'' <PERSON> Perez </PERSON> said. The plan proposed by <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Treasury Secretary <PERSON> Nicholas </PERSON> <PERSON> Brady </PERSON> on March 10 encourages banks to forgive a substantial portion of their loans to heavily indebted countries in return for guarantees that the rest will be paid. The <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Monetary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fund </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> would furnish the guarantees. The <PERSON> Brady </PERSON> plan also calls for economic reforms in debtor countries in order to receive the benefits of reductions in the debt. <PERSON> Perez </PERSON> said developed countries call for belt-tightening for the poor when they lived beyond their means `` at the expense of the rest of the world.'' He castigated the industrialized nations for basing their growth on `` the destruction of the environment along with an immoral export of toxic wastes to the Third World.'' <PERSON> Perez </PERSON> made calls to the Group of 77 to renew the commitment to economic cooperation within the underdeveloped world, saying such efforts had flagged under the strain of the debt crisis. The group, a non-aligned organization within the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> system, was formed 25 years ago to give underdeveloped nations a forum to push for changes in the international economy. Originally comprised of 77 member nations, the group officially admitted <LOCATION> Mongolia </LOCATION> as its 128th member Wednesday. The group, meeting until Friday, is expected to call for a better economic conditions in the light of the increasing impoverishment of the underdeveloped world and increased economic cooperation between the underdeveloped nations, said <PERSON> Muchkund </PERSON> <PERSON> Dubey </PERSON>, permanent secretary of economic affairs of the Indian Foreign Ministry.
