<BYLINE>By BRENDA C. COLEMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Activists who fought a clash between patriotism and creativity stemming from an art student's floor display of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> flag hailed Wednesday's <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> decision clearing a flag-burning protester. Some <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION> lawmakers, however, said they'll fight on for a law to punish improper displays of the flag. The high court, voting 5-4, threw out the conviction of a protester sentenced to a year in jail and fined $ 2,000 for burning the flag in <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>. The court said the flag-burning at a demonstration in <LOCATION> Dallas </LOCATION> during the 1984 Republican National Convention was a form of expression protected by the Constitution's guarantee of freedom of speech. One <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION> activist said the ruling will discourage passage of <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION> proposals to prohibit displaying the flag on the floor, but a sponsor of such a proposal says the <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> case may have little relevance to <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION> legislation. `` Hopefully, it -LRB- the ruling -RRB- will have some impact on the broader questions of censorship so prevalent today,'' said <PERSON> Rich </PERSON> <PERSON> Hutchinson </PERSON>, a member of the <ORGANIZATION> No-Mandatory </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Patriotism </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organizing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>. `` No doubt the reactionaries are not all going to go home,'' he added. `` I think people really need to continue this fight.'' The committee was formed in support of <PERSON> Scott </PERSON> <PERSON> Tyler </PERSON>, a student at the School of the <ORGANIZATION> Art </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION>, who provoked angry protests by