<HEAD>Government Liquidates Five Brokerages In Wake of Stock Scandal</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRASILIA, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The government Wednesday closed five stock brokerages caught in the biggest scandal in the Brazilian market's history. Among the houses liquidated was <LOCATION> Capitanea </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Distribuidora </LOCATION>, owned by <PERSON> Elmo </PERSON> <PERSON> Camoes </PERSON>, who Monday quit as president of the <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION>'s equivalent to the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Camoes </PERSON> owns 99 percent of the brokerage, which was caught short in the unprecedented scandal allegedly caused by the speculation of a single investor, multimillionaire businessman <PERSON> Naji </PERSON> <PERSON> Nahas </PERSON>. The liquidations, signed by acting <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> president <PERSON> Wadico </PERSON> <PERSON> Bucchi </PERSON>, also included the brokerages <PERSON> Ney </PERSON> <PERSON> Carvalho </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Celton </LOCATION>, Titular and Beta. The five houses ran up a debt equivalent to $ 64 million. <PERSON> Nahas </PERSON>, 42, the No. 1 investor in <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION>'s $ 30 billion stock market, bounced checks worth $ 31 million to several brokerages used to purchase stock futures, said the <ORGANIZATION> Brazilian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Nahas </PERSON> had borrowed heavily to invest in blue-chip stocks, taking advantage of a rule that allowed him to pay five days later, said the commission, which is the rough equivalent to the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>. Meanwhile, he pumped up the stock's price by buying large amounts of common stock, meaning the shares he received later were worth more. When banks restricted credit for that type of operation, <PERSON> Nahas </PERSON>' checks to several brokerages were returned for lack of funds. A judge in <LOCATION> Sao </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Paulo </LOCATION>, the nation's financial center, on Tuesday rejected a request by a prosecutor for the arrest of <PERSON> Nahas </PERSON>, ruling there was not enough evidence to show he was responsible for stock manipulation. But the <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> has barred <PERSON> Nahas </PERSON> from leaving the country. There are nine stock exchanges in <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION>, and <PERSON> Nahas </PERSON> had been playing principally on the Rio market. <PERSON> Rio </PERSON> and <LOCATION> Sao </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Paulo </LOCATION> are the principal exchanges. The Monday after the scandal broke on June 9th, the commission declared a one-day stock market holiday to prevent panic among investors, but the government refused to bail out the brokerages or the Rio Exchange. On Saturday, <ORGANIZATION> Rio </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> de </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Janeiro </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> President <PERSON> Sergio </PERSON> <PERSON> Barcellos </PERSON> announced he was taking an indefinite leave of absence. The scandal prompted an investigation of 29 brokerages by the commission. The markets began to recover Tuesday from a week-long tailspin that saw share prices plunge by more than 34 percent. The <ORGANIZATION> Rio </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> rose 10.5 percent and the <LOCATION> Sao </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Paulo </LOCATION> exchanges closed up 15.3 percent. On Wednesday, the Rio exchange fell by 0.1 percent, while in <LOCATION> Sao </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Paulo </LOCATION> the market closed up 3.9 percent.
