<HEAD>Group Questions Whether Council Will Be Fair</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS grafs 13-15 bgng: ``Margarita Suarez,'' with embassy
comment.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By W. DALE NELSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A privately financed group studying preparations for the Nicaraguan election questioned Wednesday whether the council appointed by the Sandinista government to oversee the campaign and balloting will be fair. The <ORGANIZATION> Bipartisan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> on Free and Fair Elections said the appointment of <PERSON> Mariano </PERSON> <PERSON> Faillos </PERSON>, a member of the ruling party, as president of the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Electoral </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> `` raises questions about the independence'' of the five-member panel. In addition, the group said, it `` would have improved the composition'' of the body if both of the two members representing the political opposition had been drawn from <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>'s `` Group of 14'' opposition parties. Instead, President <PERSON> Daniel </PERSON> <PERSON> Ortega </PERSON> nominated and the <ORGANIZATION> Nicaraguan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION> appointed <PERSON> Aman </PERSON> <PERSON> Sandino </PERSON>, a member of the <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Conservative </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, to one of the two slots. Leaders of the `` Group of 14'' do not recognize the Democratic Conservatives as an opposition party, but consider them allied with the governing <ORGANIZATION> Sandinistas </ORGANIZATION>. Nevertheless, the commission said, <PERSON> Sandino </PERSON> is considered a dissident in his own party and `` some say this proves <PERSON> Sandino </PERSON>'s sufficient independence'' from the <ORGANIZATION> Sandinistas </ORGANIZATION> `` Given these perspectives, it is uncertain at this point whether the five appointments are balanced and fair,'' the commission said. <PERSON> Curtin </PERSON> <PERSON> Winsor </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, co-chairman of the commission, who was ambassador to <LOCATION> Costa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rica </LOCATION> during the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration, said the commission hopes to meet with the electoral council soon and has applied for visas to enter <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> sometime this summer. On June 12, the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> accused <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> of trying to restrict foreign monitoring of the balloting by requiring Americans _ for the first time _ to acquire entry visas as of July 1. The commission released letters it has written to President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> and Secretary of State <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON> asking for an opportunity to brief them on its work. Former Sen. <PERSON> Gaylord </PERSON> <PERSON> Nelson </PERSON>, D-Wis., the other co-chairman of the commission, said the group would request a meeting with <PERSON> Ortega </PERSON> and had begun efforts to meet with other Central American presidents <PERSON> Nelson </PERSON> said a number of trips to <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> were planned, beginning in late July or early August and continuing through the elections that are to be held in February under an agreement between <PERSON> Ortega </PERSON> and the governments of <LOCATION> Costa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rica </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Guatemala </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Honduras </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Margarita </PERSON> <PERSON> Suarez </PERSON>, press officer for the <ORGANIZATION> Nicaraguan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Embassy </ORGANIZATION>, said she assumed the visas would be granted, but `` the official position is that the only people who will be allowed to be observers are those that have been invited to be observers by the government.'' `` There is really no restrictions on the visas, unless someone is really undesirable,'' Ms. <PERSON> Suarez </PERSON> said. `` There is no new qualification that people must go through simply because they are Americans.'' Ms. <PERSON> Suarez </PERSON> said the embassy had not yet received a copy of the commission's report. The commission said its proposals were `` but the minimal requirements for a free and fair electoral campaign and election.'' `` They are consistent with Central American practices and are by no means ideal standards or an attempt to impose <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> practices on <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>,'' the panel said. The commission, which held hearings here May 9-11, is sponsored by the conservative <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Freedom </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foundation </ORGANIZATION>. The group said that `` international observers, press, and broadcast media must have the right to travel throughout the country during the campaign to monitor the electoral process.'' It said polling must be permitted, there must be `` reasonable opposition access'' to press, radio and television, and laws giving the government censorship and control over media outlets must be suspended during the campaign. It proposed that <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>, which has no voter registration system, establish one by the beginning of the campaign on Sept. 1. Although few countries in <LOCATION> Latin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> allow absentee voting, the commission said a significant number of Nicaraguans now live abroad in exile and `` fairness calls for some form of participation by these people in deciding their homeland's future.''
