<HEAD>Part I: A Land of Sinking Sand, Encroaching Salt Water</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto, LaserGraphic, LaserLogo</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
 Along <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION>'s marshy coast, it's always been hard to tell where the land ends and the water begins. But the line is changing; about an acre of rich marshland sinks under water every 15 minutes. And the problem is n't confined to <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION>, as reported in the first story of a two-part series, `` Disappearing Wetlands.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>By AUSTIN WILSON</NOTE>
<NOTE>Associated Press Writer</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 From <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> to the rocky coast of <LOCATION> Maine </LOCATION>, what's left of the nation's wetlands and barrier islands is disappearing. Nowhere is it going faster than in <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION>, where 30 to 50 square miles of marshy coastline wash away every year. Shrimp fishermen pull trawls over the Port Eads schoolyard where <PERSON> Clive </PERSON> <PERSON> Duet </PERSON>, 73, used to play. Water 4 feet deep covers the 160-acre farm near <LOCATION> Galliano </LOCATION> where <PERSON> Joe </PERSON> <PERSON> Billiot </PERSON>, 51, lived as a child. A 200-year-old oak tree stands dying on land near <LOCATION> Theriot </LOCATION> bought in 1840 by the great-grandfather of <PERSON> Marvin </PERSON> <PERSON> Marmande </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>. Salt water, once more than a quarter-mile off, has eaten away the marshes and now soaks the tree's roots <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION>, with 40 percent of the nation's remaining coastal wetlands, suffers 80 percent of the annual loss. Its fragile marshes are the nurturing grounds for a yearly seafood harvest worth almost $ 1 billion, the habitat for 40 percent of the country's fur-bearing animals and the wintering home for nearly 5 million migratory birds. About half of <LOCATION> Louisana </LOCATION>'s marshes have disappeared since World War II, wiped out by such natural forces as hurricanes and by levees and dams. In <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION>, the nation's worst oil spill has devastated long stretches of coastline. But the Alaskan wetlands, however damaged, remain. Eventually, they will renew themselves. The <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION> marshes are gone, quietly, without drama, without nightly newscasts, without crowds of volunteers. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Stewart </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, director of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Wetlands </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Slidell </LOCATION>, an arm of the <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. Fish and <ORGANIZATION> Wildlife </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>, said: `` People in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, when I've had the occasion to speak over there, have said, ` The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> is the most developed, the most forward-looking, the brightest country in the world. How could you let this happen?' `` The simple truth is that we did n't know, 40 years ago, that it was going to happen. A lot of the things that started this occurred 40 years ago, and we did n't have the ability to forecast the effects.'' <PERSON> Dave </PERSON> <PERSON> Carney </PERSON>, a biologist with the <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corps </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Engineers </ORGANIZATION>, said it was only recently that the Corps began considering the environment as important as flood control and navigation. In addition, <PERSON> Carney </PERSON> said, `` It was n't until 1969 that the National Environmental Policy Act ... imposed a system for rigorous environmental examination of federal projects and activities. `` Many decisions were made long before that. Tremendous investments, the whole <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> tributaries project, all of the oil and gas exploration and investment that are now regulated, were not regulated to that degree back in the 1940s and 1950s when these things started popping. `` I'm not saying all of those decisions are irreversible, but many of them are irreversible _ commitments of resources and decisions made in <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION> before the implications were ever imagined.'' The scope of the problem is enormous. For one thing, <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION>'s 400-mile-long coast translates to almost 7,000 miles of shore when the dips, juts and loops of bays, inlets and peninsulas are included For another, the Biblical separation of earth and water never quite took hold in coastal <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION>, and solid objects tend to sink in the marshes that merge with the Gulf of <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>. `` I can not find any coastal marsh loss rate higher than that of <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION> anywhere,'' <PERSON> Stewart </PERSON> said. But he also emphasized the problem was not confined to <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION>. `` The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> has lost about 54 percent of its wetlands since settlement,'' he said. `` There have also been great losses in the <LOCATION> Dakotas </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> has lost 90 percent of its wetlands. ... `` You see the same thing in <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mobile </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bay </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Tampa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bay </LOCATION>. Go around the <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> coast, and you see the same thing. The <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Everglades </LOCATION> are undergoing tremendous change, largely because of human impact. `` <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Carolinas </LOCATION>? The same sort of thing, but to a lesser degree. It's really a more stable coastline, so you do n't have the subsidence you have here ... You have losses in <LOCATION> Chesapeake </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bay </LOCATION>. The net is a loss in all of those areas.'' The decisions that affected <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION> were made with clear logic and compelling motives but no consideration of long-range harm. A strong young nation tamed its biggest river system with dams and levees, first making it a reliable transportation artery, then keeping it from overflowing. Nobody pondered how the marshes would live without replenishment from silt-laden fresh water. A vigorous oil industry moved into <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION>'s marshes and the <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION> <LOCATION> of </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> 50 years ago, dredging canals to get drilling rigs to the oil and to lay pipe to offshore fields. Nobody considered the effects of saltwater canals through freshwater marshes. And when 27 sets of locks and dams were built on the <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Missouri </LOCATION> and a giant irrigation project was built far to the north in the <LOCATION> Dakota </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Badlands </LOCATION>, nobody thought of the <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION> marshes. `` Each one of these dams is a sediment trap,'' <PERSON> Stewart </PERSON> said. `` They have reduced the sediment substantially. In a free-flowing system, there was up to 500 million tons a year.'' It took 700 years for <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> sediment to build the marshes of the current delta. It took 22 years, from 1956 to 1978, for half of those marshes, more than 1,000 square miles, to disappear. `` We took a very dynamic system and made it stable,'' <PERSON> Stewart </PERSON> said, `` and there were some totally unforeseen consequences.'' Natural forces were at work, too. Spongy soil compresses under its own weight. Salt water levels are rising slowly. And hurricanes can wipe out miles of marshes in a day. `` You take one like <PERSON> Betsy </PERSON> in 1965 and it just rolls the marsh up like a rug,'' <PERSON> Stewart </PERSON> said. Hurricanes pile up walls of water in front of them. Those tidal surges used to dissipate over miles of marshes. Now, they funnel through canals and navigation channels, spreading salt water miles inland, killing vegetation and carving up the wetlands. Environmentalists blame Big Oil and the <ORGANIZATION> Corps </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Engineers </ORGANIZATION>. `` It comes with the territory,'' <PERSON> Carney </PERSON> said of the criticism. `` In a way, the buck does stop here. People can study it, talk about it, but eventually anything that is going to be done will be done by the state and the <ORGANIZATION> Corps </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Engineers </ORGANIZATION> in some cooperative way.'' <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Leighton </PERSON> <PERSON> Steward </PERSON>, chairman, chief executive officer and president of <ORGANIZATION> Louisiana </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Land </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exploration </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, says the oil industry has been unfairly targeted. <ORGANIZATION> LL </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; E, which owns more than 600,000 acres of marshland, the largest private holding of coastal wetlands in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, makes most of its money from oil and gas on its land, but also leases tracts for hunting and trapping. <PERSON> Steward </PERSON> estimated that hunting for petroleum in the marshes and dredging canals to reach oil and gas deposits caused about 10 percent of the loss. The remaining 90 percent has been due to natural forces exacerbated by the trapping of the <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> in its current channel, <PERSON> Steward </PERSON> said. `` We do n't claim we are absolutely guiltless,'' <PERSON> Steward </PERSON> said, `` because when you build a canal through wetlands, you are going to chew up a certain amount of wetlands.''
</TEXT>
