<SECOND>PM-Wetlands-Marmande, Adv 26,0529</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv26</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Mon PMs, June 26, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Landowner: `Our Way of Life Is Going With It'</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Disappearing Wetlands I</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By AUSTIN WILSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>THERIOT, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 To <PERSON> Marvin </PERSON> <PERSON> Marmande </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, the dying oak is a symbol. `` It was a beautiful, full-grown tree when my great-grandfather first saw it 140 years ago. I remember when I was 7 or 8 years old, having picnics with my mama and the family here, and the branches spread way over there,'' <PERSON> Marmande </PERSON>, 31, said, sweeping his arm toward a point 30 feet away. `` Now, it's dying. Its roots are in salt water.'' The plight of the 200-year-old live oak mirrors what's happening to all marshland in coastal <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION>. Erosion and subsidence claim 30-50 square miles of wetland each year. `` Our way of life is going with it,'' <PERSON> Marmande </PERSON> said. `` There used to be 70 families making a living on this land. This was all farmland, sugar cane and potatoes, mostly, and cattle. ... `` This land used to support seven families just for trapping _ muskrat, otter, mink. Now there's just one. We used to catch worlds of crawfish here, but it's salt water now.'' The Marmande land is on a finger of high ground built by 700 years of spring floods on the <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION>. The fresh water marshes that surrounded the peninsula were nourished by bayous and streams running from the river to the <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION> <LOCATION> of </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>. The river is trapped by levees now, and the bayous and streams no longer carry fresh water to the marshes. The 8-mile-long Marmande peninsula, about a half-mile wide at its landward base, ends at a 60-acre plateau that stands a dizzying 7 feet above sea level _ really high ground in these parts. `` You ca n't get there, except by boat,'' <PERSON> Marmande </PERSON> said. `` The road's under water in a couple of spots _ used to be 3 or 4 feet above sea level. `' Much of the damage has been done by the <ORGANIZATION> Houma </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Navigation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Canal </ORGANIZATION>, a straight-shot channel dredged 30 years ago to provide quicker access to the Gulf of <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> Some of the salt water comes up through <LOCATION> Cades </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lake </LOCATION> and Minors Canal. <PERSON> Marmande </PERSON> believes in levees and pumps to isolate the sources of salt water and hold back erosion. `` Look at what they've done in <LOCATION> Holland </LOCATION>. They've reclaimed land from the sea,'' he said. He points to a neighbor's land where a distinct line shows the intrusion of salt water _ a vigorous green stand of cypress on one side of the line, naked brown stumps on the other side. `` He built his own levee and put in his own pumps,'' <PERSON> Marmande </PERSON> said. `` But you ca n't get permits to do that anymore. We ca n't even get permits to raise a levee that's been there 14 years, and it's sinking. `` I consider it my obligation to try to do something about it. Maybe we can never put it back the way it was, but we can stop it from getting worse.''
</TEXT>
