<FIRST>a a PM-DisappearingWetlandsII Adv27-2Takes   06-21 1219</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Disappearing Wetlands II, Adv 27-2 Takes,1247</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv27</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Tues PMs, June 27, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Part II: Searching for Ways to Turn the Tide</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto, LaserGraphic</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
 It took 700 years for the <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> to build the marshes near its mouth, but half of them have disappeared in the last 30 years. Is there any way to stop the loss, any way to restore what's gone? This second segment in a series, `` Disappearing Wetlands,'' considers what can be done.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>By AUSTIN WILSON</NOTE>
<NOTE>Associated Press Writer</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> built <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION>'s wetlands, and only the <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> can restore them <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION> loses an acre of its productive wetlands every 15 minutes. At that rate, <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> D.C. </LOCATION>, would be swallowed up in about 14 months. An estimated 10 percent to 20 percent of <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION>'s loss is due to exploration, drilling and production of oil and gas in the marshes and offshore. The main reason for the rest of the loss is that man, in taming the <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> with dams and levees, cut off the supply of fresh water and silt that kept the wetlands green and growing. Any plans for rebuilding marshes involve getting <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> water back where it used to flow naturally, but that calls for big-ticket items. The <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corps </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Engineers </ORGANIZATION> is committed to spending $ 130 million for just three freshwater diversion projects, one under construction at <LOCATION> Caernarvon </LOCATION>, about 15 miles downriver from <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Orleans </LOCATION>, the others in final planning stages. This is an impoverished state with no money to spare: its teachers are among the nation's lowest paid, its police and fire departments are cut back to the bone, its roads are crumbling and its universities are underfunded. Unemployment is at 11.7 percent. The cheaper, less dramatic route would be to save what's left, if possible, or delay its loss. There are plenty of proposals, from planting trees to tearing down the levees. The <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Soil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Conservation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> is testing marsh grass and mangroves to find the toughest strains to help defeat wave action and tie down fragile soil. State and federal agencies are issuing fewer permits for wetlands activities. Some ideas seem too small to have any impact. <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Good </PERSON> and <PERSON> Vance </PERSON> <PERSON> Edwards </PERSON> spread discarded Christmas trees in shallow coastal waters. <PERSON> Henry </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Rodriguez </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON> plants trees on marshland hummocks. <PERSON> Roland </PERSON> <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> sets out sprigs of marsh grass. Piles of old Christmas trees might trap sediment and slow erosion, restoring and protecting the marsh. Roots from new vegetation might also hold sediment. `` Usually, thinking big is the way to go, but we may have to think small on this problem,'' said <PERSON> Dave </PERSON> <PERSON> Carney </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corps </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Engineers </ORGANIZATION>, the first biologist to be named manager of a wetlands restoration project by the Corps. <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION> Land and <ORGANIZATION> Exploration </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> thinks small in a big way _ 400 water-control weirs on the 600,000-plus acres it owns in the coastal marshes. The land, the largest private holding of coastal wetlands in the country, is dotted with LL & amp; E's oil wells. Starting in 1956, long before the plight of the wetlands was obvious, LL & amp; E began building weirs across inlets and bayous that ebb and flow with the tides. The low dams, their tops below water level, are designed to break the force of waves on their way in and slow their retreat until they have dropped their load of sediment. The weirs' effects have never been scientifically measured, but comparisons with unprotected marshes show they work, asserts <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Leighton </PERSON> <PERSON> Steward </PERSON>, chief executive officer and president of <ORGANIZATION> LL </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; E. `` If there are two little natural channels going back into the marsh, both about 30 feet wide, and you put a little weir on one and not on the other, we can see that after a time, one is still 30 feet wide, and the other has eroded on back into the marshes,'' <PERSON> Steward </PERSON> said. `` We have areas where we have the weirs in place, and another land owner, maybe a mile over, has never had them, and our guys can demonstrate that our land is in better shape than theirs is,'' he said. Dag Nummendal of <ORGANIZATION> Louisiana </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>'s geology department believes such efforts are a losing fight, and the focus should be on cutting losses, rather than spending billions of dollars trying to win. He advocates a retreat from everything south of Highway 90, the old east-west route along a natural ridge from <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Orleans </LOCATION>, down through <LOCATION> Morgan </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, then up to <LOCATION> Lafayette </LOCATION> and westward to <LOCATION> Lake </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Charles </LOCATION>. The <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION> Geological Survey estimates Highway 90 will be an oceanfront road by 2083, if nothing is done to reverse coastal erosion. <PERSON> Nummendal </PERSON> recommends a rear-guard action of weirs, pumps and dams _ anything to slow the creeping sea _ while the residents of three dozen coastal communities head for higher ground over the next 50 years. `` That's ludicrous. That's too ridiculous even to consider,'' said <PERSON> Marvin </PERSON> <PERSON> Marmande </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> Houma </LOCATION> businessman and farmer. To leave would mean abandoning land his French-born great-grandfather bought in 1840. `` I would be abandoning everything my father, my grandfather and my great-grandfather worked for, if I left.'' <PERSON> Carney </PERSON> and his fellow project manager at the <ORGANIZATION> Corps </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Engineers </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Jay </PERSON> <PERSON> Warren </PERSON>, say rudimentary studies have looked at turning the river loose below <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Orleans </LOCATION>. One proposal involved dredging a new navigation channel to connect with the <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Outlet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Canal </LOCATION>, tearing down levees and taking ship traffic out of the <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION>. `` Essentially, -LRB- it would -RRB- abandon navigation in the <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> channel, let the channel silt up to whatever depth it wanted to _ about 17 feet _ and put a lock in the river,'' <PERSON> Warren </PERSON> said. The Gulf Outlet Canal is an underused backdoor path from the <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION> <LOCATION> of </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Orleans </LOCATION>, deemed an economic godsend when it was dredged through the marshes 30 years ago. A major source of flooding in Hurricane Betsy in 1965, it introduced salt water into previously fresh marshes in <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bernard </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Parish </LOCATION>, helping to accelerate the death of miles of cypress swamps. <PERSON> Manny </PERSON> <PERSON> Fernandez </PERSON>, spokesman for Gov. <PERSON> Buddy </PERSON> <PERSON> Roemer </PERSON> on environmental matters, said letting the <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> go wild below <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Orleans </LOCATION> was not realistic. `` There are tremendous downsides to that,'' <PERSON> Fernandez </PERSON> said. `` No. 1 is the cost. No. 2 is that you're going through a tremendous amount of wetlands doing that excavation of a new channel. `` Growing up in <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bernard </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Parish </LOCATION> and seeing the tremendous loss and devastation from the Gulf Outlet, I do n't believe we ought to be looking at dredging another channel to solve environmental problems.'' <PERSON> Carney </PERSON> favors building big sluices to let controlled amounts of river water flow through the levees and dump replenishing sediment through the marshes. The freshwater diversion project at <LOCATION> Caernarvon </LOCATION>, when completed in two years, will dump 8,000 cubic feet of water into the marshes each second. <PERSON> Fernandez </PERSON> said he and the head of the state <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Environmental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Quality </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Templet </PERSON>, believe freshwater and sediment diversion structures hold the answer to restoring the marshes. `` <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Templet </PERSON> has said we may need as many as 20 of these structures, rather than the one being built and the two or three being contemplated,'' <PERSON> Fernandez </PERSON> said. `` It will take that many to get the silt back in the marshes.''
</TEXT>
