<FIRST>a a PM-OntheMoney Adv22   06-21 0618</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-On the Money, Adv 22,0633</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv22</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release PMs Thurs June 22</HEAD>
<HEAD>A Handle on Dependent-Care Costs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHET CURRIER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 American employers in increasing numbers are offering workers a tax-saving arrangement called a `` dependent care reimbursement account.'' For two-income couples and single parents, this program serves much the same function as the traditional tax credit available to workers who have dependent-care expenses necessary for them to do their jobs. But the reimbursement account differs in several important ways from the tax credit. If you have a choice between the two -LRB- you ca n't pick both -RRB-, financial advisers say you might well come out ahead with the reimbursement account In a typical case, reimbursement accounts are offered to employees with children up to the age of 13, or with older stay-at-home dependents who need care. Employees who enroll in the plan figure their expected costs for each year, and then request that a proportionate sum be withheld from their regular paychecks. The money withheld is subtracted from their taxable income. After you pay your dependent-care expenses, you submit copies of your bills or canceled checks to your employer, who then reimburses you from the money in your account. If this strikes you as a bit unwieldy, you're by no means alone. You might be put off further by the warning that you need to figure your contributions to the account carefully. The rules state that any unused money in your account at yearend ca n't be reclaimed. It's gone. So why go to all the trouble? Why not just save up your canceled checks and take a dependent-care tax credit each year? Well, because it might save you some money, says the accounting firm of <ORGANIZATION> Coopers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lybrand </ORGANIZATION>: `` For almost everyone, the reimbursement account will be the better choice.'' With such an account, people in the upper tax brackets can save 28 percent or 33 percent on each dependent-care dollar up to $ 5,000 a year, the firm points out. That compares with a 20 percent tax credit for upper-income workers on a maximum of $ 2,400 for one dependent or $ 4,800 for two or more. Furthermore, you do n't pay Social Security tax -LRB- at a rate of 7.51 percent -RRB- on the money that goes into your reimbursement account. The child-care credit has no effect on your Social Security tax. In lower income brackets, the child-care credit offers a savings of up to 30 percent. However, says <ORGANIZATION> Coopers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lybrand </ORGANIZATION>, `` most lower income people will find this is more than offset by the reduced Social Security and income taxes and, possibly, by a higher earned income credit.'' All in all, not bad: More options for many people in an era when tax breaks are disappearing fast. But there's a catch. It is very likely that fewer people _ much fewer, one might speculate _ will take advantage of any writeoffs for dependent care in 1989 than have done so in years past. Starting this year, whether you use a reimbursement plan or claim a dependent-care credit, you must specify the Social Security number or taxpayer identification number of the `` care provider.'' This gives the <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION> a means of checking whether all the money claimed as child-care expenses is reported as taxable income by the person or organization receiving the payments. It also defines more clearly cases where you are legally required to pay such things as Social Security tax and unemployment insurance for anyone who earns $ 50 or more working in your home in any calendar quarter. That pretty well puts all dependent-care tax breaks out of reach for anybody who does n't play the game strictly by the book.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv PMs Thurs June 22</NOTE>
