<FIRST>s a BC-Spill'sReach Adv24-25-1stAdd   06-21 0577</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Spill's Reach, Adv24-25 - 1st Add,0589</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv24</HEAD>
<HEAD>$Adv25</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Weekend Editions, June 24-25</HEAD>
<HEAD>VALDEZ: sufficiently clean.''</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 While the arguments rage onshore, the death toll mounts at sea. Stymied by vast distances and stormy weather, bird rescuers have been able to capture, clean and release only about 500 sea birds. For every surviving bird, more than 50 dead ones lie in freezer vans _ more than 26,000 in all. And that's just a fraction of total mortality. Some biologists say that for every dead bird collected, perhaps 100 have died unnoticed. Sea otters appear to be the hardest-hit marine mammal. The 784 dead sea otters collected so far represent about one-tenth of Prince <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Sound </PERSON>'s total population. Harbor seals may be suffering, too, but few carcasses have been found. `` Dead seals sink like lead balloons,'' explains state marine biologist <PERSON> Kathy </PERSON> <PERSON> Frost </PERSON>. The oil's lethal reach extends down the food chain. On some beaches, mats of oil have wiped out all life, suffocating intertidal creatures such as limpets, mussels, crabs and starfish. And the oil reaches upward, to the tops of tall shoreside spruce trees where bald eagles roost. Oiled sea birds have become a fatal attraction for scavenging eagles, killing 57 of the birds of prey. Biologists have collected lifeless eggs from 30 abandoned eagle nests in the spill area. Hungry brown bears on the shores of Katmai National Park have feasted on oily bird carcasses until they could eat no more, digging holes in the sand to cache the leftovers. Bears are hardy creatures, but biologists have radio-collared 30 of them to study their reaction to swallowing so much oil. `` We have n't determined what effect it has on them. But I can imagine what it would do to me,'' says Katmai National Park Superintendent <PERSON> Ray </PERSON> <PERSON> Bane </PERSON>. At the very top of the food chain are the humans who live close to nature in coastal villages. When Aleut natives complained that the oil spill kept them from gathering food through fishing and seal-hunting, <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION> flew in cases of beef, chicken and diced ham. It gave the villagers stomachaches. Many commercial fishermen have been idled by the spill, though some have landed jobs with <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION>, leasing their boats at rates of $ 3,400 a day and more. Most of the salmon and halibut swimming beneath the oil appear to be surviving. But fisheries worth more than $ 110 million have been canceled or postponed by <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION> officials worried that surface oil might taint fish as they are hauled from the water in fishermen's nets As spring turns to summer, even <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION> officials are starting to waver on the question of finishing the cleanup by mid-September, a deadline long dismissed as unrealistic by some state and federal officials. `` It's always a hope,'' says <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION>'s <PERSON> Plante </PERSON>. `` But it's tougher to predict whether we'll do it by then. That's our plan. We've always said we will not leave it uncleaned, and if that means coming back, so be it. The sooner the better for all concerned _ particularly for 120 frisky sea otters now swimming restlessly in floating pens. They've beaten the odds, thanks to rescuers at an otter hospital in <LOCATION> Seward </LOCATION> The animals are clean, healthy and ready to return to the wild. But they must stay put, biologists say, because the wild is not ready for them.
</TEXT>
