<FIRST>s a BC-Spill'sReach-Chronology Adv24-25   06-21 0593</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Spill's Reach-Chronology, Adv 24-25,0608</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv24</HEAD>
<HEAD>$Adv25</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Weekend Editions, June 24-25, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Whom Do You Believe? Rhetoric As Muddled As Alaska Oil Spill</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-Spill's Reach</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID FOSTER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ANCHORAGE, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The rhetoric surrounding the nation's worst oil spill sometimes has grown as muddled as the North Slope crude fouling <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION>'s southern coast Just how bad is the spill? How is the cleanup going? Here's a look at three months of changing pronouncements, promises and predictions offered by <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION> and other officials. _ MARCH 24 The Exxon Valdez rams a reef, spilling nearly 11 million gallons of oil. _ MARCH 25 State environmental officials call the initial response by <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Alyeska </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pipeline </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> `` inadequate and unacceptable.'' <ORGANIZATION> Alyeska </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Chuck </PERSON> <PERSON> O'Donnel </PERSON> says, `` I think our people did an excellent job.'' The slick covers 28 square miles. _ MARCH 30 `` We're going to pick up _ one way or the other _ all the oil that's out there,'' <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Don </PERSON> <PERSON> Cornett </PERSON> tells reporters in <LOCATION> Valdez </LOCATION>. _ MARCH 31 The slick now covers 600 square miles. `` Absolutely not, it has not gotten away from us,'' <PERSON> Cornett </PERSON> says. `` We are making good progress on this cleanup.'' _ APRIL 18 Oil has killed at least 1,850 birds and 328 sea otters. The slick has spread over 3,000 square miles. <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION> Chairman L.G. <PERSON> Rawl </PERSON> says he's confident most beaches will be clean by mid-September. `` Now I'm not going to tell you that if you go up there a year from now you wo n't find some black places on some rocks, but we're going to make every effort to get it off,'' <PERSON> Rawl </PERSON> says _ MAY 2 In <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION> officials say they now plan to leave nearly 200 miles of oiled coastline to be cleaned by nature. In <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION> President <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Stevens </PERSON> says, `` I believe we in <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION> have shown our commitment and our determination to deal responsibly with the spill and all its effects.'' Oil shows up in <LOCATION> Katmai </LOCATION> <LOCATION> National </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Park </LOCATION>, 300 miles from where the tanker grounded. _ MAY 5 Exxon spokesman <PERSON> Joe </PERSON> <PERSON> Tucker </PERSON> says cleanup is `` progressing on schedule.'' Oil is sighted 450 miles from where the tanker grounded. _ MAY 9 Coast Guard Vice Adm. <PERSON> Clyde </PERSON> <PERSON> Robbins </PERSON> says <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION> is as concerned with public relations as with cleaning up oil. `` They have sent PR people into the field instead of operators,'' he says. _ MAY 10 Exxon President <PERSON> Stevens </PERSON> tells a congressional committee the company `` fully expects to clean up'' by mid-September. The wildlife death toll climbs to 9,900 birds and 613 sea otters. _ MAY 24 `` I do n't think that we would portray to you that we're going to take every stain out of all the rocks that are out there,'' says <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION> official <PERSON> Otto </PERSON> <PERSON> Harrison </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Valdez </LOCATION> `` Nor do I want to portray to you that I think that's necessary to be environmentally clean.'' _ JUNE 1 Coast Guard Commandant Adm. <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Yost </PERSON> says he sees progress but predicts that <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION> almost certainly will miss its mid-September deadline. `` I think there was too much optimism,'' he says. `` I think reality has set in.'' _ JUNE 14 Exxon officials hedge on their September deadline. `` It's always a hope,'' says <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Amos </PERSON> <PERSON> Plante </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Seward </LOCATION>. `` But it's tougher to predict whether we'll do it by then. That's our plan We've always said we will not leave it uncleaned, and if that means coming back, so be it.''
