<FIRST>s a BC-Spill'sReach-OilRegulation Adv24-25   06-21 1067</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Spill's Reach-Oil Regulation, Adv 24-25,1095</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv24</HEAD>
<HEAD>$Adv25</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Weekend Editions, June 24-25, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Big Oil Faces More Regulation in Alaska as Result of Oil Spill</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-Spill's Reach</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRIAN S. AKRE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JUNEAU, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION>'s sense of betrayal by <ORGANIZATION> Big </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Oil </ORGANIZATION> is leading to stronger regulation of the state's most profitable industry in the long wake of the Exxon Valdez oil spill. It was 12 years ago this week that oil began flowing through the 800-mile trans-Alaska pipeline. Since then, the state has used its oil wealth to build roads and schools, boost its economy and keep its taxes low. But in the 12 weeks since the spill fouled Prince <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Sound </PERSON>, Alaskans have expressed anger over the industry's broken promise that it could protect the environment from such a disaster. `` Now that we've seen the down side we're going to be much more cautious about our relationship with the industry,'' said state <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> President <PERSON> Tim </PERSON> <PERSON> Kelly </PERSON>, a longtime industry supporter. `` The message I get from my constituents is the state's going to have to be more vigilant in its own regulation of the industry, and we ca n't depend on the industry or other government entities to do that for us,'' <PERSON> Kelly </PERSON> said. State legislators last month passed an initial package of bills aimed at preventing future spills and narrowly approved a measure to cut an oil-industry tax break. The change will cost the oil companies operating on <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION>'s North Slope an estimated $ 2 billion over the next 20 years. <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Webb </PERSON>, head of an Anchorage-based group that represents oil-support businesses, is one of the few industry officials who has spoken publicly against what they see as political overreaction. `` I guess I'm shocked, confused and extremely concerned about where the state's relationship with its biggest industry is and where it's heading,'' <PERSON> Webb </PERSON> said last week. `` This is the worst I've ever seen it. The tax changes and additional restrictions on the industry sent an anti-development message about <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION> to the Lower 48, <PERSON> Webb </PERSON> asserted. `` I've never seen any state that's turned and tried to do damage to their industry like <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION> has tried to do now,'' <PERSON> Webb </PERSON> said. `` Can you imagine <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION> trying to do to the auto industry what we're trying to do to oil?'' <PERSON> Kelly </PERSON> said he has seen no signs that <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION>'s pro-development image has been tarnished by its recent actions against Big Oil. `` They're not happy, but I think that we're playing under a different set of rules,'' he said. `` As the new rules are understood and stability again returns to the <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION> economy, I think they're going to work out `` There may be some short-range exploration and production losses, but in the long range the fact remains that the industry has to go where the oil is. The oil does n't go to them.'' Republican <PERSON> Kelly </PERSON> voted to maintain the oil tax break, but he has helped lead the post-spill campaign for more regulation. He and other legislators acknowledge that industry, state and federal officials became complacent about the risks involved in transporting oil across <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION>. `` I think after a decade of no serious and major accidents, that we assumed that was the norm,'' the <LOCATION> Anchorage </LOCATION> lawmaker said. `` There was a tendency of urban-area legislators to accept at face value what the industry told us, because a lot of us felt what was good for the oil industry was good for <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION>.'' Money helped lawmakers forget the state's watchdog role, said Sen. <PERSON> Pat </PERSON> <PERSON> Pourchot </PERSON>, an Anchorage Democrat. `` When everybody's making money and everybody's feeling good about the economy, it's natural to think of yourself in partnership with the industry. You're making money, they're making money _ it's sort of a ` we' kind of thing,'' <PERSON> Pourchot </PERSON> said Many recall 1981 as a watershed year for the <ORGANIZATION> Legislature </ORGANIZATION>, a year in which oil and development concerns began to outweigh environmental concerns. The Republican-led <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> especially became dominated by industry defenders. The Legislature, like the state, was infused with new Alaskans, many of whom had benefitted financially from the oil boom and wanted to see it last, <PERSON> Pourchot </PERSON> said. `` The whole view of boom, boom, boom and growth sort of swept the state at that point,'' he said. In 1981 the <ORGANIZATION> Legislature </ORGANIZATION> restructured the way state oil taxes are calculated and passed the tax break that remained untouched until this year. Proponents of the changes said the cost to the state would be negligible. `` In fact, it was a billion-dollar-plus loss to the state'' after just five years, said Rep. <PERSON> Sam </PERSON> <PERSON> Cotten </PERSON>, speaker of the Democratic-led House. Although <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION> has spent and saved billions of oil dollars, some argue that its primary failure in the past decade was not getting more money from its oil to secure the state's future when the pipeline runs dry. Sen. <PERSON> Jay </PERSON> <PERSON> Kerttula </PERSON>, a Democrat who has served in the <ORGANIZATION> Legislature </ORGANIZATION> since 1960, said lawmakers lost sight of their role as stewards of the oil for future generations. `` The wrinkles were out of the bellies of Alaskans, they were sitting there watching TV and not paying attention to their public ownership responsibilities,'' he said. `` We were n't paying attention to the bottom line.'' Throughout the past decade, development-oriented legislators opposed increased funding for the <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Environmental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Conservation </ORGANIZATION>. At times the agency was given additional responsibilities without additional funding. When Commissioner <PERSON> Dennis </PERSON> <PERSON> Kelso </PERSON> took over the department two years ago, its employees were working a four-day week because of budget cuts. He estimated then that the agency was $ 10 million short of the budget it needed to meet the minimum requirements of state and federal laws. But <PERSON> Kelso </PERSON> insists the cuts did not create the conditions that led to the <LOCATION> Valdez </LOCATION> spill and the slow cleanup. He blames <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Alyeska </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pipeline </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, the consortium of oil companies that runs the pipeline, for failing to follow their own policies and the state-approved spill-cleanup plan. Next year, when most legislators face re-election and a new governor will be elected, oil industry influence will be a major campaign issue, <PERSON> Cotten </PERSON> says. But <PERSON> Kerttula </PERSON> doubts concern over <ORGANIZATION> Big </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Oil </ORGANIZATION>'s influence will last long in a state that gets 85 percent of its revenues from the oil industry. `` The industry always wins,'' he said. `` They've got very strong economic clout and they're very firmly in control.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Weekend Editions, June 24-25</NOTE>
