<FIRST>s a BC-Spill'sReach-Psychology Adv24-25   06-21 0732</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Spill's Reach-Psychology, Adv 24-25,0751</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv24</HEAD>
<HEAD>$Adv25</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Weekend Editions, June 24-25, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Alaskans Seek Ways To Lessen Emotional Impact Of Spill</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-Spill's Reach</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID FOSTER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEWARD, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Chris </PERSON> <PERSON> Campabello </PERSON> once made $ 10 an hour as a clerk in a <LOCATION> Prudhoe </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bay </LOCATION> oilfield camp. Now she is working for free, helping to rescue sea otters caught in the nation's biggest oil spill. Each day from 6 a.m. to noon, she cracks clams and slices fish to feed ailing otters. Each day, she feels a little better about herself and a little worse about Big Oil. `` I used to believe in the oil companies. It was my job, and I did n't want things to go badly for them,'' she says. `` I've changed a lot.'' So have many Alaskans in the last three months. The wreck of the Exxon Valdez unleashed a flood of emotion across the nation as people mourned a pristine environment's lost innocence and voiced anger at those who let it happen. For many Alaskans, the anger and grief were compounded by the sense of personal responsibility that comes from living in a state heavily dependent on oil money. `` The relationship of Alaskans and oil development has always been one of uncomfortable resignation,'' says <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Gist </PERSON>, a community psychologist from <LOCATION> Overland </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Park </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Kan. </LOCATION>, who helped <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION> officials respond to the disaster. While some have likened the spill to a death in the family, <PERSON> Gist </PERSON> says it's more like a messy divorce. `` In the end, you're always telling yourself that you should have known better, that you should n't have trusted the other so much,'' he says. Exxon accepted the blame for the accident, but many Alaskans could n't help but internalize the guilt, Gist says. `` Intellectually, folks know better. But emotionally, lots of people feel it. They say, ` I must have sold out.''' A good way to heal such emotional wounds, Gist says, is to regain control by doing something _ anything _ to set things right. Many Alaskans are following that advice. Cleanup officials and environmental groups have been flooded with calls from Alaskans wanting to know what they can do to help. <PERSON> Otter </PERSON> and bird rescue centers have more volunteers than they can use. `` When the spill hit, I got really upset,'' says Campabello, 29, who is camping in a tent-trailer while volunteering at the Seward otter rescue center. `` I felt it was really important not to sit back and not do anything.'' Reaction to the spill has evolved since March 24. `` The anger has turned more to soul-searching, I think,'' says <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Henry </PERSON>, a schoolteacher in the southeastern <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION> town of <LOCATION> Haines </LOCATION>. `` Exxon and -LRB- tanker Capt. <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> -RRB- <PERSON> Hazelwood </PERSON> are easy to blame. But we are all to blame,'' <PERSON> Henry </PERSON> says. `` The people who are outraged are the very same people who moved to <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION> because they loved the pristine environment, and then supported the oil industry. They love the world around them, but they brought their selfishness up with them.'' He admits he was among them, each year eagerly collecting his dividend check from the <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION> Permanent Fund, a state savings account fueled by oil revenues. Last year, the fund distributed $ 826 to every Alaskan. `` My dividend check is blood money,'' <PERSON> Henry </PERSON> says. `` I can not hold it in good conscience to accept that money anymore.'' He plans to send this year's check to an environmental group and is urging others to do the same. Gist says volunteering or getting politically active is valuable, even if it accomplishes nothing but peace of mind. The key is doing something that gives hope. <PERSON> Henry </PERSON> tells of some school kids in Homer who seemed to know that without being told. As adults frantically built log booms to guard the <LOCATION> Kenai </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Peninsula </LOCATION> town from drifting oil, the children were on the beach, scratching messages in the sand. They wrote things like `` Ocean, we love you,'' and `` We're sorry, Mr. Sea.'' They called them prayers to the ocean, and when one of the children returned later to the beach, she ran to the same spot. The tide, of course, had wiped the beach clean, but the little girl was not disappointed. `` Look!'' she said. `` The ocean got our prayers.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Foster </PERSON> is the <ORGANIZATION> AP </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Northwest </ORGANIZATION> regional reporter, based in <LOCATION> Seattle </LOCATION>.
