<HEAD>For Release Sunday, June 25 and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Futrell-Shanker Rivalry Ends Amicably</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Teacher President</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 When <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> <PERSON> Hatwood </PERSON> <PERSON> Futrell </PERSON> became president of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Education </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, she often found herself overshadowed by <PERSON> Albert </PERSON> <PERSON> Shanker </PERSON>, the longtime president of the rival <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Federation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Teachers </ORGANIZATION>. `` I would make a statement and it was like you made a statement. Half an hour later, <PERSON> Shanker </PERSON> would come back and say the same thing and people acted like he was a guru,'' she said. `` He is the AFT. It is like a cult.'' <PERSON> Futrell </PERSON> says she learned not to compete with <PERSON> Shanker </PERSON>, a philosopher and provocateur with a knack for grabbing headlines, and instead to talk and react from a teacher's perspective. `` Now a lot of those people have come to respect and appreciate me,'' she said. The AFT, which claims about 700,000 members to the <ORGANIZATION> NEA </ORGANIZATION>'s 2 million, embraced the education reform movement from the start, while the lumbering <ORGANIZATION> NEA </ORGANIZATION> edged onto the bandwagon late and largely due to prodding by <PERSON> Futrell </PERSON>. The two union leaders `` had some really bad clashes at the beginning,'' <PERSON> Futrell </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Shanker </PERSON>, the AFT president since 1974, now calls them `` the usual clashes of two rival organizations trying to pick up members.'' Now, <PERSON> Futrell </PERSON> says, `` we get along fine.'' Both insist the other has changed. `` He has promoted himself to the position of statesperson so he ca n't fight like he used to. It would not be becoming to him,'' says <PERSON> Futrell </PERSON>, referring to <PERSON> Shanker </PERSON>'s heavy involvement with the business community and the political establishment. <PERSON> Shanker </PERSON> contends that <PERSON> Futrell </PERSON> started off with the typical NEA view of reform _ `` Why are these people criticizing the schools? Make them go away. Everything is pretty good.'' Unlike many, he said, <PERSON> Futrell </PERSON> eventually became convinced that improvements were needed. `` She underwent a change, a growth,'' <PERSON> Shanker </PERSON> said. `` She's a different person today ... than she was three years ago. She's been the best spokesperson for the <ORGANIZATION> NEA </ORGANIZATION> that I've ever known.''
</TEXT>
