<HEAD>Departing NEA Chief Gives Bennett Worst Marks as Education Secretary</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Teacher President</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The three education secretaries of the last nine years would get grades ranging from A-minus to D from <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> <PERSON> Hatwood </PERSON> <PERSON> Futrell </PERSON>, the outgoing president of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Education </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Futrell </PERSON> gives her lowest mark of D to former secretary <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON>, who made repeated assaults on her organization during her six-year tenure. `` <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> did n't know how to get people to work with him,'' she said in an interview. `` He reminds me of the person who desperately wants people to work with them and like them but does n't know how to do it. He knew how to give the speech but he did n't know how to get the people to follow him.'' <PERSON> Futrell </PERSON> reserves her highest mark of A-minus for <PERSON> Terrel </PERSON> <PERSON> Bell </PERSON>, President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s first education secretary. `` Bell was the leader, the one who had the vision, the substance. He understood education,'' she said. <PERSON> Futrell </PERSON> noted that <PERSON> Bell </PERSON> instituted the annual `` wall chart,'' a state-by-state comparison of education indicators, and commissioned the `` Nation at Risk'' report that fueled the education reform movement. `` He saved the department,'' she said, alluding to <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s campaign pledges to abolish it. The current secretary, <PERSON> Lauro </PERSON> <PERSON> Cavazos </PERSON>, receives a C-plus or B-minus from <PERSON> Futrell </PERSON>. `` He's not being allowed to do well,'' she said. `` Like <ORGANIZATION> Bell </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Cavazos </PERSON> understands the issues. But he does not have the kind of support he needs to do the job. He's being hamstrung right now.''
