 A federal judge has approved an unprecedented civil securities fraud settlement between the government and <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Burnham </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lambert </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Milton </PERSON> <PERSON> Pollack </PERSON> on Tuesday placed the Wall Street firm under strict supervision and barred it from dealing with its former junk bond financier, <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Milken </PERSON> The decision cleared the way for <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> to plead guilty to six felonies and pay a record $ 650 million in order to settle separate criminal charges with the <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The major oil companies have announced plans to create a nationwide network of oil-spill response teams capable of handling an accident as large as the <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Valdez </ORGANIZATION> disaster anywhere on <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> coastal waters. The companies, including <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION>, also proposed measures Tuesday designed to prevent future spills and to establish clearer lines of government authority for reacting to tanker accidents. Environmental groups called the program a step in the right direction. The new system is expected to be in full operation within one year.
