<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Procter </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Gamble </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> says it plans to fund projects to recycle the plastic from disposable diapers into such things as flower pots, garbage bags and park benches. The pulp of the diapers will be used in cardboard boxes, building insulation and wallboard liner, the company said at a news conference Tuesday. About 16 billion disposable diapers are used and discarded in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> each year. Environmentalists warn that the plastic-coated disposable diapers do n't decompose. That, they say, could provide breeding grounds for dangerous viruses and bacteria.
