<HEAD>House Committee Favors More Trade Benefits To Caribbean</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ways </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Means </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> has voted in favor of making permanent a system of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> trade preferences for <LOCATION> Caribbean </LOCATION> nations and to extend the program to textiles. The liberalization of the Reagan-era Caribbean Basin Initiative also would establish a guaranteed minimum floor for <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> imports of sugar from the region at present quota levels. Some committee members expressed concern Tuesday that the bill could work to the disadvantage of <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION> and other sugar-exporting nations. Rep. <PERSON> Sam </PERSON> <PERSON> Gibbons </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Fla </LOCATION>., chairman of the Ways and Means trade subcommittee, said nothing in the measure would alter present sugar quotas from countries outside the <LOCATION> Caribbean </LOCATION> Since the <LOCATION> Caribbean </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Basin </LOCATION> Initiative was enacted in 1983 to help lift the economy of the region, it has allowed duty-free import of a variety of <LOCATION> Caribbean </LOCATION> exports. But it specifically exempts several major categories, especially textiles. The Caribbean Basin Initiative expansion approved by the committee removes the exception for textiles and apparel. It would permit duty-free imports of fabric and clothing made from materials deemed to be in short supply in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, and of textiles from U.S.-made and - cut fabrics that are sewn in the <LOCATION> Caribbean </LOCATION> The new legislation would mean <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> buyers would no longer have to pay an 8.1 percent tariff on clothes imported from the <LOCATION> Caribbean </LOCATION>. Rep. <PERSON> Ed </PERSON> <PERSON> Jenkins </PERSON>, D-Ga., sought unsuccessfully to eliminate from the bill most of the concessions toward <LOCATION> Caribbean </LOCATION> apparel `` This bill is a direct attack on the textile workers,'' he said. <PERSON> Jenkins </PERSON>' amendment would have required that any increase in <LOCATION> Caribbean </LOCATION> textiles be offset by reductions in imports allowed from <LOCATION> Asia </LOCATION>.
