<HEAD>Tensions In International Trade Increasing, Says Report</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Tensions have increased in international trade and the commitment of governments to free trade talks is facing its `` sternest test,'' says the organization sponsoring the talks. The 1988 U.S. Trade Act could have the greatest short-term adverse impact on the world trading system, the secretariat of the 96-nation General Agreement on Tariffs and <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> said Tuesday in a six-month review. The so-called Section 301 of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> law could lead to moves aimed at pressuring countries into bilateral trade accords outside <ORGANIZATION> GATT </ORGANIZATION>'s international trade rules, the review said. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> last month singled out <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION> for priority action under the law that calls for penalties against countries deemed to be especially protectionist. <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> will raise the issue at the two-day council meeting beginning Wednesday, which is part of the latest four-year <ORGANIZATION> GATT </ORGANIZATION> talks known as the <LOCATION> Uruguay </LOCATION> Round, a <ORGANIZATION> GATT </ORGANIZATION> source said on condition of anonymity. The review said although much progress had been made in the <LOCATION> Uruguay </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Round </LOCATION>, there had been `` a further increase in the uncertainties and tensions affecting trade policies'' in the period reviewed, the six months until last February.
</TEXT>
