<HEAD>Grapefruit Exports Set Record</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LAKELAND, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> exported a record 23.5 million cartons of grapefruit this year, up 14 percent from the 1987-88 season, citrus officials said. <PERSON> Arthur </PERSON> <PERSON> Chadwell </PERSON>, general manager of the <ORGANIZATION> Citrus </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administrative </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, attributed the sharp rise to favorable currency exchange rates and increased spending on foreign promotions by the state <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Citrus </ORGANIZATION>. He said <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> remained the biggest importer, buying 12 million cartons, up 10 percent from a year ago, followed by <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, which bought 8.8 million cartons, up 4 percent. The fastest-growing market was <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>, whose imports of 609,000 were 306 percent higher than the previous year, <PERSON> Chadwell </PERSON> said Monday. A grapefruit carton holds four-fifths of a bushel of fruit, or about half of an 85-pound box. Fresh orange exports totaled 154,000 cartons, down from about 200,000 last season. Total fresh citrus shipments of all varieties through early June, both domestic and offshore, fell 3.2 percent to 68.9 million cartons.
