<SECOND>PM-Abortion Show, Bjt,0671</SECOND>
<HEAD>ABC Radio to Run Abortion Special Despite Lack Of Ads</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SKIP WOLLENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> ABC </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Radio </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Network </ORGANIZATION> officials say a special program on abortion hosted by <PERSON> Barbara </PERSON> <PERSON> Walters </PERSON> will run today even though national advertisers refused to buy time on the program. The 54-minute special airs starting at 2:06 p.m. EDT on about 144 radio stations across the country, <ORGANIZATION> ABC </ORGANIZATION> said. <PERSON> Lou </PERSON> <PERSON> Severine </PERSON>, senior vice president of sales for the network, said Tuesday that he was able to find only one buyer _ <ORGANIZATION> ABC </ORGANIZATION>'s `` 20-20'' television show, which also features Ms. <PERSON> Walters </PERSON> _ for one minute of the six minutes that were allocated for national ads He said advertisers `` are scared to death of the abortion topic. ... They just do n't want to be involved with any controversy.'' But <PERSON> Philip </PERSON> <PERSON> Giordano </PERSON>, senior vice president at the radio network, said the program was so important to the network's objectives of providing timely programs on compelling topics that <ORGANIZATION> ABC </ORGANIZATION> was prepared to absorb all of the costs of producing the show. The costs can run to $ 12,000, he said. It is the latest example of advertisers backing way from programs that have either offended or risk offending individuals or groups who have become increasingly vocal in complaining about controversial subjects on radio and TV. The <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION> television network, for instance, had to cut prices to find buyers for ad time on the made-for-TV movie `` Roe Vs. <PERSON> Wade </PERSON>,'' which ran last month and dealt with the case that led to the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>'s 1973 decision that legalized abortion. Advertisers have backed out of shows such as <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION>'s `` Saturday Night Live'' and the <PERSON> Fox </PERS