ers are lining up to get a piece of it. Despite skepticism, <PERSON> Guy </PERSON> <PERSON> Cook </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> Machinists </ORGANIZATION> union District Lodge 143, emerged Tuesday from a meeting with <PERSON> Checchi </PERSON> confident that the airline could carry through its plan to double in size in the next five years. `` I think it's probable at this point that we can establish that,'' said <PERSON> Cook </PERSON>, who heads a 20,000-member union, the airline's largest Not as confident were leaders of the 5,000-member <ORGANIZATION> Northwest </ORGANIZATION> pilots union, who also met with <PERSON> Checchi </PERSON> on Tuesday. `` Basically he said he feels that debt is his expertise and he only talked about it in general terms,'' said <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Halvorson </PERSON>, a spokesman for the <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Line </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pilots </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> unit. `` He said all the things you'd expect him to say. He told us not to worry.'' The pilots, who have an open contract and have threatened to strike if they do n't receive competitive wages and job security, have said <PERSON> Checchi </PERSON>'s deal would add debt that would be troublesome in an economic downturn and possibly lead to layoffs. But <PERSON> Checchi </PERSON> said his group's financing package is strong enough to carry the company through a recession as severe as the 1980-81 downturn. `` I would not enter any kind of transaction where the downside was not provided for,'' he said. <PERSON> Checchi </PERSON> promised to provide pilots with details of his financing package later in the week, <PERSON> Halvorson </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Halvorson </PERSON> said <PERSON> Checchi </PERSON> made a friendly gesture by saying he would consider giving <ORGANIZATION> Northwest </ORGANIZATION> employees a stake in the company. <PERSON> Checchi </PERSON>, 41, said the concept proved popular at other companies where he has worked, including <ORGANIZATION> Marriott </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp </ORGANIZATION>. But he said he wo n't discuss the measure until the pilots settle on a contract because it may be viewed as an attempt at gaining employee concessions <PERSON> Cheechi </PERSON> said he hopes to close the deal within about four weeks after the $ 121-a-share tender offer is launched Friday.
