<HEAD>Dollar Fluctuates in Narrow Range, Gold Falls</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The dollar ebbed and flowed in a narrow range today, gaining against <LOCATION> European </LOCATION> currencies. Gold was down. Traders in <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION> said the dollar's most significant movements in the past few days came in Asian trading, while European trading was calm. In <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, the central bank intervened as the pound sterling dropped as low as $ 1.5297 in the morning. The British currency also slipped to 3.0498 West German marks, but rallied to 3.0531 after the <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> England </ORGANIZATION> stepped in. One dealer in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> said the pound may have been hurt by strikes that shut down rail, subway and bus service in the capital. `` If one's got to hitchhike to work, it does n't put sterling in good grace,'' the dealer said. In <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>, where trading ends before the European markets open, the dollar closed at 144.95, up 1.15 yen from Tuesday's close. Other late rates for the dollar in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, compared with Tuesday's late rates, included: 1.9915 West German marks, up from 1.9775; 1.7278 Swiss francs, up from 1.7110; 6.7530 French francs, up from 6.7025; 2.2446 Dutch guilders, up from 2.2255; 1,443.00 Italian lire, up from 1.431.75; and 1.1977 Canadian dollars, down from 1.2000. In <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, one British pound cost $ 1.5320, down from $ 1.5553 late Tuesday. Gold opened in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> at $ 364.75, down from Tuesday's closing price of $ 366.50. At mid-morning, the city's five major gold dealers fixed a recommended price of $ 365.70. Earlier in <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION> gold closed at $ 366.57, down from $ 366.95 late Tuesday. Silver bullion traded late in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> at $ 5.26 bid a troy ounce, from $ 5.34.
