<HEAD>Tokyo Stocks Higher, Dollar Up 1.15 Yen</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Tokyo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>'s main index closed higher today after early declines, while the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> dollar gained against the Japanese yen. The doller closed at 144.95 yen, up 1.15 yen from Tuesday's 143.80-yen close It opened at 144.85 yen and fluctuated from 144.73 yen to 145.03 yen. Traders said the dollar's strength followed its higher trend in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> overnight. <PERSON> Yutaka </PERSON> <PERSON> Nakamura </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> Daiwa </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> trader, said the currency stayed just below 145 yen most of the day. `` Selling for profit-taking also helped to halt the dollar's further rise,'' he said `` Toward the end of the day, the dollar moved slightly up against the yen as it rose against the major <LOCATION> European </LOCATION> currencies,'' <PERSON> Nakamura </PERSON> added. The <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Japan </ORGANIZATION> sold an estimated $ 200 million in efforts to curb the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> currency's rise, but it did not have much impact on trading, <PERSON> Nakamura </PERSON> said. The central bank does not comment on its foreign exchange market activities. Trading was inactive mainly because of uncertainties, he added. On the stock exchange, the 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average, which gained 220.29 points the previous day, added another 111.81 points, or 0.34 percent, closing at 33,345.28. After early losses, the index reversed the trend and rose in the afternoon. <PERSON> Kazuhiro </PERSON> <PERSON> Nomura </PERSON>, a dealer with <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Japan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, said the index began to climb when institutional investors bought `` a substantial amount'' of cheaper issues. In addition, he said, foreign investors were buying in arbitrage deals between the spot and futures markets. The dollar's rebound had no negative impact on Wednesday's stock trading, but trading was thin, <ORGANIZATION> Nomura </ORGANIZATION> said. Volume traded on the first section was estimated at 600 million shares, down from Tuesday's 700 million. `` Investors would not panic over dollar-yen fluctuations between 143 and 146 yen. But they are little motivated in buying at the moment since last week's wild fluctuations,'' <ORGANIZATION> Nomura </ORGANIZATION> added. Last week, the dollar closed at 151.30 yen on Thursday, its highest level in almost two years. It then lost 6.25 yen on Friday. Meanwhile, the <ORGANIZATION> Nikkei </ORGANIZATION> lost more than 1,100 points during the week. Among today's gainers were steel and shipbuilding issues.
