<HEAD>New Directions Loses Third Issue, But Leader's Happy</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: CORRECTS typo in `feel' in final graf; convention convenes at
noon EDT; PMs lead unlikely.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto ANS1 of June 20</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ANAHEIM, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Auto </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Workers </ORGANIZATION> dissident group lost a third, key battle at the union's constitutional convention, but despite the outcome, the group's leader says he is happy with the way it went. About 2,000 delegates to the <ORGANIZATION> UAW </ORGANIZATION>'s constitutional convention turned back an attempt Tuesday by the New Directions movement to limit Japanese-style labor-management programs on factory floors. The decision came on two show-of-hands votes in which no more than 20 percent of the delegates supported the New Directions effort. Today, delegates are scheduled elect top national and regional officers. <ORGANIZATION> UAW </ORGANIZATION> President <PERSON> Owen </PERSON> <PERSON> Bieber </PERSON> faces no opposition to a third, three-year term. The convention also will elect two vice presidents to replace retiring vice presidents <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> Ephlin </PERSON> and <PERSON> Marc </PERSON> <PERSON> Stepp </PERSON>. Later, <PERSON> Bieber </PERSON> will assign the vice presidents to head the union's various departments, including one for each of the Big Three automakers and another with administrative responsibility for agricultural implement and aerospace workers covered by the union Despite the overwhelming loss Tuesday, New Directions leader <PERSON> Jerry </PERSON> <PERSON> Tucker </PERSON> of <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Louis </LOCATION> said he was happy with his troops and their reception. `` I think it was a good debate,'' he said. `` Debate on the floor today was healthy.'' <PERSON> Tucker </PERSON> held out the possibility that there would be more from New Directions forces, especially next year when the <ORGANIZATION> UAW </ORGANIZATION> plots its strategies for negotiations with the Big Three automakers. Contracts between the <ORGANIZATION> UAW </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> expire Sept. 14, 1990. <PERSON> Tucker </PERSON> said he was pleased with the way <PERSON> Bieber </PERSON> handled the debate, which sometimes got a little rowdy, and hoped that delegates would take the New Directions message back to their locals. `` The rank and file will ultimately find ways to express themselves,'' he said. The loss Tuesday was the third by New Directions forces since the convention opened Sunday. It winds up Friday. During the first two days of the convention, <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Directions </ORGANIZATION> backers failed in an attempt to require rank-and-file referendum voting for top national officers, instead of a vote by convention delegates, and lost a credentials fight for seating some delegations. Members of the movement made a loud entrance to the convention hall Tuesday. About 250 delegates and alternates paraded in carrying signs and shouting: `` What do we need? New Directions. When do we want it? Right now.'' <PERSON> Bieber </PERSON> ignored the parade as it passed in front of the stage. Delegate <PERSON> Tony </PERSON> <PERSON> Torres </PERSON> of Local 653 in <LOCATION> Pontiac </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mich. </LOCATION>, stood on a chair in front of <PERSON> Bieber </PERSON>, waved a New Directions placard and shouted, `` We do n't have to go to <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>; Injustice is right here.'' <PERSON> Tucker </PERSON> watched the demonstration from the stage. When asked how it made him feel, he said, `` Bigger.''
