<HEAD>FDIC Chief Considers Seeking More Power Over S&amp;L Bailout</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDs: SUBS last graf with 5 new grafs to include Treasury Department
comment</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Seidman </PERSON>, who would become the new deposit insurance czar under legislation moving through <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, is conferring with the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration about an idea that would enhance his power over the savings and loan bailout. Under the plan, <PERSON> Seidman </PERSON>, chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Deposit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Insurance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, would have greater authority than originally envisioned by the administration within the <ORGANIZATION> Resolution </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trust </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, a new agency being created to oversee the closing or sale of insolvent thrift institutions and of real estate repossessed by the <ORGANIZATION> S </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; Ls. Under bills passed by the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> RTC </ORGANIZATION> will be run by a board headed by the <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> secretary. It would have an oversight staff, headed by an executive director. But, as the administration envisions the structure, most of the work would be contracted out, presumably to the <ORGANIZATION> FDIC </ORGANIZATION>. According to an industry official, who spoke on condition of anonymity, <PERSON> Seidman </PERSON> wants the <ORGANIZATION> FDIC </ORGANIZATION> to report directly to the <ORGANIZATION> RTC </ORGANIZATION> oversight board rather than through a staff working for the board. Ultimate authority would still rest with the <ORGANIZATION> RTC </ORGANIZATION> board, but without the separate staff there would be less opportunity for administration second-guessing of <PERSON> Seidman </PERSON>'s agency. Also, the <ORGANIZATION> FDIC </ORGANIZATION> _ not the <ORGANIZATION> RTC </ORGANIZATION> board _ in practice would choose which private firms are hired for the lucrative job of assisting the government in the huge undertaking. <PERSON> Seidman </PERSON>, in a telephone interview Tuesday, declined to say his agency is advocating the idea, but he described it as `` worth exploring'' and `` feasible.'' `` It's not our idea. It came from a suggestion that the <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION> -LRB- the congressional <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Accounting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> -RRB- made. We have been talking to <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> about it,'' he said. The <ORGANIZATION> RTC </ORGANIZATION>, under legislation that passed the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> last week and the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> in April, will have the mammoth task of spending $ 50 billion in new bailout funds and of handling $ 300 billion to $ 500 billion of bad loans and property. That would make it, if it were private, the largest corporation in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. The legislation does not spell out how the <ORGANIZATION> RTC </ORGANIZATION> will be structured beyond the composition of its board and the fact that it must hire a chief executive officer. It does not define the relationship between the <ORGANIZATION> FDIC </ORGANIZATION> and RTC. However, <PERSON> Seidman </PERSON> has said he does not want his agency to get expanded responsibility without added authority to control the conditions and terms under which it does the additional work. <PERSON> Seidman </PERSON> said if the <ORGANIZATION> FDIC </ORGANIZATION> were not given the added authority, and were simply a contractor of the <ORGANIZATION> RTC </ORGANIZATION>, it would want to pick and choose what S & amp; L liquidation work it wanted. Assistant Treasury Secretary <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Mullins </PERSON> said the administration has planned all along for the <ORGANIZATION> FDIC </ORGANIZATION> to take the lead role in disposing of failed S & amp; Ls. At issue, he said, is the vigor of administration oversight. `` No one likes the idea of a full-time person overseeing them. But our view is we're required to have oversight,'' he said. The <ORGANIZATION> FDIC </ORGANIZATION> `` wants as much independence as -LRB- it -RRB- can get, but there's a limit as to what can be done on that.''
</TEXT>
