<FIRST>r f PM-BenefitsStudy     06-21 0524</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Benefits Study,0541</SECOND>
<HEAD>Employees Have More Savings Choices, Pay More Medical Costs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LINCOLNSHIRE, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Salaried employees of large <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> companies are paying a bigger share of their medical expenses than they did five years ago, according to a soon-to-be-released study of employee benefits. The same workers face a wider array of employer-sponsored savings plans, and are increasingly being asked to take a more active role in designing their own benefits packages. `` There is a desire among employers to involve employees more in all aspects of benefits,'' said <PERSON> Howard </PERSON> <PERSON> Levin </PERSON>, a partner in <ORGANIZATION> Hewitt </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Associates </ORGANIZATION>, the suburban <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> consulting firm that conducted the survey of 227 major employers. `` There's a sense that when employees participate, they get involved more and have a greater appreciation'' for their benefits, <PERSON> Levin </PERSON> said Tuesday in a telephone interview from his <LOCATION> Lincolnshire </LOCATION> office. The study will be released publicly early next month, said <PERSON> Hewitt </PERSON> spokeswoman <PERSON> Jean </PERSON> <PERSON> Campbell </PERSON>. Medical plans are paying more catastrophic-illness costs but employees are paying a larger share of other medical expenses, researchers discovered. <PERSON> Hewitt </PERSON> found that just 29 percent of the survey respondents' medical plans covered 100 percent of hospital room and board charges, compared with 53 percent in 1984 The more typical practice is for the plan to cover 80 percent of hospital charges and require employees to pay 20 percent up to a specified maximum, usually $ 2,000 or less. The plan then kicks in and pays 100 percent. Employers also are trying to better manage medical costs by encouraging employees to seek second surgical opinions and have medical tests done on an outpatient basis. In 1984, <PERSON> Hewitt </PERSON> found that 62 percent of companies surveyed offered the same medical coverage for surgery whether or not the employee got a second opinion. In 1988, only 29 percent of the respondents offered the same coverage regardless of whether a second opinion was obtained. `` Cost-sharing causes people to be more careful consumers of health-care services,'' <PERSON> Levin </PERSON> said. `` The employee who has to pay for part of any service they use is going to use more discretion.'' The survey revealed a dramatic increase _ from 56 percent in 1984 to 82 percent in 1988 _ in the prevalence of employer-sponsored 401 -LRB- k -RRB- plans. These optional savings plans usually supplement traditional pension plans and offer tax benefits superior to individual retirement accounts. Among retirement savings plans, the survey found a trend toward more investment options such as company stock, stock-market mutual funds and guaranteed-income instruments. <PERSON> Levin </PERSON> said retirement savings options have grown in response to the changing demographics of the work force, which was once composed mainly of married men with families but now includes large numbers of both sexes, married and single, some with children, some without. `` We have a work force with a much broader diversity of needs,'' he said. `` Some have high retirement-income needs, some have low-retirement income needs.'' In addition to providing a new way for employees to set aside money for retirement, a 401 -LRB- k -RRB- plan `` takes some of the pressure off of employers to funnel more dollars into the pension plan, no doubt about it,'' <PERSON> Levin </PERSON> said.
</TEXT>
