<HEAD>Crop Futures Continue Slide On Rain Forecasts</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Grain and soybean futures prices opened slightly lower today on the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION>, continuing a retreat prompted by forecasts for scattered thunderstorms in the <LOCATION> Midwest </LOCATION>. Traders are keeping a close watch on weather conditions in western <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION> and southwestern <LOCATION> Minnesota </LOCATION>, where rain was expected today. The threat of precipitation _ with expected amounts ranging from \ inch to 1 -LCB- inches _ is alleviating the drought fears that prompted a strong rally in the crop markets during the past week. Prices began falling on Tuesday. The showers are expected to move across the <ORGANIZATION> Corn </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Belt </ORGANIZATION> over the next several days, with clearing skies and cooler temperatures predicted for the weekend. The wheat market continued to be pressured by selling linked to harvest activity in the <LOCATION> Great </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Plains </LOCATION> and uncertainty over U.S.-China relations. Some experts fear tensions between the two countries may impede sales of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> grain to <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>. In early trading, wheat was 1 -LCB- cents to 1 -RCB- cents lower with the contract for delivery in July at $ 3.94 a bushel; corn was -RCB- cent to 1 -LCB- cents lower with July at $ 2.65 -LCB- a bushel; oats were -LCB- cent to 2 cents lower with July at $ 1.67 -RCB- a bushel; soybeans were 1 -RCB- cents to 4 \ cents lower with July at $ 7.33 a bushel Cattle futures were little changed while pork futures were mixed in early trading on the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>. Live cattle were unchanged to .22 cent lower with August at 70.45 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .17 cent lower to .13 cent higher with August at 81.35 cents a pound; live hogs were .23 cent to .45 cent higher wiith July at 49.55 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies were .17 cent to .30 cent lower with July at 34.20 cents a pound. Livestock and meat futures settled mixed on Tuesday.
