cquire the franchises to about 800 cable television systems <ORGANIZATION> Time </ORGANIZATION> owns. <PERSON> Appert </PERSON> said the takeover fight could turn on whether Time, in agreeing to the merger with <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION> in March, effectively put itself up for sale. If the courts decide that is the case, <ORGANIZATION> Time </ORGANIZATION> directors could be forced to seek the highest price for the company's stock and the <ORGANIZATION> Paramount </ORGANIZATION> bid might then succeed. Wall Street _ in depressing <ORGANIZATION> Time </ORGANIZATION>'s stock _ is betting the courts will side with <ORGANIZATION> Time </ORGANIZATION> and allow the directors to pursue an acquisition of <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION>. Meanwhile, in filings with the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communications </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> Tuesday, <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION> charged that <ORGANIZATION> Paramount </ORGANIZATION>'s bid for Time violates the 1984 Cable Act and FCC rules and <ORGANIZATION> Paramount </ORGANIZATION> told the commission it should set aside a ruling allowing Time to transfer control of its cable TV systems to <ORGANIZATION> Time-Warner </ORGANIZATION>. Paramount said Time had misrepresented to its stockholders the nature of the transfer and that <ORGANIZATION> Time </ORGANIZATION> had written to state attorneys general asking them to oppose <ORGANIZATION> Paramount </ORGANIZATION>'s proposal without notifying Paramount of the letters. These actions raise `` questions about Time's character qualifications,'' <ORGANIZATION> Paramount </ORGANIZATION> said, asking the <ORGANIZATION> FCC </ORGANIZATION> to set aside its approval of the license transfers pending an investigation. Paramount earlier this month asked the <ORGANIZATION> FCC </ORGANIZATION> for permission to give control of Time to former <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Donald </PERSON