<TEXT>
 A group of semiconductor companies today announced the formation of a manufacturing corporation that expects to raise more than $ 1 billion over several years to boost <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> production of memory chips. The plan, which sets up a corporation named <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Memories </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, calls for the venture to be funded by microchip makers and their major customers. Companies which contributed `` seed money'' to form the corporation include <ORGANIZATION> Advanced </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Micro </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Devices </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Digital </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Equipment </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Hewlett-Packard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Business </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Machines </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Intel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> LSI </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Logic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> and National Semiconductor. `` The time is right for a collective memory manufacturing venture in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> to improve <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s market position in what is truly a critical technology,'' said <PERSON> Sanford </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kane </PERSON>, president and chief executive officer of the newly formed corporation and a former vice president at <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION>. The venture is aimed at lessening the dependence on <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> for DRAMs, the dynamic random access memory chips that are important to computers, consumer electronics and advanced military hardware. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> companies, which once led the DRAM business, account for about 15 percent of the $ 12 billion North American market. Another chip consortium, called <ORGANIZATION> Sematech </ORGANIZATION>, researches new manufacturing technologies but can not build commercial products. It is funded with $ 100 million annually from the <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> and an equal amount from 14 <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> chipmakers. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Memories is expected to begin by setting up a high-volume plant to make a new generation of DRAM that can store 4 million bits of information. Japanese companies are just beginning to ship samples of the four-megabit varieties that offer four times the storage of the one-megabit chips often found in personal computers. <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Semiconductor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industry </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> has been organizing the consortium. `` Any consortium that brings together <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> electronics companies to further our global advantage is a step in the right direction,'' said <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Krause </PERSON>, chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Electronics </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>. `` I find this to be a very positive step.''
