<HEAD>Japanese Business Returning to China; Unlikely To Exploit Any U.S.
Void</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSAN MOFFAT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Japanese businessmen cautiously are returning to <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>, hoping to resume the business that they long have conducted in that market while remaining wary of another outbreak of unrest. Foreign Minister <PERSON> Hiroshi </PERSON> <PERSON> Mitsuzuka </PERSON> has criticized businessmen for returning too quickly _ saying they invited charges that they are `` trying to make money like a thief at a fire'' _ but the government has not formally asked firms to refrain from business. <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> has been more cautious in its criticism of <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> than the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, which is pushing for the suspension of all new <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> loans to protest the <LOCATION> Chinese </LOCATION> government's bloody suppression of pro-democracy demonstrations two weeks ago. `` For the time being the Japanese government is not considering sanctions,'' but is continuing to gather information, Chief Cabinet Secretary <PERSON> Masajuro </PERSON> <PERSON> Shiokawa </PERSON> told a news conference Wednesday. Nevertheless, on Tuesday Foreign Ministry officials said negotiations on a new five-year, $ 5.6 billion loan package to <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> were not being conducted, but <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> would decide whether to resume talks after watching the situation in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>. Sanctions by <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> could be more serious than sanctions by the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> because <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s trade with <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> is larger _ $ 19.3 billion last year _ and because <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> provides 80 percent of <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s foreign loans Prime Minister Sousuke Uno has expressed regret at the Chinese crackdown but so far has stressed maintaining good long-term ties with <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>. He and other officials have cited <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s pre-World War II invasion of <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> as a major reason for reluctance to criticize the Chinese government. The government's cautious attitude has been criticized as too weak by some of the Japanese press and some business leaders. But many businessmen want the government to help smooth resumption of business. They fear that <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> economic sanctions could harm the general business environment and the suspension of <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> loans could hurt <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s ability to conduct trade with <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>. If the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> cut trade ties with <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>, `` some Japanese companies might take up the slack,'' said <PERSON> Jan </PERSON> <PERSON> VanDenBerg </PERSON>, an economist at <ORGANIZATION> Merrill </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lynch </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>. `` However, it's unlikely they would take up the slack in <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> direct investment in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> sanctions would be a disincentive for anyone else to invest,'' she said. The Chinese government has been trying to woo foreign businessmen back with reassurances that its economic open-door policy remains intact. Some traders say <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> even has speeded up the normally glacial paperwork required to do business. Japanese traders view these assurances with skepticism, but like many Americans are trying to maintain business ties while carefully watching the situation, said <PERSON> Hiroaki </PERSON> <PERSON> Kasahara </PERSON>, general manager of the <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> department at <ORGANIZATION> Marubeni </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corporation </ORGANIZATION>. Major trading houses have sent limited numbers of staff back to <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> to carry out existing contracts and monitor the situation, said a trader who declined to be named. Trading houses said that even at the height of the unrest, shipments in and out of <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> did not stop, although there were some slowdowns. Production at a number of joint-venture factories far from <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Shanghai </LOCATION> were undisturbed by events in the capital. Japanese banks and securities houses do not plan to send staff back to <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> for now, while a number of manufacturers plan to proceed with plans for joint ventures, <ORGANIZATION> Japan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Broadcasting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corporation </ORGANIZATION> reported. <PERSON> Kumagai </PERSON> <PERSON> Gumi </PERSON>, a major construction company, said it has not resumed work on a 51-story <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> building stopped during the unrest. `` We're not sure yet if there are workers and materials available,'' said <PERSON> Makoto </PERSON> <PERSON> Sasaki </PERSON>, a company spokesman. None of the company employees who were evacuated have returned to <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> and it is unclear if they will, he said. But <ORGANIZATION> Yokogawa </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Electric </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Company </ORGANIZATION>, a major electrical machinery manufacturer, said its joint venture factory in <LOCATION> Xian </LOCATION> resumed production last week following a temporary shutdown during the unrest. Half of the Japanese China-based staff have returned to <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> and the company hopes to send the rest back later, said <PERSON> Tatsuya </PERSON> <PERSON> Ando </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Yokogawa </ORGANIZATION>'s public relations office. `` We have a very long history in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>, and we are not considering fundamentally rethinking our plans in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> just because of recent events,'' <PERSON> Ando </PERSON> said.
</TEXT>
