<HEAD>Georgia Barbecue Makers Offering Japanese Food _ To Japan</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 6th graf pvs, Nitto sent ..., with one graf to include
full first reference to Saga. SUBS 11th graf pvs, `We send ..., to conform.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELLIOTT MINOR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAVANNAH, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION> frozen food company known mainly for its chicken and barbecue is selling its new Japanese food in a crowded market _ <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>. But the overseas competition does n't worry <ORGANIZATION> R </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> H </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Food </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Enterprises </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, which is exploiting it's product's cost advantages to carve a niche in the market. `` It's cheaper to produce in <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>,'' said <PERSON> Don </PERSON> <PERSON> Hall </PERSON>, president of <ORGANIZATION> Savannah-based </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> R </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; H Food. `` Our labor is cheaper. Our costs of goods are cheaper. And even if you add in the shipping charges, it's still cheaper. Since Hall's company was established in 1981, it has produced chicken and dumplings, chicken pot pies, pork barbecue and such frozen rice dishes such as seafood and catfish gumbos. In 1987, <ORGANIZATION> R </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; H joined <ORGANIZATION> Nitto </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Food </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Products </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ltd. </ORGANIZATION>, a leading Japanese food manufacturer, and <ORGANIZATION> Nozaki </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> America </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, a Japanese trading company, in forming <ORGANIZATION> Georgia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pro </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foods </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>. Nitto sent <PERSON> Hideo </PERSON> <PERSON> Saga </PERSON>, a consultant for a Japanese company with which <ORGANIZATION> R </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; H markets the U.S.-made frozen dinners, to <LOCATION> Savannah </LOCATION> to develop test products, including `` beef-rice,'' a popular Japanese dish of rice, beef and vegetables <PERSON> Hall </PERSON>'s 50 employees ship 80,000 pounds of cooked beef a month to <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, the maximum allowed under a government-set quota. The beef, cooked and packed in six-pound pouches, is used in various Nitto products. Pro Foods also ships 40,000 pounds of frozen beef-rice a month, packed in plastic pouches that can be heated in boiling water or microwave ovens. To assure the authenticity of the dish, the rice is steamed in a Japanese rice cooker resembling a large safe, complete with a wheel to bolt it shut. Another Japanese machine keeps the beef slices to a thickness of between 1.5 and 2.5 millimeters, a tolerance specified by <PERSON> Nitto </PERSON>. A third Japanese machine known as a nitrogen tunnel cools the beef-rice pouches to minus-10 degrees Fahrenheit. The blast of nitrogen keeps the rice from clumping when heated and served. `` We send it to small restaurants and cafeterias. The people in the back know it was made in <LOCATION> Savannah </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ga. </LOCATION>, but not the customers,'' said Saga. Saga, who spent six years developing frozen and canned foods in <LOCATION> Nitto </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Yamagata </LOCATION> headquarters, has been assigned permanently to <LOCATION> Savannah </LOCATION>. He is one of two Japanese quality control consultants at Pro Foods. Nitto sends a new assistant every three months. Japanese consumers eat rice about three times a day, but have to pay about five times more than their <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> counterparts, said Saga. To protect growers, the Japanese government bars imports of cheaper foreign rice but permits foods containing rice. Beef, the second-most popular meat in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> after fish, must be imported because the Japanese can not produce enough to meet demand, said <PERSON> Hall </PERSON>. As a result, the wholesale price of beef is $ 8 to $ 12 a pound in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, compared to about $ 3.50 a pound for prime filet mignon at American grocery stores, he said. Saga is developing additional products for Pro Foods to export. His countrymen like Italian food, but probably would not enjoy chili and tacos, he said. Saga also does n't see a future for Hall's catfish gumbo, because in Japanese mythology catfish are thought to cause earthquakes. `` There are many catfish in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, but they are never eaten,'' <PERSON> Saga </PERSON> said. Hall believes there are many untapped opportunities for small companies such as <ORGANIZATION> R </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; H that want to sell to the Japanese. But the firms will have to supply products that meet their needs and specifications. `` The future is in small ventures,'' <PERSON> Hall </PERSON> said. `` There are 124 million Japanese living in an area the size of <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>. They all eat, they all sleep and they all drink ... The items that can be manufactured here to Japanese specifications are just unlimited.''
</TEXT>
