 <ORGANIZATION> A.H. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Robins </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Home </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Products </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> announced Wednesday that they have moved back to Dec. 31 the deadline for <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Home </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Products </ORGANIZATION> to buy the Richmond-based pharmaceutical company. Under the orginal purchase agreement, <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Home </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Products </ORGANIZATION> could terminate the purchase and withdraw from the Chapter 11 reorganization of <PERSON> Robins </PERSON> if all appeals of the plan were not cleared up by July 26. <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Home </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Products </ORGANIZATION> is purchasing <PERSON> Robins </PERSON> through a $ 700 million stock swap. Last week, the 4th U.S. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Richmond </LOCATION> affirmed a lower court ruling approving the reorganization plan. Part of the plan includes a $ 2.5 billion trust fund to pay off the claims of nearly 200,000 women who claimed physical injury from the use of the Robins' Dalkon Shield intrauterine birth control device. Both <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Home </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Products </ORGANIZATION> chairman <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Stafford </PERSON> and <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Claiborne </PERSON> <PERSON> Robins </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, president and chief executive officer of the pharmaceutical company, said the extension of the termination date would allow sufficient time for any appeals of the appeals court decision. `` We would like to get on with the completion of our acquisition of <ORGANIZATION> A.H. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Robins </ORGANIZATION>,'' <PERSON> Stafford </PERSON> said. `` We believe doing so promptly would be in the best interests of all concerned. If no appeals of the orders ... are taken to the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>, our present anticipation is that the transaction will be complete early in the fourth quarter of this year.'' <PERSON> Robins </PERSON> sought federal bankruptcy protection in 1985 in the wake of mounting claims from the use of the Dalkon Shield, marketed by the company in the mid-1970s. Women who used the IUD said they suffered injuries ranging from internal bleeding to sterility. After three years of hearings, the reorganization plan was approved by federal District Judge <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Merhige </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, and later by <PERSON> Robins </PERSON>' creditors. That approval was challenged by attorneys representing some of the claimants, who argued votes from women who claimed the greatest injury should be given a greater weight than other claimants.
