<HEAD>Ex-Banker Accused of Insider Trading Admits Fraud</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANIEL J. WAKIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A former <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> board member pleaded guilty Wednesday to illegally passing on confidential interest rate data in the first insider trading case involving government securities. In a plea agreement, <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> A. Rough, 50, pleaded guilty to a single bank fraud charge and the government in exchange dropped two insider trading charges and four related counts. Rough admitted leaking confidential data while he served as a <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION> board member from 1982 to 1984 to a securities firm that made about $ 50 million from the information. As part of the plea deal, prosecutors also agreed to recommend a prison term of under one year for the former banker. Rough faces a maximum five years in jail and $ 10,000 fine. Sentencing is set for Aug. 18. Rough's attorney, <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Himmel </PERSON>, said his client had sent letters of apology to the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. `` To me, it's certainly a step in the right direction, an example of contrition,'' <PERSON> Himmel </PERSON> said. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Dickinson </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Debevoise </PERSON> called the apologies a `` good step.'' Rough admitted giving a <PERSON> Livingston </PERSON> brokerage confidential data about the discount rate set by the <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION> and 11 sister regional banks make regular recommendations to the <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION> on the rate, which has a powerful bearing on government securities. Rough sat on the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION>'s board as president of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sussex </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> County </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Branchville </LOCATION>. He admitted leaking recommendations as well as advance word of a change in the <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION>'s discount rate The allegations surfaced during the 1987 trial of a <PERSON> Gilbert </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Schulman </PERSON>, president of the brokerage firm of <PERSON> Bevill </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Bresler </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Schulman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc </ORGANIZATION>. He and three other <PERSON> Bevill </PERSON>, <PERSON> Bresler </PERSON> officials were imprisoned for the firm's $ 144 million collapse in 1985. Rough admitted that he passed on the data to <PERSON> Schulman </PERSON>, a longtime friend and business associate, and other principals. The government said the information allowed the firm to make an estimated $ 50 million in profits and avoid losses. In exchange, Rough allegedly received $ 47,000 in interest deferred loans. After the charges were disclosed, the <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION> tightened its procedures regarding the discount rate. <PERSON> Himmel </PERSON> said Rough's disclosures were `` not done out of any motivation for greed or to line his pockets'' and blamed `` pumping and prodding by <PERSON> Gilbert </PERSON> <PERSON> Schulman </PERSON>.'' He claimed Rough probably would have received the loans from <PERSON> Bevill </PERSON>, <PERSON> Bresler </PERSON> regardless of whether he provided the information. <PERSON> Schulman </PERSON> had agreed to cooperate in the prosecution of Rough. <PERSON> Himmel </PERSON> said Rough, a former chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Jersey </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bankers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, admitted the facts outlined in those charges even though he was not required to plead guilty to them. In pre-trial arguments, <PERSON> Himmel </PERSON> argued the discount rate data had no inherent material value and was not comparable to information about stocks. But <PERSON> Debevoise </PERSON> disagreed, ruling that insider trading laws could apply to Rough's case. The insider trading charges would have carried a fine of $ 100,000 per count.
