<HEAD>Khomeini's Ghost Won't Haunt Oil Market, Strategists Say</HEAD>
<HEAD>Graphic in AP Access under IRANOIL</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SALLY JACOBSEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 When <PERSON> Ayatollah </PERSON> <PERSON> Ruhollah </PERSON> <PERSON> Khomeini </PERSON> triumphantly led <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> through a revolution a decade ago, oil output tumbled, world prices soared and shock waves hurt the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> economy. But analysts say that with the spiritual leader's death earlier this month, history wo n't repeat itself. `` It's business as usual,'' said <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Gignoux </PERSON>, director of the <ORGANIZATION> international </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> department </ORGANIZATION> at <ORGANIZATION> Shearson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lehman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hutton </ORGANIZATION> brokerage in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Fergus </PERSON> <PERSON> MacLeod </PERSON>, analyst at <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Barclays </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> de </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Zoete </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Wedd </ORGANIZATION>, said, `` In the short-term, the impact will be extremely limited.'' With the quick transfer of power to President ere have so far been no reports of instability that would threaten the flow of crude from one <PERSON> Ali </PERSON> <PERSON> Khamenei </PERSON>, thof the world's major producing nations. `` There does n't appear to be any civil disruptions which could unsettle the oil sector,'' said <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Mlotok </PERSON>, head of energy research at <ORGANIZATION> Morgan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stanley </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. The 1979 revolution, which brought <PERSON> Khomeini </PERSON> to power and ended the reign of <PERSON> Shah </PERSON> <PERSON> Mohammad </PERSON> <PERSON> Reza </PERSON> <PERSON> Pahlavi </PERSON>, was marked by unrest in the oilfields and a sharp drop in production. World oil prices soared, roiling the economies of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and other indus recently that <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> could produce 3.5 million barrels a day without any problem. `` We want to keep onshore and offshore production capacity for the next five years at a level of 4 million barrels a day,'' he said. Repairing its damaged industry would boost the slumping economy. <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> earned an estimated $ 9 billion last year from oil revenues, compared with $ 23.6 billion in 1977. With increased production and higher prices, 1989 earnings should climb to about $ 12 billion, analysts predict.
