<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Energy futures prices rose Wednesday, led by a rally in the heating oil market. On the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, the July heating oil contract jumped 2.29 cents to finish at 47.98 cents a gallon, while the August contract closed 2 cents higher at 48.07 cents a gallon. All other contracts posted healthy advances. Crude prices also made strong gains. The August contract for <ORGANIZATION> West </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Intermediate </ORGANIZATION>, the benchmark grade of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> crude oil, rose 43 cents to close at $ 19.31 a barrel. Contracts for later delivery showed similar increases. Among other refined oil products, meanwhile, unleaded gasoline for July fell 0.7 cent to 59.10 cents a gallon, but other contracts rose. Analysts said crude and heating oil prices got a strong boost from weekly <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Petroleum </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> statistics that showed a sharp decline in stocks from last year's levels. Crude oil inventories plunged by 25.2 million barrels from 1988 and were off 1.2 million barrels for the week ended June 16, the <ORGANIZATION> API </ORGANIZATION> said. Heating oil stocks fell 11.5 million barrels from last year and 1.6 million barrels for the week, according to the API report released after the close of trading on Tuesday. `` After the APIs came out and people saw that heating oil was running so far below last year, those who had been cutting back started to look at buying it again,'' said <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Unger </PERSON>, oil broker with <ORGANIZATION> Merrill </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lynch </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Futures </ORGANIZATION>. Unleaded gasoline stocks, meanwhile, rose by about 63,000 barrels last week and by 819,000 barrels from 1988 levels.
