<BYLINE>By MARCY GORDON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The champagne and string quartet are gone from the busy terminal at <LOCATION> LaGuardia </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Airport </LOCATION>, and even <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> Trump </PERSON> ca n't master the weather to make the flights run on time for his newly acquired <ORGANIZATION> Northeast </ORGANIZATION> shuttle airline But passengers say they like the service and the Trump Shuttle meets their needs as business travelers _ for them, the frills are secondary. The billionaire developer launched his new airline two weeks ago with a blitz of trademark Trump glitz, soon after a federal bankruptcy judge approved his $ 365 million purchase of the New York-Washington-Boston shuttle from strikebound <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Pan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Am </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, which operates a rival shuttle and gained a big chunk of business from <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION>, concedes that curiosity about <PERSON> Trump </PERSON>'s new service has robbed it of some passengers _ at least for a while. <ORGANIZATION> Pan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Am </ORGANIZATION>'s share of the shuttle market `` has definitely come down, as we expected,'' said <ORGANIZATION> Pan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Am </ORGANIZATION> spokeswoman <PERSON> Pamela </PERSON> <PERSON> Hanlon </PERSON>. That share was around 75 percent two weeks ago but has slipped since <PERSON> Trump </PERSON>'s startup to 65 percent to 70 percent, she estimated But Trump Shuttle President <PERSON> Bruce </PERSON> <PERSON> Nobles </PERSON> claims a bigger share for the new service, around 45 percent to 55 percent. `` I'm very pleased with the way the operation is running,'' he said Wednesday. <PERSON> Nobles </PERSON> added that he has been disappointed by the recent run of unseasonably stormy weather in the <LOCATION> Northeast </LOCATION>, which has caused many delays and cancellations. On Wednesday, the Trump Shuttle terminal at <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> LaGuardia </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Airport </LOCATION> was back to normal. The red and white balloons, Mozart-playing string quartet and buffet tables laden with champagne and finger food present for its inaugural day were gone, although new fresh plants and big red T's remained as permanent touches. Thunderstorms in the Northeast snarled the shuttle's hourly schedule and shattered <PERSON> Trump </PERSON>'s advertised claim for getting the flights off precisely on time. The red neon advisory warned of runway delays of up to 90 minutes. Passengers on the 7 a.m. EDT flight from <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> National </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Airport </LOCATION> to <ORGANIZATION> LaGuardia </ORGANIZATION> did n't arrive until 10:40 a.m., after a detour to <LOCATION> Albany </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.Y. </LOCATION>, for refueling. Some of the travelers arriving at <LOCATION> LaGuardia </LOCATION> were exasperated but conceded that the weather is beyond even <PERSON> Trump </PERSON>'s control. `` I do n't know how Eastern would have handled it,'' said a young woman traveling on business to Mt. <PERSON> Kisco </PERSON>, <LOCATION> N.Y. </LOCATION> On Tuesday, with good weather, flights were running closer to schedule although still not always exactly on the hour as promised by <PERSON> Trump </PERSON>. The 7:40 a.m. New York-to-Washington run left only five minutes late and arrived 10 minutes early, while the 5 <ORGANIZATION> p.m. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Washington-New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> flight left only a few minutes late and arrived on time at 6 p.m. `` The service was fine; it's like any other airline,'' one young businessman said Wednesday. `` It did n't seem any different to me. It got me here, that's the main thing.'' <PERSON> Trump </PERSON> has promised his shuttle will be a `` diamond'' service, but a number of passengers indicated they cared more about transportation than about <PERSON> Trump </PERSON>'s planned refurbishing of the jets in burgundy and saddle-brown tones with chrome and maple wood veneer accents. On the outside, only four of Trump Shuttle's fleet of 21 <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> 727s have been repainted in the new color scheme: white fuselage with red, black and gold stripes, the word `` Trump'' above the stripes and a red ` T' on the tail. Except for a `` Trump'' hastily painted in red on the rest of the planes, they still sport the familiar Eastern silver and blue. The food is pretty much the same, too. On a recent morning flight the offering was a bagel, a dollop of cream cheese, a few grapes, a strawberry, half-frozen orange juice that had to be eaten with a spoon and coffee served in paper cups. Evening fare consisted of three pieces of barbecued chicken breast, corn-tomato salad and a slice of rye bread in a plastic box, along with free beer, wine and soft drinks. Most of the 1,000 or so Trump employees were formerly with <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION>, and many of them are enthusiastic and visibly happy to be working again after more than three months on the picket line. `` It's a world of difference,'' said first officer <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Bowen </PERSON>, an 18-year Eastern pilot, comparing the two airlines. `` Better working conditions, more flexible management.'' A young woman selling tickets at <LOCATION> LaGuardia </LOCATION>, also a former <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> employee, said, `` <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> Trump </PERSON> is a perfectionist. And now we get our paychecks on time!''
